[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ When I was a kid in the mid-80s, my father bought me the book Sicilian Defence by Garry Kasparov and Alexander Nikitin. While the Russian original was simply called Sicilian Defence, the Serbo-Croatian translation had three more words on the cover: 'My Strongest Weapon.'The book dealt extensively with the Scheveningen variation of the Sicilian. Kasparov used the Scheveningen a lot in the early 80s with great results and even played it in the 1st game of his first World Championship match against Karpov. Even though he drew that game relatively comfortably, he later switched to the Najdorf, not only in the match but also in his later career. But the 'strongest weapon' was not forgotten - in his last tournament, in Linares in 2005, Kasparov admitted that he was planning to play the Scheveningen in what seemed to him a must-win situation in his game against Rustam Kasimdzhanov! Alas, Kasimdzhanov played 1.d4 and we will never get to see what Kasparov had in mind.The Scheveningen is an underrated opening nowadays, mostly because Black is worried about theKeres Attack with 6.g4. While the Keres Attack is undoubtedly the most critical test, it can be dealt with successfully as I will attempt to demonstrate in the corresponding chapters.The Modern Scheveningen, when Black plays without the move a6 @@StartBracket@@as opposed to the Classical Scheveningen where he plays a6@@EndBracket@@ is the subject of this course. The idea is a more direct and central approach by Black. He plans to develop his kingside with Be7, O-O and play in the center with Nc6 in connection with the pawn breaks d5 or e5. The benefit of this approach is two-fold: the play is more concrete as it takes place in the centre, and the risk of a kingside attack is largely decreased. With this approach, Black also achieves active play with excellent counter-chances.I started using the Scheveningen as an extension to my Najdorf repertoire because only a small modification is required to turn the Najdorf into a Scheveningen - instead of 5...a6 Black plays 5...e6. As it turned out, it was one of the best opening-related decisions of my career, considering that I scored heavily with it. I hope that it will serve you even better after you have studied this course.   Happy learning!   GM Alex Colovic }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Keres Attack with 7.h4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen setup that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. g4
{ The Keres Attack is White's most ambitious try against the Scheveningen. Black's last move closed the h3-c8 diagonal for the bishop on c8, so White uses that fact to advance the g-pawn immediately. }
6... h6
{ Practice has shown that this is Black's best reply. Black stops White's threat of g5 and uses the next moves to develop and strike in the centre. }
7. h4
{ The most aggressive attempt. White intends Rg1 and g5 to attack the knight on f6. However, it is curious that modern theory evolved so much that, in spite of the aggressive nature of White's play, his best chances lie in the endgame! }
7... Nc6
{ Black develops in the centre and is just in time to strike with d5 before the knight on f6 is attacked. This move is needed to cover the e5-square, so that after Black's d5 White cannot play e5. }
8. Rg1
{ White removes the rook from h1, so that he can recapture with hxg5 after pushing g5. Note that theline with an immediate 7.g5 is analysed in the next chapter @@StartBracket@@Keres Attack Various 7th Moves@@EndBracket@@.   Against other moves, Black obtains good play immediately, for example,  8.Nxc6?!  bxc6  gives Black a strong centre, @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3pp1/2nppn1p/8/3NP1PP/2N5/PPP2P2/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Nb3  allows again  8...d5  , while @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3pp1/2nppn1p/8/3NP1PP/2N5/PPP2P2/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Be3?!  drops a pawn after  8...Nxd4  9.Bxd4  e5  when the pawn on g4 is attacked twice. }
8... d5
{ Just in time! Black plays in classical fashion, countering White's flank attack with a strike in the centre. Now White has three options: take on d5, play Bb5 or take on c6. The only critical option is the first one. }
9. Bb5
{ Pinning the knight on c6, but the bishop on b5 will be very vulnerable to Nxd4 tactics later on. }
9... Bd7 { Breaking the pin and now threatening to take on e4. } 10. exd5 Nxd5
{ Black takes with the knight, thus avoiding any problems connected with the g5 move, and at the same time he opens the h4-d8 diagonal for the queen, attacking the pawn on h4. }
11. Nxd5 exd5 { Now White has two moves:  12.Qe2  and  12.Be3  . } 12. Qe2+
{ While it looks natural, this check actually helps Black because White's queen on e2 and king on e1 only give Black extra tactical chances. }
12... Be7 13. Nf5
{ With this move White puts immediate pressure, but he is neglecting his development and should be careful after Black's next move . }
13... O-O
{ Finishing development and moving the king out of the centre. Now Black threatens to play Re8, exposing White's king and queen on the e-file. }
14. Bxc6
{ It appears that White wins a piece, but Black has a cute retort. Taking on e7 leads to simplifications after  14.Nxe7+  Nxe7  . }
14... Re8
{ A very nice move to make, introducing the threat of Bb4, so White doesn't have the time to save the extra piece. }
15. Nxe7+ { White seeks refuge in simplifications. } 15... Rxe7 16. Be3 Bxc6
{ Black is comfortably equal here. The threat is to play d4.   Chessable note: You can find thefull variation here. }
