[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen setup that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. g4
{ The Keres Attack is White's most ambitious try against the Scheveningen. Black's last move closed the h3-c8 diagonal for the bishop on c8, so White uses that fact to advance the g-pawn immediately. }
6... h6
{ Practice has shown that this is Black's best reply. Black stops White's threat of g5 and uses the next moves to develop and strike in the centre. }
7. h4
{ The most aggressive attempt. White intends Rg1 and g5 to attack the knight on f6. However, it is curious that modern theory evolved so much that, in spite of the aggressive nature of White's play, his best chances lie in the endgame! }
7... Nc6
{ Black develops in the centre and is just in time to strike with d5 before the knight on f6 is attacked. This move is needed to cover the e5-square, so that after Black's d5 White cannot play e5. }
8. Rg1
{ White removes the rook from h1, so that he can recapture with hxg5 after pushing g5. Note that theline with an immediate 7.g5 is analysed in the next chapter @@StartBracket@@Keres Attack Various 7th Moves@@EndBracket@@.   Against other moves, Black obtains good play immediately, for example,  8.Nxc6?!  bxc6  gives Black a strong centre, @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3pp1/2nppn1p/8/3NP1PP/2N5/PPP2P2/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Nb3  allows again  8...d5  , while @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3pp1/2nppn1p/8/3NP1PP/2N5/PPP2P2/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Be3?!  drops a pawn after  8...Nxd4  9.Bxd4  e5  when the pawn on g4 is attacked twice. }
8... d5
{ Just in time! Black plays in classical fashion, countering White's flank attack with a strike in the centre. Now White has three options: take on d5, play Bb5 or take on c6. The only critical option is the first one. }
9. Bb5
{ Pinning the knight on c6, but the bishop on b5 will be very vulnerable to Nxd4 tactics later on. }
9... Bd7 { Breaking the pin and now threatening to take on e4. } 10. exd5 Nxd5
{ Black takes with the knight, thus avoiding any problems connected with the g5 move, and at the same time he opens the h4-d8 diagonal for the queen, attacking the pawn on h4. }
11. Nxd5 exd5 { Now White has two moves:  12.Qe2  and  12.Be3  . } 12. Be3
{ This is the more critical choice. } 12... Be7
{ Black develops his kingside and is ready to move his king from the centre. Now White has an ample choice where to develop his queen in order to prepare long castle. Taking on h4 is dangeous because after  12...Qxh4?!  13.Qd3  followed by O-O-O White has excellent compensation in view of Black's lag in development. Note that the move @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pp1b1pp1/2n4p/1B1p4/3N2Pq/4B3/PPP2P2/R2QK1R1 w Qkq - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Qe2  transposes tothe line with 12.Qe2+. }
13. Qd2
{ The most natural move, introducing the idea of a piece sacrifice on h6. }
13... O-O
{ Black is not afraid of ghosts. He banks on his finished development and the ability of his pieces to counterattack. It is possible to play for simplifications after  13...Nxd4  , when Black should be fine, but there is no reason why Black should seek simplifications when his chances are quite promising in the middlegame!   Note that taking the pawn on h4 leads to problems after  13...Bxh4?!  14.O-O-O  Bf6  15.Nf5  with strong initiative as in the classical game Karpov-Spassky from Tilburg in 1980. }
14. Nf5
{ White avoids the threat of Nxd4 and places his knight on an active position in the vicinity of Black's king. }
14... d4
{ A very important move that opens the centre. With White's king still on e1 Black seeks to take advantage of the opening of the position. }
15. Bxh6
{ In fact White cannot conveniently take the pawn on d4, so he takes the one on h6. }
15... Bb4 { Black activates his pieces. } 16. c3
{ The only way to avoid the loss of queen. } 16... dxc3
{ Black naturally takes the pawn, opening the centre completely. } 17. bxc3 Ne5
{ With the double threat of Nf3 and Bxb5. The immediate  18...Re8  19.Kf1  Bf8  is also possible. }
18. Be2
{ White covers the f3-square and retreats the bishop back to the defence. }
18... Re8
{ Black continues to activate his pieces. The threat is Nf3. At the same time the f8-square is made available for the bishop in order to cover the g7-pawn. }
19. Kf1 Bf8
{ Black retreats the bishop and defends the g7-pawn. Now with his kingside defended he wants to take the bishop on h6. }
20. Bg5 Qc8
{ Putting pressure on the knight on f5 and the pawn on g4. The position is complex but Black has excellent compensation for the pawn in view of the great activity of his pieces and White's unsafe king. The immediate threat now for Black is to take Bxf5 or Nxg4 followed by Bxf5, regaining the pawn and continuing to play against White's king. }
