{ Practice has shown that this is Black's best reply. Black stops White's threat of g5 and uses the next moves to develop and strike in the centre. }
7. h4
{ The most aggressive attempt. White intends Rg1 and g5 to attack the knight on f6. However, it is curious that modern theory evolved so much that, in spite of the aggressive nature of White's play, his best chances lie in the endgame! }
7... Nc6
{ Black develops in the centre and is just in time to strike with d5 before the knight on f6 is attacked. This move is needed to cover the e5-square, so that after Black's d5 White cannot play e5. }
8. Rg1
{ White removes the rook from h1, so that he can recapture with hxg5 after pushing g5. Note that theline with an immediate 7.g5 is analysed in the next chapter @@StartBracket@@Keres Attack Various 7th Moves@@EndBracket@@.   Against other moves, Black obtains good play immediately, for example,  8.Nxc6?!  bxc6  gives Black a strong centre, @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3pp1/2nppn1p/8/3NP1PP/2N5/PPP2P2/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Nb3  allows again  8...d5  , while @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3pp1/2nppn1p/8/3NP1PP/2N5/PPP2P2/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Be3?!  drops a pawn after  8...Nxd4  9.Bxd4  e5  when the pawn on g4 is attacked twice. }
8... d5
{ Just in time! Black plays in classical fashion, countering White's flank attack with a strike in the centre. Now White has three options: take on d5, play Bb5 or take on c6. The only critical option is the first one. }
9. exd5
{ The immediate  9.g5  is met by  9...hxg5  and after  10.Nxc6  bxc6  11.hxg5  Nxe4  transposes tothe line 9.Nxc6. }
9... Nxd5
{ Taking with the knight opens the h4-d8 diagonal. In many lines, the pawn on h4 hangs and Black happily takes it. }
10. Nxd5 exd5
{ It is entirely possible to take with the queen, although I feel that in those lines White has easier play. }
11. Be3
{ The main move. Pinning the knight on c6 with  11.Bb5  Bd7  leads to thelines analysed after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3pp1/2n1pn1p/3p4/3NP1PP/2N5/PPP2P2/R1BQKBR1 w Qkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Bb5  Bd7  10.exd5  Nxd5  11.Nxd5  exd5  . }
11... Qxh4 { Black takes the pawn and activates the queen. } 12. Qf3
{ This is the most critical move. The alternatives are easier to deal with. }
12... Nxd4
{ Black opens the e-file, which allows for the following queen maneuver that forces the exchange of queens. }
13. Bxd4 Qe7+
{ Black gains a tempo and with his next move centralises the queen on e4. } 14.
Be2 Qe4
{ Seeking the exchange of queens. Black spends a lot of time moving with the queen, but in the endgame he will be a pawn up. }
15. O-O-O { White will have compensation in the endgame. } 15... Qxf3
{ Black exchanges queens. In the endgame his king won't be in trouble if it stays in the centre. }
16. Bxf3 Be6 { Defending the d5-pawn and developing the queenside. } 17. Rge1
Kd7
{ Getting away from the pin on the e-file. Now White has several options at his disposal. In most cases the general scenario is that White manages to regain the pawn but loses the initiative, leading to equality. For the details on how to play the endgame check themain course. For a quick start, it suffices to know that the position is OK for Black. His main ideas are Rc8 @@StartBracket@@to pin the c-pawn in case White plays c4@@EndBracket@@ and f6 @@StartBracket@@to blunt the bishop on d4 and allow for the development of the dark-squared bishop@@EndBracket@@. }
