[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Keres Attack with 7.Be3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen setup that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. g4
{ The Keres Attack is White's most ambitious try against the Scheveningen. Black's last move closed the h3-c8 diagonal for the bishop on c8, so White uses that fact to advance the g-pawn immediately. }
6... h6
{ Practice has shown that this is Black's best reply. Black stops White's threat of g5 and uses the next moves to develop and strike in the centre. }
7. Be3
{ Here we will take a look at what happens if White employs the setup that is characteristic for the English Attack. }
7... Nc6
{ The usual developing move for Black. However, in this position Black has an interesting alternative in the move  7...e5!?  , which you can check in themain course. }
8. f3 { This is the move that characterises the English Attack. } 8... d5
{ As is typical in the Scheveningen, Black is ready to strike early in the centre thanks to the development of both knights on c6 and f6 that control all four central squares e4, d4, e5 and d5. }
9. Bb5
{ The only critical try. Taking on d5 is harmless,  9.exd5  Nxd5  10.Nxd5  Qxd5  with easy play after  11.Nxc6  bxc6  with the idea of Bb7 @@StartBracket@@or  11...Qxc6  with the idea of b6 and Bb7@@EndBracket@@ as Black's bishops can easily come into play. }
9... Bd7 { Breaking the pin and threatening e5. } 10. exd5
{ White couldn't sustain the tension in the centre any longer and is forced to take. }
10... Nxd5
{ The usual recapture for Black, opening the h4-d8 diagonal and removing the knight from f6 where it could have been subject to attack after g5. }
11. Nxd5 exd5
{ This position resembles the one from the chapterKeres Attack with 7.h4 after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3pp1/3ppn1p/8/3NP1P1/2N5/PPP2P1P/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.h4  Nc6  8.Rg1  d5  9.Bb5  Bd7  10.exd5  Nxd5  11.Nxd5  exd5  ,  with the difference that here White has played f3 and Be3 instead of h4 and Rg1. On one hand, this facilitates his queenside development, but on the other, he has fewer chances on the kingside as g5 isn't a threat without the support from the rook and the h-pawn. Black's next moves are Be7 and O-O with a complex middlegame ahead, check themain course for the details of White's options 12.Qe2 and 12.Qd2. }
