[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Keres Attack with 7.Rg1 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen setup that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. g4
{ The Keres Attack is White's most ambitious try against the Scheveningen. Black's last move closed the h3-c8 diagonal for the bishop on c8, so White uses that fact to advance the g-pawn immediately. }
6... h6
{ Practice has shown that this is Black's best reply. Black stops White's threat of g5 and uses the next moves to develop and strike in the centre. }
7. Rg1
{ This move can be a prelude to h4, but White can also postpone his kingside expansion. It is a useful move as sometimes White can push g5 without the help of h4 and the rook on the g-file can become active. }
7... Nc6 { Black develops in the usual way. } 8. Be3
{ The bishop move speeds up the queenside development, White stays flexible and prepares long castle after the queen moves from d1. This setup is one of the more challenging ones for Black. }
8... Be7
{ Black develops the bishop and waits for White to move the queen, so he can take on d4 and win a tempo by pushing e5 @@StartBracket@@he didn't do this immediately as White would take Qxd4 in one go@@EndBracket@@. At the same time he keeps the option to push d5. So against any move Black will now react in one of these two ways: he will either take on d4 and push e5 or he will push d5. Now White has a wide choice. }
9. Qd2
{ White prepares long castling, but the queen left the d1-h5 diagonal and doesn't defend the g4-pawn. This is an additional reason for Black to go for the e5 push after exchanging on d4. }
9... Nxd4 10. Qxd4
{ White is forced to lose time with the queen as  10.Bxd4  e5  drops the pawn on g4. }
10... e5 { A double attack on the queen and the pawn on g4. } 11. Qa4+
{ In case of  11.Qd1  Be6  Black is perfectly fine as White only wasted time with the queen and did nothing as she ended up again on d1. }
11... Bd7 12. Bb5
{ White must play with tempo in order to avoid losing the pawn on g4. } 12...
a6 { Forcing exchanges on d7 that lead to an equal endgame. } 13. Bxd7+ Qxd7
14. Qxd7+ Kxd7
{ Black takes with the king as in the endgame he wants to keep him in the centre. The endgame is equal, Black will centralise the king with Ke6 and try to push d5 and attack White's extended kingside with h5. The details are in the main course.   
Chessable note: You can find the full variations starting fromhere. }
