[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Keres Attack with 7.g5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen setup that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. g4
{ The Keres Attack is White's most ambitious try against the Scheveningen. Black's last move closed the h3-c8 diagonal for the bishop on c8, so White uses that fact to advance the g-pawn immediately. }
6... h6
{ Practice has shown that this is Black's best reply. Black stops White's threat of g5 and uses the next moves to develop and strike in the centre. }
7. g5
{ White opens the g-file immediately and this means that Black won't be able to castle short. }
7... hxg5 8. Bxg5 Nc6
{ Black develops naturally. His intention is to put pressure in the centre with Qb6. }
9. Qd2 { This is the most common move, preparing long castle. } 9... Qb6
{ Attacking both the knight on d4 and the pawn on b2. } 10. Nb3
{ The endgame after  10.O-O-O  Qxd4  11.Qxd4  Nxd4  12.Rxd4  a6  is somewhat better for Black thanks to his better structure. He will continue with Bd7-c6 and will play in the centre and the kingside where White has the isolated h-pawn. }
10... Ne5
{ An important move, immediately targeting the weakened square on f3. } 11. Be2
{ White covers f3. } 11... Bd7
{ Black continues the development and liberates the c8-square for the rook. }
12. O-O-O
{ Sacrificing the pawn on f2. Note that the immediate  12.f4?!  isn't very good in view of  12...Neg4  when the f2 and e3-squares are difficult to defend.  The move  12.h4  is a useful move if White doesn't want to sacrifice on f2, but after  12...Rc8  we have a transposition to the 9.h4 variation. }
12... Rc8
{ A practical choice. It is perfectly possible to take on f2, but the complications after  12...Qxf2  13.Nd4  Rc8  are enormous.  By developing the rook on c8 Black introduces the threat of an exchange sacrifice by taking on c3 as this exposes the e4-pawn. Check themain course for the details of how play can continue. As a quick start knowing the ideas of Rxc3, Nc4 and also Rh3 suffices. }
