{ Practice has shown that this is Black's best reply. Black stops White's threat of g5 and uses the next moves to develop and strike in the centre. }
7. h3
{ The setup with an 'advanced' fianchetto became very popular against the Najdorf and this popularity switched to the Scheveningen as well, especially after the more direct lines with 7.h4 were largely neutralised. Apart from this one, White has several other setups he can try. }
7... Nc6 { The usual developing move for Black in the Scheveningen. } 8. Be3
Be7
{ Black continues with his development. Similar tothe line 7.Rg1 Nc6 8.Be3 Be7 he waits for the development of White's queen in order to take on d4. }
9. Qd2 { The critical continuation. } 9... Nxd4
{ Now White must lose a tempo and move again with either the bishop or the queen. Both moves require serious attention. }
10. Bxd4 a6
{ Preparing the queenside expansion with b5, which will also allow for the development of the bishop on b7.   Again @@StartBracket@@as in theline after 10.Qxd4@@EndBracket@@ the natural move  10...e5  is insufficient because White manages to stabilise his queenside after  11.Be3  Be6  12.O-O-O  Qa5  13.f3  Rc8  14.a3  and the exchange sacrifice on c3 brings little. }
11. O-O-O b5
{ The natural continuation. Now White has two principled plans: to play more actively with f4 or to strengthen the e4-pawn by f3 and prepare h4 and g5. }
12. f4
{ This gives Black more counterplay in view of the vulnerability of the e4-pawn. }
12... Bb7 { Continuing development and attacking the e4-pawn. } 13. Bg2 b4
{ Harassing the knight on c3 and indirectly fighting for the centre. } 14. Ne2
{ In case of  14.Na4  Qa5  15.b3  O-O  the knight on a5 can become problematic after Nd7 and Bc6. }
14... Qa5
{ The pawn on e4 can be taken, but this leads to a mess after  14...Bxe4  15.Bxf6  Bxg2  16.Bxg7  Rg8  17.Rh2  Bd5  .  The queen move is a multi-purpose move: the queen attacks the pawn on a2 but also supports e5. Black's activity on the queenside gives Black good counterplay.   Chessable note: You can find thefull variation here. }
