[Black "Classical Variation - 6.Be2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen setup that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. Be2
{ This classical development is always a solid option for White in the Open Sicilian. When choosing this line White usually seeks more positional play, but there are also more aggressive plans. }
6... Nc6 { Black develops his knights before the bishops. } 7. O-O
{ The most common move, fully in line with the development with Be2, which seeks calmer play. }
7... Be7 { Black continues development and will castle next. } 8. Be3
{ The usual development of the dark-squared bishop. White can also try a couple of other ideas. }
8... O-O { Black finishes the development of the kingside. } 9. f4
{ White expands in the centre and the kingside. } 9... e5
{ The key move of the Modern Scheveningen. It was the discovery of this move that gave the Scheveningen a modern twist. Black moves the e-pawn again but forces favourable changes in the centre. }
10. Nb3 { The most commonly played move. } 10... exf4
{ By exchanging the pawns Black obtains the e5-square for his knight. } 11.
Rxf4 Ne8
{ This is an instructive move to remember. There is nothing wrong with the natural  11...Be6  , intending d5, but the knight move contains the positional idea of the activation of the dark-squared bishop. The idea is two-fold: either to play Bg5 and exchange the bishops or to play Bf6-e5. The move works well in this position because of the somewhat awkward placement of the rook on f4 and the bishop on e3.  Chessable note: You can find thefull variation here. }
