[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Classical Variation - 6.Be2 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen setup that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. Be2
{ This classical development is always a solid option for White in the Open Sicilian. When choosing this line White usually seeks more positional play, but there are also more aggressive plans. }
6... Nc6 { Black develops his knights before the bishops. } 7. Be3
{ With this move order we will explore some more aggressive plans for White in which he aims to castle long and/or push his kingside pawns. }
7... Be7 { Black continues along the usual lines. } 8. f4 O-O
{ Black finishes development and on the next move will strike in the centre. }
9. Qd2
{ Preparing long castle. The alternatives @@StartBracket@@except  9.O-O  , which would lead to a transposition to thelines after 7.O-O@@EndBracket@@ are harmless and can even land White in trouble. }
9... e5 { The typical central thrust works well here. } 10. Nb3
{ The natural retreat, but this motivates Black's next move. } 10... a5
{ Black immediately threatens to harass the knight on b3. } 11. a4
{ White cannot really allow a4 as the knight has no good squares to go to. }
11... Nb4
{ Landing on the weakened b4-square. After White's last move the knight cannot be chased away with a3 while c3 is impossible to organise. Black has a sharp alternative in  11...Be6  , check themain course for the details. }
12. O-O-O { The sharper choice. } 12... Qc7
{ The queen is developed on the c-file where White's king is. From c7 she can also come to c6, attacking the pawns on e4 and a4. }
13. Kb1 { Removing the king from the sensitive c-file. } 13... Be6
{ Black is fully developed now, with the rooks connected, and doesn't fear White's possible advance with f5. }
14. f5 Nxe4
{ A great resource that gives Black very strong initiative. Here  14...Bxb3?  is bad as after  15.cxb3  Black cannot follow it up with the opening of the game with d5 and White can consolidate his light-square dominance with Rc1 and Bc4. }
15. Nxe4 Bxf5
{ But now it is Black who is attacking on the light squares. The immediate threat is d5, hitting the vulnerable pawn on c2.  See themain course for the details, for a quick start it is enough to arrive at this position armed with the ideas of d5 and Qd7 @@StartBracket@@defending the bishop on f5 and attacking the pawn on a4@@EndBracket@@. }
