[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "English Attack - 6.Be3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen setup that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. Be3 Be7
{ It is important for Black to start with this move because of a possible transposition to theline with 6.f4 where Black needs to be able to castle quickly. }
7. g4 { This is another aggressive option. } 7... d5
{ Black reacts in the classical manner - he strikes in the centre to deal with an attack on the flank. }
8. Bb5+ Nbd7
{ Covering the check with a knight leaves the bishop on b5 somewhat loose as White doesn't really want to take on d7. }
9. exd5 Nxd5
{ Black captures with the knight as it frees his play. Now the h4-d8 diagonal is open and after castling the bishop or the knight can come to f6. }
10. Nxd5 exd5 11. Qf3
{ The critical move, preparing castling long and attacking the pawn on d5. Against other queen moves Black castles and then plays a6 or Ne5 with good game, for example  11.Qd2  O-O  12.O-O-O  Ne5  13.h3  a6  14.Bf1  Nc4  with good play after  15.Bxc4  dxc4  with the bishop pair compensating for White's central presence. }
11... O-O
{ Black sacrifices the central pawn for active piece play. In fact, thanks to that activity he will soon regain it. }
12. Qxd5 Qa5+
{ Black removes the queen from d8 with tempo and now threatens Nf6, attacking the queen on d5 and the pawn on g4. }
13. c3
{ In case of  13.Bd2  Qc7  followed by Nf6 Black regains the pawn and still has free play. }
13... Nf6
{ This leads to a messy middlegame. If Black prefers a messy endgame, the alternative  13...a6  is a good one. After  14.Bc4  Qxd5  15.Bxd5  Nf6  16.Bg2  Nxg4  17.Bf4  Bf6  the endgame is balanced but still rather sharp. }
14. Qe5 a6 { Attacking the pinned bishop on b5. } 15. Qxe7 axb5
{ Play is very sharp here, the unsafe position of White's king guarantees Black good compensation. White is risking a lot by entering this position.   Chessable note: You can find thefull variation here. }
