[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "English Attack - 6.Be3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen setup that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. Be3 Be7
{ It is important for Black to start with this move because of a possible transposition to theline with 6.f4 where Black needs to be able to castle quickly. }
7. f3
{ This is the move that characterises the English Attack. The idea is very simple - White strengthens the pawn on e4 and plans to play Qd2, castle long and then start a kingside attack with g4-g5, h4-h5 etc. }
7... Nc6 { Castling is also possible, see the differences in themain course. }
8. Qd2
{ Playing  8.g4?!  is premature in view of  8...Nd7!  , threatening Bh4. } 8...
O-O
{ Black moves the king from the centre and is ready to play in the centre. Now White needs to decide whether to follow suit or to start immediate kingside action. }
9. g4 { White starts immediate kingside action, threatening g5. } 9... d5
{ Black counters in the centre, following the principle that an attack on the wing should be met by a counterstrike in the centre. }
10. g5
{ White indirectly fights for the centre by attacking the knight on f6 that puts pressure on it. }
10... Nh5
{ This is slightly more precise than  10...Nxd4  . While in most cases the lines transpose, White does have one unpleasant option after  11.Qxd4  Nh5  12.Rg1!?  . }
11. O-O-O { The most common move for White. } 11... Nxd4
{ Now White drops the pawn on g5 but will take on d5. } 12. Qxd4
{ This is more critical than  12.Bxd4  Bxg5  , which is fine for Black. } 12...
Bxg5 13. Kb1 { This move is the critical test. } 13... g6
{ This extremely rare move seems to be the best when it comes to keeping a balance between complexity and safety. Black has two good alternatives here. The simplest one is  13...Bxe3  while the most complex one is  13...Kh8  , when White has many options but Black is holding his own. Check themain course for the details. }
14. Be2 { With this move White keeps the tension in the centre. } 14... Bd7
{ Black cannot take on e4 in view of  14...dxe4?  15.Qc5!  when he suffers from the lag in development, so he makes sure he finishes his development before clarifying the position in the centre. Now the idea is to play Bc6. }
15. exd5 { Sooner rather than later White must regain the pawn. } 15... exd5
{ Black naturally recaptures. } 16. Qxd5
{ In case of  16.Nxd5  Bxe3  17.Nxe3  Be6  Black has no problems, while after @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp1b1p1p/6p1/3p2bn/3Q4/2N1BP2/PPP1B2P/1K1R3R w - - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16.Bxg5  Qxg5  17.Nxd5  Be6  18.Bc4  Bxd5  we have a transposition to theline 14.exd5 when both sides have wasted a tempo: White by playing Be2 before Bc4 and Black by playing Bd7 before Be6. }
16... Bxe3 { Both Black's bishops were hanging, so Black had to take on e3. }
17. Qxd7 Qc8
{ A nice move - defending the pawn on b7 and not allowing a rook on the 7th rank after the exchange of queens. Now Black wants to continue with Nf6, chasing away the queen from d7, or Nf4, placing the knight on a dominant square. Black has a pleasant position, always with the long-term advantage of the better pawn structure. }
