Bxg5 13. Kb1 { This move is the critical test. } 13... g6
{ This extremely rare move seems to be the best when it comes to keeping a balance between complexity and safety. Black has two good alternatives here. The simplest one is  13...Bxe3  while the most complex one is  13...Kh8  , when White has many options but Black is holding his own. Check themain course for the details. }
14. Rg1 { Hitting the bishop on g5. } 14... Bf6
{ With this move Black seeks complexity as he intends to keep the extra pawn. There is a simpler solution here in  14...Bxe3  15.Qxe3  Bd7!  , finishing development. The line is analysed in more detail in themain course. }
15. e5
{ White naturally gains space. In case of  15.Qd3  Qa5  Black threatens to take on c3 and wreck White's queenside structure. }
15... Bg7
{ The fianchettoed bishop will exert pressure on the e5-pawn after Black's next move. }
16. f4 f6
{ Undermining White's centre and intending to open the f-file, when the rook will be able to come to f5 and attack the pawn on e5. An additional idea for Black to attack the pawn on e5 is the move Qc7. The ensuing middlegame is complex, but Black is a pawn up with a clear plan and a solid position, so he can look forward with optimism, as you can check themain course for possible developments. }
