[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "English Attack - 6.Be3 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen setup that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. Be3 Be7
{ It is important for Black to start with this move because of a possible transposition to theline with 6.f4 where Black needs to be able to castle quickly. }
7. f3
{ This is the move that characterises the English Attack. The idea is very simple - White strengthens the pawn on e4 and plans to play Qd2, castle long and then start a kingside attack with g4-g5, h4-h5 etc. }
7... Nc6 { Castling is also possible, see the differences in themain course. }
8. Qd2
{ Playing  8.g4?!  is premature in view of  8...Nd7!  , threatening Bh4. } 8...
O-O
{ Black moves the king from the centre and is ready to play in the centre. Now White needs to decide whether to follow suit or to start immediate kingside action. }
9. O-O-O d5 { Before White starts to push g4-g5 Black strikes in the centre. }
10. Qe1
{ The queen moves away from the d-file as White hopes to take advantage of the opposition of his rook and the black queen. }
10... e5
{ After White's last move there is no pressure on d5 so Black can expand in the centre. }
11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. exd5 cxd5
{ Black is actually spoilt for choice here. By taking with the pawn he is willing to sacrifice material for initiative and attack. He can also opt for the calmer alternative  12...Nxd5  , leading to a positional battle, for example,  13.Bc4  Be6  with a pleasant position for Black who will likely play Qc7 and then his ideas include a5, f5 followed by Bf6, putting the rooks in the centre or on the b-file. }
13. Bg5 { Putting maximum pressure on Black's centre. } 13... Be6
{ Developing the bishop and defending the pawn on d5. Black sacrifices the pawn on e5 in order to develop an attack on the white king. }
14. Qxe5 Qa5
{ Activating the queen and intending Rab8 when the threat of a sacrifice on b2 can become a very dangerous one. }
15. Nxd5
{ This is critical, taking a second pawn. Against other moves, Black plays Rab8 when an immediate tactical opportunity to take on b2 might arise or he will continue with Rfc8, Qb6, putting more pressure on White's queenside. }
15... Nxd5 { The natural response. } 16. Bxe7
{ White makes use of the pin along the 5th rank to regain the piece. } 16...
Rfc8
{ The rook is active on the c-file, while the other one can come to the b-file. Black now threatens to take on a2 or on c2, with the tactical idea of  17.--  Rxc2  18.Kxc2  Nb4+  , winning the undefended queen on e5. Black has fantastic compensation as he has a strong attack against White's king.  Chessable note: You can find thefull variation here. }
