[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "English Attack - 6.Be3 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen setup that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. Be3 Be7
{ It is important for Black to start with this move because of a possible transposition to theline with 6.f4 where Black needs to be able to castle quickly. }
7. f3
{ This is the move that characterises the English Attack. The idea is very simple - White strengthens the pawn on e4 and plans to play Qd2, castle long and then start a kingside attack with g4-g5, h4-h5 etc. }
7... Nc6 { Castling is also possible, see the differences in themain course. }
8. Qd2
{ Playing  8.g4?!  is premature in view of  8...Nd7!  , threatening Bh4. } 8...
O-O
{ Black moves the king from the centre and is ready to play in the centre. Now White needs to decide whether to follow suit or to start immediate kingside action. }
9. O-O-O d5 { Before White starts to push g4-g5 Black strikes in the centre. }
10. Be2
{ This calm move, simply developing the bishop when there is so much going on, is the trickiest one for Black to meet. }
10... Re8
{ A very deep and surreptitious move that prepares for the opening of the e-file after an exchange on d5, eyeing the bishops on e2 and e3. To understand why Black needs to prepare instead of playing in the centre and to see the strength of White's 10th move we can take a look at the endgame after  10...dxe4?!  11.Nxc6  bxc6  12.Qxd8  Rxd8  13.Rxd8  Bxd8  14.Rd1!  @@StartBracket@@taking the d-file with tempo, thanks to the fact that the bishop is hanging@@EndBracket@@  14...Be7  15.Nxe4  Nxe4  16.fxe4  e5  17.Bc4  with a favourable endgame as in the game So-Duda played online in 2018.   Black's other direct attempt  10...Nxd4?!  also doesn't work in view of  11.Bxd4  dxe4  12.fxe4  when again the bishop on e2 is useful as the white rook can come to f1 while White already threatens e5. Having seen the problems with direct play we now understand that Black needs to be more patient - hence the rook move. }
11. g4
{ A natural attempt in the spirit of the English Attack, but now Black can take advantage of this weakening by transposing to an ending after taking on e4. }
11... dxe4
{ This didn't work so well immediately on move 10, but here it does because White's extra move g4 is in fact weakening once the f3-pawn is forced to move to e4. }
12. Nxc6 Qxd2+
{ Since Black will lose the fight for the d-file even in case of  12...bxc6  13.Qxd8  Rxd8  13.Rxd8  Bxd8  14.Rd1  @@StartBracket@@thanks to the bishop being on e2 White can occupy the d-file@@EndBracket@@, he takes on d2 instead and keeps the rook on e8, covering the 8th rank as in some lines the bishop on e7 can move without the need to guard the d8-square. }
13. Rxd2 bxc6 14. Nxe4
{ In case of  14.fxe4  Bb4!  @@StartBracket@@here we see the bishop free to move without the need to guard against a mate on d8@@EndBracket@@  followed by e5, attacking the pawn on g4  @@StartBracket@@here we see why the extra move g4 is in fact weakening for White@@EndBracket@@ Black is very comfortable. }
14... Nxe4 15. fxe4 e5
{ Opening the h3-c8 diagonal for the light-squared bishop and fixing the pawn on e4. The pawn on g4 limits White's play as either the bishop needs to stay on e2 to defend it, or after h3 or g5 it will give Black a target for counterplay, for example with h5 against the former or f6 against the latter. Black will now develop with Be6 and will likely play a5-a4 to try to fix White's queenside and remove the a-pawn from the attacked square on a7. He will also challenge the d-file with Red8 and bring the king to the centre. }
