8. Qd2
{ Playing  8.g4?!  is premature in view of  8...Nd7!  , threatening Bh4. } 8...
O-O
{ Black moves the king from the centre and is ready to play in the centre. Now White needs to decide whether to follow suit or to start immediate kingside action. }
9. O-O-O d5 { Before White starts to push g4-g5 Black strikes in the centre. }
10. Be2
{ This calm move, simply developing the bishop when there is so much going on, is the trickiest one for Black to meet. }
10... Re8
{ A very deep and surreptitious move that prepares for the opening of the e-file after an exchange on d5, eyeing the bishops on e2 and e3. To understand why Black needs to prepare instead of playing in the centre and to see the strength of White's 10th move we can take a look at the endgame after  10...dxe4?!  11.Nxc6  bxc6  12.Qxd8  Rxd8  13.Rxd8  Bxd8  14.Rd1!  @@StartBracket@@taking the d-file with tempo, thanks to the fact that the bishop is hanging@@EndBracket@@  14...Be7  15.Nxe4  Nxe4  16.fxe4  e5  17.Bc4  with a favourable endgame as in the game So-Duda played online in 2018.   Black's other direct attempt  10...Nxd4?!  also doesn't work in view of  11.Bxd4  dxe4  12.fxe4  when again the bishop on e2 is useful as the white rook can come to f1 while White already threatens e5. Having seen the problems with direct play we now understand that Black needs to be more patient - hence the rook move. }
11. Kb1
{ Note that the capture on d5 after  11.exd5  Nxd5  12.Nxd5  Qxd5  13.Nxc6  Qxc6  14.Bd3  Rd8  leads to atransposition to the line @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2bppp/2n1pn2/3p4/3NP3/2N1BP2/PPPQ2PP/2KR1B1R w - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.exd5  Nxd5  11.Nxd5  Qxd5  12.Nxc6  Qxc6  13.Bd3  Rd8  where both sides have lost a tempo: White on Be2-d3 and Black on Re8-d8. }
11... Bb4
{ Similar to theline with 11.h4 Black pins the knight on c3 and threatens e5. Black also has an interesting alternative in the move  11...Bd7!?  . The point of the move is to block the d-file so now Black can take on e4 without fear of an inferior endgame. For example after moves like  12.g4  ,  12.h4  and  12.Nb3  Black can safely take on e4 with a good game. }
12. Bg5 { A counterpin by White. } 12... Nxd4
{ Black is aiming for the e5 push and sets a small trap along the way. } 13.
Qxd4 Bxc3
{ The bishop was hanging and this exchange forces White to wreck his queenside structure. }
14. bxc3 { The trap consisted in  14.Qxc3?!  Nxe4!  when Black wins a pawn. }
14... e5
{ Achieving the central push. Black now sacrifices the d5-pawn but obtains good long-term compensation in view of the weak white king. }
15. Bxf6
{ Or  15.Qe3  h6  16.Bxf6  Qxf6  17.exd5  Bd7  followed by Rac8, Qd6, Rc5 with great play on the dark squares. }
15... Qxf6 16. Qa4
{ Taking on d5 is bad, as  16.Qxd5?!  Be6  followed by Rec8 gives Black tremendous play on the c-file. }
16... Re6 { The rook is very active on the 6th rank. } 17. exd5
{ In case of  17.Rxd5  Rb6  White has to repeat with  18.Rb5  Rd6  because moving the king with @@StartFEN@@r1b3k1/pp3ppp/1r3q2/3Rp3/Q3P3/2P2P2/P1P1B1PP/1K5R w - - 1 18@@EndFEN@@  18.Ka1  allows  18...Be6  with play on the  c-file after Rc6 and Rac8  . }
17... Rb6+ { Moving away with tempo. } 18. Ka1 Bf5
{ The bishop is very active on f5, pinning down the white queen to the defence of the c2-pawn. Black has excellent compensation here. His ideas also include playing on the kingside with Qg5 or Qg6, hitting the pawn on g2, and also the d2-square in case the rook occupies it. }
