[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Sozin Attack - 6.Bc4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen setup that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. Bc4
{ The Sozin Attack is a universal weapon against many Sicilians. However, against the Scheveningen it is less optimal as with the black pawn already on e6 Black can play for quick development, save on the move a6 @@StartBracket@@when we can have a transposition to the Najdorf@@EndBracket@@ and aim for fast counterplay. }
6... Be7
{ A few words about the move-order: against the Sozin Black intends to use the absence of the pawn on a6 in order to use that square for the knight's route to c5, namely Na6-c5. That is why he first develops the kingside and then embarks on the knight maneuver. This is different from the usual lines when Black develops the knight to c6. }
7. Bb3 { White usually drops the bishop back to b3 automatically. } 7... O-O
{ Black finishes development of the kingside and will now start the knight transfer to c5. }
8. f4
{ White generally has two plans: to castle long or short. With both these plans White plays the moves f4, Be3 and Qf3. }
8... Na6 { Going to c5 next. } 9. Qf3 Nc5 10. Be3 a5
{ Again a transposition to the Najdorf with 10... a6 is possible, as the theoretical verdict on those positions is that Black has no problems, but the Scheveningen option to push the a-pawn for two squares is an extra bonus here that Black can gladly take! The threat is a4-a3, to harass the bishop on b3 and to weaken White's queenside. }
11. O-O-O
{ The sharpest try, as after a4-a3 White's queenside will be weakened. } 11...
a4 12. Bc4 a3
{ A natural advance of the a-pawn that weakens the dark squares around White's king. }
13. b3
{ White shouldn't allow axb2, which would completely destroy White's queenside shelter. }
13... Nfxe4
{ This trick works again, only this time it's much more complicated than in theline with 11.O-O: here White has a rook on the d-file and this makes a considerable difference, as we shall shortly see. Black has an alternative in  13...Qa5  , but that one allows White to force a repetition if he wishes to after  14.Bd2  Qb6  15.Be3  Qa5  . }
14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Qxe4 d5 { Black regains the piece thanks to this fork. } 16.
Qf3
{ White keeps the d-file open for the rook. After  16.Bxd5?!  exd5  17.Qd3  Bf6  with Re8 next Black is simply better. White's king is weak and so are the light squares in White's camp, the e4-square in particular. }
16... dxc4 17. Nxe6
{ This is White's best chance. The rook on d1 makes the difference. } 17...
Bxe6 { A fine positional queen sacrifice! } 18. Rxd8 Rfxd8
{ This curious position is much more dangerous for White than it may look at first sight. For example, now he has only one move @@StartBracket@@  19.b4  @@EndBracket@@ in order not to be worse. Check themain course for the details and the dangers White faces. }
