[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Fianchetto Line - 6.g3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen setup that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. g3
{ The fianchetto is always a decent option for White in the Open Sicilian. White wants to play Bg2, castle short and then decide whether to play on the kingside by expanding with g4, f4 etc. or to play on the queenside with either Nxc6 followed by Be3, Na4 and c4, or with Nb3, Be3, a4-a5. }
6... Nc6
{ Black should be precise with this and the next move as after Bg2 the long diagonal becomes sensitive. For example  6...Be7  already means that after  7.Bg2  the move  7...Nc6?!  is not very good in view of  8.Nxc6  bxc6  9.e5  when White manages to inflict structural damage. }
7. Bg2
{ White already threatens to use the strength of the fianchettoed bishop by taking on c6 and pushing e5, attacking the pawn on c6. }
7... Bd7
{ A very important move. Black must defend against White's threat of Nxc6 and e5. Now in case of  8.Nxc6  he can safely recapture with  8...Bxc6  . }
8. O-O
{ White finishes development of the kingside and is ready for the middlegame. }
8... Be7
{ Black also continues developing and is ready to castle short. Now White has a wide choice of continuations and plans. }
9. h3 { This move is played with the idea to continue with g4. } 9... O-O
{ Black is now fully developed. } 10. Nde2
{ Avoiding an exchange on d4, which would ease Black's play. To illustrate, in case of  10.g4  Nxd4  11.Qxd4  Bc6  Black is perfectly fine as he exchanged one pair of knights,  liberating the c6-square for the light-squared bishop in the process, and can continue with his queenside play of b5, possibly a5 and b4. This exchange on d4 followed by Bc6 is typical for many lines in the Scheveningen. }
10... Rc8
{ Removing the rook from the long diagonal and activating it on the c-file. }
11. g4 h6
{ A typical move in the Fianchetto Line: Black stops g5 and is not worried about the weakening of his kingside because his own queenside counterplay comes faster than White's preparation to push through g5 with the help of f4 or h4. }
12. Ng3
{ White continues regrouping.  The knight on g3 lends more support to the e4-pawn and can be included in the kingside activities.   In case of  12.f4  b5!  Black's counterplay is fast as White cannot take the pawn on b5 in view of the double attack  13.Nxb5?  Qb6  14.Nbd4  e5  . }
12... Ne5
{ The knight is heading to c4, from where it will control the e3-square @@StartBracket@@making the development of White's dark-squared bishop more difficult@@EndBracket@@ and pressurise White's queenside, particularly the pawn on b2. }
13. f4 Nc4 { Threatening Qb6 followed by Ne3. } 14. Kh1
{ Removing the king from the sensitive g1-a7 diagonal. } 14... b5
{ Black is moving forward with his queenside activity and has great play. All of these moves have been played in my game against GM Kevin Spraggett from the San Sebastian tournament in 2011. I got an advantage with Black and after some adventures, the game ended in a draw. }
