[Black "Fianchetto Line - 6.g3 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen setup that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. g3
{ The fianchetto is always a decent option for White in the Open Sicilian. White wants to play Bg2, castle short and then decide whether to play on the kingside by expanding with g4, f4 etc. or to play on the queenside with either Nxc6 followed by Be3, Na4 and c4, or with Nb3, Be3, a4-a5. }
6... Nc6
{ Black should be precise with this and the next move as after Bg2 the long diagonal becomes sensitive. For example  6...Be7  already means that after  7.Bg2  the move  7...Nc6?!  is not very good in view of  8.Nxc6  bxc6  9.e5  when White manages to inflict structural damage. }
7. Bg2
{ White already threatens to use the strength of the fianchettoed bishop by taking on c6 and pushing e5, attacking the pawn on c6. }
7... Bd7
{ A very important move. Black must defend against White's threat of Nxc6 and e5. Now in case of  8.Nxc6  he can safely recapture with  8...Bxc6  . }
8. O-O
{ White finishes development of the kingside and is ready for the middlegame. }
8... Be7
{ Black also continues developing and is ready to castle short. Now White has a wide choice of continuations and plans. }
9. Nb3
{ This avoids the typical exchange on d4. Note that the move  9.Re1  would likely transpose, for example after  9...O-O  10.a4  we have a transposition to the line starting with  9.a4  . }
9... O-O 10. Kh1
{ Removing the king from the g1-a7 diagonal and preparing f4 and g4-g5. The immediate  10.f4?!  is met by  10...b5!  as the pawn cannot be taken in view of  11.Nxb5?  Qb6  ,  winning the knight on b5. }
10... a6
{ Starting immediate queenside action. There are alternatives of course,  10...Rc8  or  10...Ne5  , but in this particular case it's important to start queenside action as soon as possible. }
11. f4 b5 { Threatening b4. } 12. a3 Rc8
{ The usual spot for the rook, outside of the scope of the fianchettoed bishop. }
13. g4
{ White expands on the kingside and threatens g5. Against other moves like  13.Be3  or  13.Qe2  Black continues with  13...b4  , check themain course for those lines. }
13... Ne8
{ Introduction to a very interesting idea. The alternative is  13...h6  14.Be3  Nh7  , stopping White's kingside advance. }
14. Be3
{ In case of  14.g5  e5!  Black starts attacking White's exposed kingside pawns. }
14... g5
{ The positional idea I wanted to demonstrate. Black is fighting for the dark squares, especially the e5-square. A perfectly valid alternative is  14...Bf6  threatening Bxc3 and Na5. }
15. e5
{ An ambitious attempt not to allow Black control the dark squares, which would happen in case of  15.f5  h6  @@StartBracket@@solidifying the pawn on g5 and intending further Ne5, Nf6@@EndBracket@@ or after @@StartFEN@@2rqnrk1/3bbp1p/p1npp3/1p4p1/4PPP1/PNN1B3/1PP3BP/R2Q1R1K w - - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15.Nd2  gxf4  16.Bxf4  Ne5  . }
15... gxf4
{ Forcing White to take on d6. However the exchanges will be in Black's favour. }
16. exd6 fxe3 17. dxe7 Nxe7
{ Black would like to continue with Bc6, exchanging the defender of White's king. Black strives for an endgame here as in that case he can use his mobile central majority, while in the middlegame he can try the sharp plan of Kh8 and f5, opening the g-file and exposing White's king. }
