[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "White Plays 6.f4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen setup that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. f4
{ Usually, after 6.f4 White aims to establish a so-called 3rd rank set-up with Be3, Bd3, Qf3 and then either O-O or O-O-O. }
6... Be7
{ An important move! Usually Black plays Nc6, but against the line with 6.f4 it is important to castle as soon as possible. In the line  6...Nc6  7.Be3  Be7  8.Qf3  e5  9.Nxc6  bxc6  10.f5  White seems to have the upper hand even though the lines are quite complicated. }
7. Nf3
{ Removing the knight to f3 is a clear sign that White wants to play Bd3, O-O and then either Qe1-g3 or Qe2 and e5. }
7... Nc6
{ Black doesn't hurry with castling in order to have the option to play Nb4, to harass the bishop on d3. }
8. Bd3
{ If White starts with  8.a3  then after  8...O-O  9.Bd3  Qb6  makes it tricky for White to castle. Then  10.Qe2  is met by  10...e5  with easy play for Black. }
8... Nb4
{ Going after the light-squared bishop. Another thing to know here is that Black will postpone castling to speed up his queenside play after Nxd3 with b5, Qb6, a5 etc.  
Chessable note: You can find thefull variations here. }
