{ The Scheveningen setup that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. Bg5
{ The move  6.Bg5  is the most common of White's rare 6th moves, popular with players who play the same move against the Najdorf. }
6... h6
{ Black wants to clarify what the bishop intends to do. The move  6...a6  is a transposition to the Najdorf and the move  6...Nc6  is a transposition to the Rauzer Attack in the Classical Sicilian. }
7. Bh4
{ The retreat  7.Be3  makes little sense, as White gives Black a clear tempo @@StartBracket@@h6@@EndBracket@@ in the English Attack. The exchange on f6 is also not very threatening, after  7.Bxf6  Qxf6  Black has the bishop pair very early in the game. He will retreat the queen back to d8 in order to remove it from possible attacks with g4-g5 and will continue with Be7, a6, b5, Bb7 etc. }
7... Nc6
{ The more complex move. The alternative  7...Be7  is just as good, with the idea to continue with a6 and b5 in Najdorf-style. }
8. Qd3 { With the idea to castle long. } 8... Be7
{ Black continues in Scheveningen style, aiming to meet White's f4 with e5. }
9. O-O-O O-O 10. f4 e5 { The typical Modern Scheveningen reaction. } 11. Nxc6
bxc6 12. f5
{ The endgame after  12.fxe5  dxe5  13.Qxd8  Rxd8  14.Rxd8  Bxd8  15.Bc4  Kf8  is quite alright for Black, the weaknesses of the pawns on c6 and e4 compensate each other. }
12... d5 { A very promising pawn sacrifice. } 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. exd5 Qb6
{ The key move, introducing threats on the long diagonal and the b-file, both converging on the b2-square.  Chessable note: You can find thefull variation here. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Keres Attack with 7.h4"]
[Black "Keres Attack 7.h4 - 9.Nxc6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. g4
{ The Keres Attack is White's most ambitious try against the Scheveningen. Black's last move closed the h3-c8 diagonal for the bishop on c8, so White uses that fact to advance the g-pawn immediately. }
6... h6
{ Practice has shown that this is Black's best reply. Black stops White's threat of g5 and uses the next moves to develop and strike in the centre. }
7. h4
{ The most aggressive attempt. White intends Rg1 and g5 to attack the knight on f6. However, it is curious that modern theory evolved so much that, in spite of the aggressive nature of White's play, his best chances lie in the endgame! }
7... Nc6
{ Black develops in the centre and is just in time to strike with d5 before the knight on f6 is attacked. This move is needed to cover the e5-square, so that after ...d5 White cannot play e5. }
8. Rg1
{ White removes the rook from h1, so that he can recapture with hxg5 after pushing g5. Note that theline with an immediate 7.g5 is analysed in the next chapter @@StartBracket@@Keres Attack Various@@EndBracket@@.   Against other moves, Black obtains good play immediately, for example,  8.Nxc6?!  bxc6  gives Black a strong centre, @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3pp1/2nppn1p/8/3NP1PP/2N5/PPP2P2/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Nb3  allows again  8...d5  , while @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3pp1/2nppn1p/8/3NP1PP/2N5/PPP2P2/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Be3?!  drops a pawn after  8...Nxd4  9.Bxd4  e5  when the pawn on g4 is attacked twice. }
8... d5
{ Just in time! Black plays in classical fashion, countering White's flank attack with a strike in the centre. Now White has three options: take on d5, play Bb5 or take on c6. The only critical option is the first one. }
9. Nxc6 { This exchange is harmless as it leads to an equal endgame. } 9...
bxc6 10. g5 hxg5 11. hxg5
{ Note that taking with the bishop is bad, as after  11.Bxg5?!  Qb6  White has problems defending the pawn on b2 and the pawn e4. }
11... Nxe4
{ Black takes a pawn and White will have to spend some time to regain it. } 12.
Nxe4 dxe4 13. Qxd8+
{ If White avoids the exchange with  13.Qg4  then Black has the nice maneuver  13...Qa5  14.c3  Qf5  , offering the exchange again. }
13... Kxd8
{ The endgame is problem-free for Black. He is still a pawn up and his pieces can easily enter the game. }
14. Rg4 { This is another way to attack the pawn. } 14... f5
{ This is the simplest. } 15. gxf6 gxf6 16. Rxe4 e5
{ With easy play for Black who can continue with Bf5 or Be6-d5, Kc7 etc. } *

