{ Just in time! Black plays in classical fashion, countering White's flank attack with a strike in the centre. Now White has three options: take on d5, play Bb5 or take on c6. The only critical option is the first one. }
9. Bb5
{ Pinning the knight on c6, but the bishop on b5 will be very vulnerable to tactics with Nxd4 later on. }
9... Bd7 { Breaking the pin and now threatening to take on e4. } 10. exd5 Nxd5
{ Black takes with the knight, thus avoiding any problems connected with the g5 move, and at the same time he opens the h4-d8 diagonal for the queen, attacking the pawn on h4. }
11. Nxd5 exd5 { Now White has two moves:  12.Qe2  and  12.Be3  . } 12. Qe2+
{ While it looks natural, this check actually helps Black because White's queen on e2 and king on e1 only give Black extra tactical chances. }
12... Be7 13. Nf5
{ With this move White puts immediate pressure, but he is neglecting his development and should be careful after Black's next move . }
13... O-O
{ Finishing development and moving the king out of the centre. Now Black threatens to play Re8, exposing White's king and queen on the e-file. }
14. Nxe7+ { This leads to simplifications. } 14... Nxe7 15. Bxd7 Qxd7
{ But these favour Black who is ahead in development. Now White has problems with his king stuck in the centre. For example: }
16. Bd2
{ In case of  16.Be3  d4  17.O-O-O  Qe6  Black gladly exchanges the d4-pawn for the one on a2 as this will weaken White's king. }
16... Qa4 { Preventing castling by latching onto the a2-pawn. } 17. b3 Qd4
{ Forcing further weakening of White's queenside. } 18. c3 Qc5
{ Placing the queen on the c-file where White's king will be after the long castle. }
19. O-O-O d4
{ With initiative against White's weakened king. Black will continue with Nd5, Rac8 when it's clear that White is on the defensive. }
