{ The most aggressive attempt. White intends Rg1 and g5 to attack the knight on f6. However, it is curious that modern theory evolved so much that, in spite of the aggressive nature of White's play, his best chances lie in the endgame! }
7... Nc6
{ Black develops in the centre and is just in time to strike with d5 before the knight on f6 is attacked. This move is needed to cover the e5-square, so that after ...d5 White cannot play e5. }
8. Rg1
{ White removes the rook from h1, so that he can recapture with hxg5 after pushing g5. Note that theline with an immediate 7.g5 is analysed in the next chapter @@StartBracket@@Keres Attack Various@@EndBracket@@.   Against other moves, Black obtains good play immediately, for example,  8.Nxc6?!  bxc6  gives Black a strong centre, @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3pp1/2nppn1p/8/3NP1PP/2N5/PPP2P2/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Nb3  allows again  8...d5  , while @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3pp1/2nppn1p/8/3NP1PP/2N5/PPP2P2/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Be3?!  drops a pawn after  8...Nxd4  9.Bxd4  e5  when the pawn on g4 is attacked twice. }
8... d5
{ Just in time! Black plays in classical fashion, countering White's flank attack with a strike in the centre. Now White has three options: take on d5, play Bb5 or take on c6. The only critical option is the first one. }
9. Bb5
{ Pinning the knight on c6, but the bishop on b5 will be very vulnerable to tactics with Nxd4 later on. }
9... Bd7 { Breaking the pin and now threatening to take on e4. } 10. exd5 Nxd5
{ Black takes with the knight, thus avoiding any problems connected with the g5 move, and at the same time he opens the h4-d8 diagonal for the queen, attacking the pawn on h4. }
11. Nxd5 exd5 { Now White has two moves:  12.Qe2  and  12.Be3  . } 12. Be3
{ This is the more critical choice. } 12... Be7
{ Black develops his kingside and is ready to move his king from the centre. Now White has an ample choice where to develop his queen in order to prepare long castle. Taking on h4 is dangeous because after  12...Qxh4?!  13.Qd3  followed by O-O-O White has excellent compensation in view of Black's lag in development. Note that the move @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pp1b1pp1/2n4p/1B1p4/3N2Pq/4B3/PPP2P2/R2QK1R1 w Qkq - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Qe2  transposes tothe line with 12.Qe2+. }
13. Qd3 O-O
{ Black finishes development and now threatens  14.--  Nxd4  15.Bxd4  Qa5+  . Before castling this would have been met by Bxd7 with check. }
14. g5
{ This looks dangerous for Black at first sight, but please note how quick Black's counterplay is. }
14... Ne5
{ Black attacks White's queen and also targets the f3-square. In this position, Black has another two satisfactory moves. I'll give a short analysis here if you prefer to explore them.   One is  14...Nxd4  15.Qxd4  Bxb5  when Black wins a piece, but White hopes to create threats along the g-file. The maximum White can get is a perpetual and for that he needs to play only moves, for example  16.gxh6  Bf6  17.Rxg7  Kh8  18.Qf4  and now Black can choose between  18...Qa5  ,  18...Re8  and  18...Bxb2  .   The third alternative is  14...h5  , which leads to unclear play after  15.O-O-O  g6  . }
15. Qe2 Qa5+ { Now White is forced to cover with the bishop. } 16. Bd2
{ The point of Black's 14...Ne5 is shown after  16.c3  when Black takes on b5 with  16...Bxb5  and White must take with a knight because taking with the queen loses the exchange after  17.Qxb5?  Qxb5  18.Nxb5  Nf3  .   After @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pp2bpp1/7p/qb1pn1P1/3N3P/2P1B3/PP2QP2/R3K1R1 w Q - 0 17@@EndFEN@@  17.Nxb5  h5  Black is much better because he stopped White's kingside activity  while the king on e1 cannot find safety on the queenside because of the queen on a5 that attacks the pawn on a2. }
16... Bxb5 { Black takes the bishop and now White has a choice to make. } 17.
Qxe5
{ Taking the bishop is worse,  17.Nxb5  Bb4!  @@StartBracket@@opening the e-file with tempo@@EndBracket@@  18.c3  Rfe8  and White has problems on the e-file.   Taking the queen leads to an equal endgame after  17.Bxa5  Bxe2  18.Kxe2  h5  followed  by Rfe8 and Bc5 when Black's activity and White's weakened kingside provide good play. }
17... Bb4 { Attacking the bishop on d2 and opening the e-file. } 18. O-O-O
{ White has to get away from the centre but he still hasn't found peace. }
18... Bxd2+ { Forcing White to blockade the d2-square with a rook. } 19. Rxd2
Qxa2
{ Threatening mate. If you go back and observe the moves since White's 14.g5 you will notice that it is Black who is doing the attacking all the time and White didn't have time to take on h6, a threat he created a long time ago! }
20. Nb3 { Covering the a1-square. } 20... Rae8
{ It is important to remove the queen from the a1-h8 diagonal so that a capture on h6 doesn't threaten mate on g7. }
21. Qxd5
{ If White remains on the long diagonal after  21.Qd4  Black continues to harass the queen with  21...Re4  22.Qxd5  Bc6  followed  by h5 when Black closes the kingside and continues with his attack on the queenside. }
21... Ba4
{ Black threatens to take on b3 and then give check @@StartBracket@@or mate@@EndBracket@@ on a1. }
22. gxh6
{ Finally executing the threat created eight moves ago! White's position is dangerous so he's best advised to go for the perpetual. }
22... Bxb3 { Threatening mate. } 23. Rxg7+ Kh8 24. Rh7+
{ After this White gives perpetual check. He cannot take the bishop with  24.cxb3  because after  24...Qa1  25.Kc2  Rc8  26.Kd3  Rfd8  Black wins  the queen on d5. }
24... Kxh7 25. Qf5+ Kxh6 26. Qg5+ Kh7 27. Qh5+ Kg7 { With a draw. } *

