{ The Keres Attack is White's most ambitious try against the Scheveningen. Black's last move closed the h3-c8 diagonal for the bishop on c8, so White uses that fact to advance the g-pawn immediately. }
6... h6
{ Practice has shown that this is Black's best reply. Black stops White's threat of g5 and uses the next moves to develop and strike in the centre. }
7. h4
{ The most aggressive attempt. White intends Rg1 and g5 to attack the knight on f6. However, it is curious that modern theory evolved so much that, in spite of the aggressive nature of White's play, his best chances lie in the endgame! }
7... Nc6
{ Black develops in the centre and is just in time to strike with d5 before the knight on f6 is attacked. This move is needed to cover the e5-square, so that after ...d5 White cannot play e5. }
8. Rg1
{ White removes the rook from h1, so that he can recapture with hxg5 after pushing g5. Note that theline with an immediate 7.g5 is analysed in the next chapter @@StartBracket@@Keres Attack Various@@EndBracket@@.   Against other moves, Black obtains good play immediately, for example,  8.Nxc6?!  bxc6  gives Black a strong centre, @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3pp1/2nppn1p/8/3NP1PP/2N5/PPP2P2/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Nb3  allows again  8...d5  , while @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3pp1/2nppn1p/8/3NP1PP/2N5/PPP2P2/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Be3?!  drops a pawn after  8...Nxd4  9.Bxd4  e5  when the pawn on g4 is attacked twice. }
8... d5
{ Just in time! Black plays in classical fashion, countering White's flank attack with a strike in the centre. Now White has three options: take on d5, play Bb5 or take on c6. The only critical option is the first one. }
9. Bb5
{ Pinning the knight on c6, but the bishop on b5 will be very vulnerable to tactics with Nxd4 later on. }
9... Bd7 { Breaking the pin and now threatening to take on e4. } 10. exd5 Nxd5
{ Black takes with the knight, thus avoiding any problems connected with the g5 move, and at the same time he opens the h4-d8 diagonal for the queen, attacking the pawn on h4. }
11. Nxd5 exd5 { Now White has two moves:  12.Qe2  and  12.Be3  . } 12. Be3
{ This is the more critical choice. } 12... Be7
{ Black develops his kingside and is ready to move his king from the centre. Now White has an ample choice where to develop his queen in order to prepare long castle. Taking on h4 is dangeous because after  12...Qxh4?!  13.Qd3  followed by O-O-O White has excellent compensation in view of Black's lag in development. Note that the move @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pp1b1pp1/2n4p/1B1p4/3N2Pq/4B3/PPP2P2/R2QK1R1 w Qkq - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Qe2  transposes tothe line with 12.Qe2+. }
13. Qd2
{ The most natural move, introducing the idea of a piece sacrifice on h6. }
13... O-O
{ Black is not afraid of ghosts. He banks on his finished development and the ability of his pieces to counterattack. It is possible to play for simplifications after  13...Nxd4  , when Black should be fine after  14.Bxd7  Qxd7  15.Qxd4  Bf6  16.Qb4  d4!  , when Black sacrifices the d-pawn for activity, but there is no reason why Black should seek simplifications when his chances are quite promising in the middlegame!   Note that taking the pawn on h4 leads to problems after  13...Bxh4?!  14.O-O-O  Bf6  15.Nf5  with strong initiative as in the classical game Karpov-Spassky from Tilburg in 1980. }
14. Be2
{ Another move, apart from Nf5, that avoids the threat of Nxd4 as White removes the bishop from the vulnerable position on b5. }
14... Bxh4
{ Black is fully developed and now can take the pawn on h4. Without a pawn on h4 it is more difficult for White to push g5 as Black now has more control over that square. }
15. O-O-O Re8
{ Activating the rook and introducing ideas like ...Re5 or ...Re4. } 16. Nf5
{ White is also fully developed and starts to place pieces closer to the black king. After 16.Bf3 Re5 we can see how the black rook can be used to defend the pawn on d5, with the tactical justification of 17.Bf4 Bg5! exchanging the dark-squared bishops. }
16... d4
{ A very important move. Black sacrifices the central pawn in order to open the central files. }
17. Nxd4 Nxd4 18. Qxd4 { Or  18.Bxd4  Bc6  with easy play for Black. } 18...
Bxf2
{ This tactic is possible because of the active position of the rook on the e-file and the vulnerable position of the bishop on e2 @@StartBracket@@the hapless bishop wasn't safe on b5 but neither it is on e2!@@EndBracket@@. }
19. Bxf2 Rxe2 { White is now forced to exchange queens and after } 20. Qxd7
Qxd7 21. Rxd7 Rxf2 22. Rxb7 Rc8
{ Black is at least equal in this double-rook endgame thanks to the activity of his rooks. }
23. c3 a5
{ Black has three main ideas in this endgame: if possible, to activate the rooks along the 2nd rank @@StartBracket@@for example Rd8-d2 or Re8-e2@@EndBracket@@, to activate his kingside majority @@StartBracket@@g5 and h5 or f5@@EndBracket@@ and to keep an eye on the queenside by taking care of the a5-pawn. }
