14. Nf5
{ White avoids the threat of Nxd4 and places his knight on an active position in the vicinity of Black's king. }
14... d4
{ A very important move that opens the centre. With White's king still on e1 Black seeks to take advantage of the opening of the position. }
15. Bxd4
{ The other recapture  15.Nxd4?  loses a piece to  15...Nxd4  in view  of the threat of Nf3 and Bxb5. The capture on d4 leaves White with a weak king in the centre. }
15... Bxf5
{ Now the bishop on d4 hangs, so White must eliminate the piece that attacks it, i.e. the knight on c6. }
16. Bxc6 Bxc2
{ Black nicely takes advantage of the loose position of White's bishops. The queen must stay on d2 to defend the bishop on d4 and the bishop on c6 still hangs. }
17. Bc3
{ Removing the bishop from d4. Taking on b7 is worse, as after  17.Bxb7?  Rb8  the open b-file is only in Black's favour. If the bishop moves from b7 there is the threat of Bb4 and in case of  18.Bc3  Rxb7  19.Qxc2  Bxh4  White's king is stuck in the centre. }
17... Bxh4 { In addition to the initiative Black is now also a pawn up. } 18.
Qxd8
{ Escaping to an endgame, but it doesn't bring much respite. After  18.Qxc2  bxc6  Black is a pawn up and continues the attack against White's king in the centre. }
18... Raxd8 19. Bb5
{ Keeping control over the e8-square. After  19.Bxb7  Bd3  White's king won't survive for long as the threat is a check on the e-file, for example  20.Bc6  Rd6  with ideas like Re6 or Rfd8 and then Re6. }
19... a6 { Chasing away the bishop. } 20. Be2 { Covering the e-file. } 20...
Rfe8
{ Black has a winning endgame: a pawn up, much better pieces and a continuous initiative against White's king. }
