{ Black develops in the centre and is just in time to strike with d5 before the knight on f6 is attacked. This move is needed to cover the e5-square, so that after ...d5 White cannot play e5. }
8. Rg1
{ White removes the rook from h1, so that he can recapture with hxg5 after pushing g5. Note that theline with an immediate 7.g5 is analysed in the next chapter @@StartBracket@@Keres Attack Various@@EndBracket@@.   Against other moves, Black obtains good play immediately, for example,  8.Nxc6?!  bxc6  gives Black a strong centre, @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3pp1/2nppn1p/8/3NP1PP/2N5/PPP2P2/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Nb3  allows again  8...d5  , while @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3pp1/2nppn1p/8/3NP1PP/2N5/PPP2P2/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Be3?!  drops a pawn after  8...Nxd4  9.Bxd4  e5  when the pawn on g4 is attacked twice. }
8... d5
{ Just in time! Black plays in classical fashion, countering White's flank attack with a strike in the centre. Now White has three options: take on d5, play Bb5 or take on c6. The only critical option is the first one. }
9. Bb5
{ Pinning the knight on c6, but the bishop on b5 will be very vulnerable to tactics with Nxd4 later on. }
9... Bd7 { Breaking the pin and now threatening to take on e4. } 10. exd5 Nxd5
{ Black takes with the knight, thus avoiding any problems connected with the g5 move, and at the same time he opens the h4-d8 diagonal for the queen, attacking the pawn on h4. }
11. Nxd5 exd5 { Now White has two moves:  12.Qe2  and  12.Be3  . } 12. Be3
{ This is the more critical choice. } 12... Be7
{ Black develops his kingside and is ready to move his king from the centre. Now White has an ample choice where to develop his queen in order to prepare long castle. Taking on h4 is dangeous because after  12...Qxh4?!  13.Qd3  followed by O-O-O White has excellent compensation in view of Black's lag in development. Note that the move @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pp1b1pp1/2n4p/1B1p4/3N2Pq/4B3/PPP2P2/R2QK1R1 w Qkq - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Qe2  transposes tothe line with 12.Qe2+. }
13. Qd2
{ The most natural move, introducing the idea of a piece sacrifice on h6. }
13... O-O
{ Black is not afraid of ghosts. He banks on his finished development and the ability of his pieces to counterattack. It is possible to play for simplifications after  13...Nxd4  , when Black should be fine after  14.Bxd7  Qxd7  15.Qxd4  Bf6  16.Qb4  d4!  , when Black sacrifices the d-pawn for activity, but there is no reason why Black should seek simplifications when his chances are quite promising in the middlegame!   Note that taking the pawn on h4 leads to problems after  13...Bxh4?!  14.O-O-O  Bf6  15.Nf5  with strong initiative as in the classical game Karpov-Spassky from Tilburg in 1980. }
14. Bxc6
{ With this move White eliminates the threat of Nxd4 and gains tempo to castle long. }
14... bxc6
{ Black opens the b-file and obtains mobile pawns in the centre that can move forward with c5 and d4. }
15. O-O-O Rb8
{ Activating the rook first. The move  15...c5?!  is premature in view of  16.Nf5  d4  17.Bxh6!  . }
16. Nf5
{ Moving either pawn on the kingside is harmless, for example  16.g5?!  h5  allows Black to close the kingside, while @@StartFEN@@1r1q1rk1/p2bbpp1/2p4p/3p4/3N2PP/4B3/PPPQ1P2/2KR2R1 w - - 2 16@@EndFEN@@  16.h5  c5  17.Nf5  Bf6  gives Black good play as White cannot continue with kingside play because moving the g-pawn leaves  the f5-knight without protection. }
16... Bf6
{ It is also possible to take on f5, it leads to an equal position, but Black can keep the tension by keeping more pieces on the board. }
17. Bd4
{ Neutralising the bishop. After  17.c3  Qa5  18.a3  Rb7  , intending to double on the b-file Black has great play. }
17... c5 { Forcing White to take on f6 and activating the central pawn pair. }
18. Bxf6 Qxf6 19. Qc3
{ Black is way too active and allowing  19.c3  d4  is dangerous for White. }
19... Qxc3
{ Black couldn't avoid the exchange of queens, but this capture wrecks White's queenside structure. }
20. Ne7+
{ With this intermediate check White wants to win the d5-pawn. The simple  20.bxc3  Bxf5  21.gxf5  Rfd8  leads to an equal endgame. }
20... Kh7 21. bxc3 Be6
{ Black wants to defend the pawn on d5 with Rfd8 now, so White must take it. }
22. Nxd5 Rb5
{ Black is a pawn down, but he has more than enough compensation. He wants to play Rfb8 and penetrate along the open b-file. Note that White's a2-pawn is isolated and can easily be attacked with Rb2 and also the knight on d5 cannot really move as then the bishop would take the a2-pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Keres Attack with 7.h4"]
[Black "Keres Attack 7.h4 - 9.exd5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. g4
{ The Keres Attack is White's most ambitious try against the Scheveningen. Black's last move closed the h3-c8 diagonal for the bishop on c8, so White uses that fact to advance the g-pawn immediately. }
6... h6
{ Practice has shown that this is Black's best reply. Black stops White's threat of g5 and uses the next moves to develop and strike in the centre. }
7. h4
{ The most aggressive attempt. White intends Rg1 and g5 to attack the knight on f6. However, it is curious that modern theory evolved so much that, in spite of the aggressive nature of White's play, his best chances lie in the endgame! }
7... Nc6
{ Black develops in the centre and is just in time to strike with d5 before the knight on f6 is attacked. This move is needed to cover the e5-square, so that after ...d5 White cannot play e5. }
8. Rg1
{ White removes the rook from h1, so that he can recapture with hxg5 after pushing g5. Note that theline with an immediate 7.g5 is analysed in the next chapter @@StartBracket@@Keres Attack Various@@EndBracket@@.   Against other moves, Black obtains good play immediately, for example,  8.Nxc6?!  bxc6  gives Black a strong centre, @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3pp1/2nppn1p/8/3NP1PP/2N5/PPP2P2/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Nb3  allows again  8...d5  , while @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3pp1/2nppn1p/8/3NP1PP/2N5/PPP2P2/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Be3?!  drops a pawn after  8...Nxd4  9.Bxd4  e5  when the pawn on g4 is attacked twice. }
8... d5
{ Just in time! Black plays in classical fashion, countering White's flank attack with a strike in the centre. Now White has three options: take on d5, play Bb5 or take on c6. The only critical option is the first one. }
9. exd5
{ The immediate  9.g5  is met by  9...hxg5  and after  10.Nxc6  bxc6  11.hxg5  Nxe4  transposes tothe  9.Nxc6  line. }
9... Nxd5
{ Taking with the knight opens the h4-d8 diagonal. In many lines, the pawn on h4 hangs and Black happily takes it. }
10. Nxd5 exd5
{ It is entirely possible to take with the queen, although I feel that in those lines White has easier play. }
11. Qe2+
{ Inserting this check before playing Be3 limits White's possibilities. } 11...
Be7 { Black develops his kingside. } 12. Be3 O-O
{ The sharper option. Here's a brief analysis of the calmer alternative that simpifies the position:  12...Qa5  13.c3  Be6  @@StartBracket@@Black prepares to castle long@@EndBracket@@  14.g5  O-O-O  15.Qb5  Qxb5  16.Bxb5  Nxd4  17.Bxd4  hxg5  18.hxg5  a6  19.Be2  f6  with an equal endgame. }
13. g5
{ This is bad, as White neglects his development and his king and queen on the e-file are exposed after }
13... Nxd4 14. Bxd4 Re8 { When Black is winning. } *

