{ It is entirely possible to take with the queen, although I feel that in those lines White has easier play. }
11. Qe2+
{ Inserting this check before playing Be3 limits White's possibilities. } 11...
Be7 { Black develops his kingside. } 12. Be3 O-O
{ The sharper option. Here's a brief analysis of the calmer alternative that simpifies the position:  12...Qa5  13.c3  Be6  @@StartBracket@@Black prepares to castle long@@EndBracket@@  14.g5  O-O-O  15.Qb5  Qxb5  16.Bxb5  Nxd4  17.Bxd4  hxg5  18.hxg5  a6  19.Be2  f6  with an equal endgame. }
13. O-O-O Bxh4
{ Black takes the h-pawn. As is usual in similar cases, it is more about the control over the g5-square than the extra pawn. }
14. Nf3
{ White attacks the bishop on h4 and increases control over the g5-square. }
14... Be7
{ The bishop retreats to e7 in order to avoid  14...Bf6?  15.g5!  with a tempo. }
15. Qd2 { Now  15.g5  can be met by  15...h5  . } 15... Be6
{ Black has more than one decent move here. For example the sensible  15...Qd6  prevents the sacrifice on h6 and the endgame after  16.Qxd5  Qxd5  17.Rxd5  g5!?  @@StartBracket@@a good move, fixing the pawn on g4@@EndBracket@@ is equal.   Another good option is  15...Re8  , liberating the f8-square for the bishop. I give  15...Be6  in order to show Black's attacking possibilities. }
16. Bxh6
{ The sacrifice is natural and now both sides try to mate each other. } 16...
d4
{ An important move, opening the a2-g8 diagonal for the bishop. It is also possible to take the bishop, as White has a perpetual but nothing more. Still, it's more exciting to play for counterplay. }
17. Rh1 { Threatening Bxg7 and Qh6+. } 17... Nb4
{ Black threatens to take on a2. } 18. Bxg7 Nxa2+ 19. Kb1 Nc3+
{ An important resource! Now White should repeat with  20.Kc1  Na2  because taking the knight leads to mate. }
20. bxc3 Qb6+
{ White's king cannot hide from the queen helped by the bishops. } 21. Ka1 Qa5+
22. Kb1 Qa2+ 23. Kc1 Qa1# { A nice way to finish a game of chess. } *

