6. g4
{ The Keres Attack is White's most ambitious try against the Scheveningen. Black's last move closed the h3-c8 diagonal for the bishop on c8, so White uses that fact to advance the g-pawn immediately. }
6... h6
{ Practice has shown that this is Black's best reply. Black stops White's threat of g5 and uses the next moves to develop and strike in the centre. }
7. h4
{ The most aggressive attempt. White intends Rg1 and g5 to attack the knight on f6. However, it is curious that modern theory evolved so much that, in spite of the aggressive nature of White's play, his best chances lie in the endgame! }
7... Nc6
{ Black develops in the centre and is just in time to strike with d5 before the knight on f6 is attacked. This move is needed to cover the e5-square, so that after ...d5 White cannot play e5. }
8. Rg1
{ White removes the rook from h1, so that he can recapture with hxg5 after pushing g5. Note that theline with an immediate 7.g5 is analysed in the next chapter @@StartBracket@@Keres Attack Various@@EndBracket@@.   Against other moves, Black obtains good play immediately, for example,  8.Nxc6?!  bxc6  gives Black a strong centre, @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3pp1/2nppn1p/8/3NP1PP/2N5/PPP2P2/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Nb3  allows again  8...d5  , while @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3pp1/2nppn1p/8/3NP1PP/2N5/PPP2P2/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Be3?!  drops a pawn after  8...Nxd4  9.Bxd4  e5  when the pawn on g4 is attacked twice. }
8... d5
{ Just in time! Black plays in classical fashion, countering White's flank attack with a strike in the centre. Now White has three options: take on d5, play Bb5 or take on c6. The only critical option is the first one. }
9. exd5
{ The immediate  9.g5  is met by  9...hxg5  and after  10.Nxc6  bxc6  11.hxg5  Nxe4  transposes tothe  9.Nxc6  line. }
9... Nxd5
{ Taking with the knight opens the h4-d8 diagonal. In many lines, the pawn on h4 hangs and Black happily takes it. }
10. Nxd5 exd5
{ It is entirely possible to take with the queen, although I feel that in those lines White has easier play. }
11. Be3
{ The main move. Pinning the knight on c6 with  11.Bb5  Bd7  leads to thelines analysed after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3pp1/2n1pn1p/3p4/3NP1PP/2N5/PPP2P2/R1BQKBR1 w Qkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Bb5  Bd7  10.exd5  Nxd5  11.Nxd5  exd5  . }
11... Qxh4 { Black takes the pawn and activates the queen. } 12. Bb5
{ White develops with tempo, pinning the knight on c6. } 12... Qh2
{ An important maneuver, showing another idea of the pawn capture on h4: the queen gains tempo and returns back to d6 to cover the knight. }
13. Nf3 Qd6
{ Now White must try to use his development advantage before Black finishes development and consolidates. }
14. Qe2 a6
{ Not fearing ghosts, Black wants to clarify White's intentions with the light-squared bishop. }
15. Bxc6+
{ Taking on h6 will transpose after  15.Bxh6  Be6  16.Bxc6  Qxc6  , while moving to a4 is worse because after  15.Ba4  Qb4  16.Bd2  Qe4  Black forces the exchange of queens that leaves him in a better endgame. }
15... Qxc6
{ Taking with a pawn is entirely possible, for example  15...bxc6  16.0-0-0  Be7  followed by O-O with unclear play. }
16. O-O-O
{ White wants to extract more from the position. After  16.Bxh6  Be6  17.Nd4  Qb6  18.Nxe6  Qxe6  followed  by O-O-O the position is equal. }
16... Qc4
{ Challenging White's queen and attacking the pawn on a2. White cannot allow the exchange of queens, being a pawn down, so he must continue with... }
17. Rd3 Qxa2
{ Black is not afraid of the discovered check as White has nothing to attack on the dark squares. }
18. Bd4+ Be6 { Preparing long castle. } 19. Re3
{ With the blunt threat to take on e6. Black cannot stop it, but he can get his king to the queenside. }
19... O-O-O 20. Rxe6
{ White doesn't have a choice, otherwise he's two pawns down for nothing. Now he manages to force a perpetual check. }
20... fxe6 21. Qxe6+ Kb8 22. Be5+ Ka7
{ After  22...Ka8  things are a bit complicated after  23.Qb6  followed by Bd4, even though here again it can lead to a repetition. Moving the king to a7 is simpler. }
23. Bd4+ Kb8
{ With a perpetual check. It's worth noting that White cannot play for more. }
24. Qb6 Bd6
{ Black covers the dark squares and is winning with the extra material. } *

