{ White removes the rook from h1, so that he can recapture with hxg5 after pushing g5. Note that theline with an immediate 7.g5 is analysed in the next chapter @@StartBracket@@Keres Attack Various@@EndBracket@@.   Against other moves, Black obtains good play immediately, for example,  8.Nxc6?!  bxc6  gives Black a strong centre, @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3pp1/2nppn1p/8/3NP1PP/2N5/PPP2P2/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Nb3  allows again  8...d5  , while @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3pp1/2nppn1p/8/3NP1PP/2N5/PPP2P2/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Be3?!  drops a pawn after  8...Nxd4  9.Bxd4  e5  when the pawn on g4 is attacked twice. }
8... d5
{ Just in time! Black plays in classical fashion, countering White's flank attack with a strike in the centre. Now White has three options: take on d5, play Bb5 or take on c6. The only critical option is the first one. }
9. exd5
{ The immediate  9.g5  is met by  9...hxg5  and after  10.Nxc6  bxc6  11.hxg5  Nxe4  transposes tothe  9.Nxc6  line. }
9... Nxd5
{ Taking with the knight opens the h4-d8 diagonal. In many lines, the pawn on h4 hangs and Black happily takes it. }
10. Nxd5 exd5
{ It is entirely possible to take with the queen, although I feel that in those lines White has easier play. }
11. Be3
{ The main move. Pinning the knight on c6 with  11.Bb5  Bd7  leads to thelines analysed after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3pp1/2n1pn1p/3p4/3NP1PP/2N5/PPP2P2/R1BQKBR1 w Qkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Bb5  Bd7  10.exd5  Nxd5  11.Nxd5  exd5  . }
11... Qxh4 { Black takes the pawn and activates the queen. } 12. Qe2
{ This move also prepares long castle, but the position of the white queen and king on the same file allow Black to force the exchange of queens. }
12... Nxd4 { Opening the e-file. } 13. Bxd4+ Qe7
{ Being a pawn up Black seeks the exchange of queens. } 14. Qxe7+
{ After  14.O-O-O  Qxe2  15.Bxe2  Be6  followed by Kd7 Black is fine as the bishop on e2 closes the e-file so White cannot quickly use it to his advantage @@StartBracket@@compare for example to theline starting with 12.Qf3 when the bishop is already on f3  . }
14... Kxe7
{ A forced recapture for Black as the bishop on f8 must stay there to defend the pawn on g7. }
15. O-O-O
{ Black is a pawn up in this endgame, but White's better coordination gives him compensation. A likely scenario is that White regains the pawn but this in turn leads to simplifications and an equal position. A sample line is: }
15... f6 { Blunting the long diagonal. } 16. Be3 Be6
{ Black defends the pawn and develops. } 17. Bg2 b6
{ Black has to defend the pawn on a7 before moving the rook, allowing White to regain the pawn. }
18. Bxd5 Rd8
{ Black forces further exchanges. It may appear dangerous for him, but that's not the case. }
19. Bxe6 Rxd1+ 20. Rxd1 Kxe6 21. Rd8 g6
{ Black has this nice move which threatens h5. The passed h-pawn will be very strong and will not allow White to go after Black's queenside pawns. }
