{ Black gains a tempo and with his next move centralises the queen on e4. } 14.
Be2 Qe4
{ Seeking the exchange of queens. Black spends a lot of time moving with the queen, but in the endgame he will be a pawn up. }
15. O-O-O { White will have compensation in the endgame. } 15... Qxf3
{ Black exchanges queens. In the endgame his king won't be in trouble if it stays in the centre. }
16. Bxf3 Be6 { Defending the d5-pawn and developing the queenside. } 17. Rge1
Kd7
{ Getting away from the pin on the e-file. Now White has several options at his disposal. In most cases the general scenario is that White manages to regain the pawn but loses the initiative, leading to equality. }
18. Kb1 { This is the most critical move, preparing c4. } 18... f6
{ Blunting the bishop on d4 and preparing the development of the bishop on f8. }
19. c4 { White executes his idea. } 19... Bb4
{ An important move, developing with tempo. We will see the importance of the control of the e1-square soon. This is a big improvement over  19...Bf7?  that was played in the online game Karjakin-Duda from the New In Chess Classic in April 2021 in which White obtained an advantage after  20.Bxd5  Bxd5  21.Be3!  . }
20. Rxe6
{ An ambitious exchange sacrifice. White gets a pawn and a powerful light-squared bishop in return. The automatic  20.Re2  allows Black to oppose on the e-file with  20...Rhe8  and  21.cxd5  Bf7  leads to equality as the passed d-pawn is well-controlled by Black's centralised king. }
20... Kxe6 21. Bxd5+ Ke7
{ Black doesn't put the king on the d-file where it will be exposed. Notice the important task of the bishop on b4, covering the e1-square and making sure the king is not harassed on the e-file. }
22. Bxb7 Rab8 { Moving away with tempo. } 23. Bd5 a5
{ Another important move. The key in this position for Black is to blockade White's queenside majority. He will do so on the dark squares @@StartBracket@@b4 and c5@@EndBracket@@ and the task of the a-pawn is to prevent White from expanding with a3 and b4. }
24. Kc2 a4
{ Grabbing more queenside space. Now a possible  25.b3  can be met by  25...a3  @@StartBracket@@in a distant future this pawn may turn out to be very important, being close to the coronation square@@EndBracket@@ and White won't be able to advance his two passed pawns thanks to Black's control over the b4- and c5-squares.   The endgame is dynamically balanced and Black has his chances. He wants to activate his rooks, primarily by pushing h5 and opening the h-file. If White's rook leaves the d-file he can put his king on d6 and use the e-file for one of his rooks. He can also use one rook on the c-file, to further strengthen control over the c5-square. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Keres Attack - Various 7th Moves"]
[Black "Keres Attack Various - 7.Be3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. g4
{ The Keres Attack is White's most ambitious try against the Scheveningen. Black's last move closed the h3-c8 diagonal for the bishop on c8, so White uses that fact to advance the g-pawn immediately. }
6... h6 7. Be3
{ Here we will take a look at what happens if White employs the setup that is characteristic for the English Attack. }
7... Nc6
{ The usual developing move for Black. However, in this position Black has an interesting alternative in the move  7...e5!?  It has been played twice by Svidler and it seems that it's a good try.  The critical line runs  8.Bb5  Bd7  9.Bxd7  Qxd7  10.Nf5  g6  11.Nxh6  Bxh6  12.g5  Ng4  13.gxh6  Nxe3  14.fxe3  and now a possible improvement on the game Radjabov-Svidler from the World Cup in 2015 is the natural recapture  14...Rxh6  when Black should be fine. }
8. f3
{ This is the move that characterises the English Attack. The move  8.h3  is analysed via themove order 7.h3 Nc6 8.Be3, while the move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3pp1/2nppn1p/8/3NP1P1/2N1B3/PPP2P1P/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Rg1  transposes to the line analysed after7.Rg1 Nc6 8.Be3. The move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3pp1/2nppn1p/8/3NP1P1/2N1B3/PPP2P1P/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Bg2?  is bad as  8...Nxd4  followed by e5 wins the pawn on g4. }
8... d5
{ As is typical in the Scheveningen, Black is ready to strike early in the centre thanks to the development of both knights on c6 and f6 that control all four central squares e4, d4, e5 and d5. }
9. Bb5
{ The only critical try. Taking on d5 is harmless,  9.exd5  Nxd5  10.Nxd5  Qxd5  with easy play after  11.Nxc6  bxc6  with the idea of Bb7 @@StartBracket@@or  11...Qxc6  with the idea of b6 and Bb7@@EndBracket@@ as Black's bishops can easily come into play. }
9... Bd7 { Breaking the pin and threatening e5. } 10. exd5
{ White couldn't sustain the tension in the centre any longer and is forced to take. }
10... Nxd5
{ The usual recapture for Black, opening the h4-d8 diagonal and removing the knight from f6 where it could have been subject to attack after g5. }
11. Nxd5 exd5
{ This position resembles the one from the chapterKeres Attack with 7.h4 after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3pp1/3ppn1p/8/3NP1P1/2N5/PPP2P1P/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.h4  Nc6  8.Rg1  d5  9.Bb5  Bd7  10.exd5  Nxd5  11.Nxd5  exd5  ,  with the difference that here White has played f3 and Be3 instead of h4 and Rg1. On one hand, this facilitates his queenside development, but on the other, he has fewer chances on the kingside as g5 isn't a threat without the support from the rook and the h-pawn. }
12. Qe2
{ An alternative development of the queen. White threatens a discovered check. }
12... Be7 { Covering the e-file and preparing short castle. } 13. O-O-O O-O
{ Both sides are ready for the middlegame. The opposite-side castling promises sharp play, but the open centre means that pawn storms are less likely and that both sides will use pieces to create threats. Black now wants to play Re8 to take advantage of the somewhat clumsy position of White's queen and bishop on the e-file. }
14. Nb3
{ Targeting the d5-pawn. In case of  14.Nf5?!  Bxf5  15.gxf5  Re8  ,  with the idea of Bf6, Black is somewhat better as his bishop on f6 cements the kingside and exerts pressure on the long diagonal which Black can add to with ideas like Rc8, Nb4, Qa5 etc.   Now Black has two approaches. One is the more dynamic, where he sacrifices the central d5-pawn to obtain compensation in an open position and the other one is more positional when White's central blockade is compensated with the pair of bishops. }
14... Re8
{ This is the dynamic approach, sacrificing the central pawn on d5. If Black wants to keep it more positional he can play  14...a6  , forcing the exchange on c6. After  15.Bxc6  bxc6  16.Nc5  Rb8  White has control over the dark squares in the centre, d4 and c5 in particular, while Black has the pair of bishops and a solid position. His ideas are Rb5 @@StartBracket@@to keep an eye on the knight on c5@@EndBracket@@, a5 @@StartBracket@@to get some space on the queenside and remove the pawn from the vulnerable square@@EndBracket@@, Re8, Bf6 and so on.   Note that taking the pawn on a6 is not recommendable for White as  17.Qxa6?!  Rb5  gives Black good compensation because White cannot keep the blockade on the c5-square and after  18.Nxd7  Qxd7  Black can use the b-file after Rfb8 to create threats on the queenside. }
15. Rxd5 Qc7
{ Removing the queen from the pin. Now Black's compensation is based on the loose position of White's pieces: the queen and the bishop on the e-file are vulnerable, and so are the rook on d5 @@StartBracket@@Nb4 can be tricky to meet@@EndBracket@@ and the bishop on b5 @@StartBracket@@which can be harassed by a6@@EndBracket@@. }
16. Nc5
{ This move is more direct, with ideas of attacking the bishop on d7 and placing the knight on e4, but White's pieces continue to be loose. }
16... Bg5 { Black pinpoints the problems White has on the e-file. } 17. Ne4
{ The only way to keep the bishop on e3 alive. After  17.Rxd7?  Bxe3  18.Kb1  Qc8  Black wins as the knight on c5 is attacked and it cannot move because that would leave the rook on d7 undefended. }
17... a6 { Introducing more tension in the position. } 18. Bd3
{ Trying to keep it tight, but now the rook on d5 cannot drop back. White cannot allow the opening of the a-file after  18.Nxg5?  axb5  because the pawn on a2 hangs. Going back to a4 invites b5, so after  18.Ba4  b5  19.Bb3  Be6  20.Rdd1  Bxb3  21.axb3  Qa5  Black has unpleasant threats against White's king. }
18... Nb4 { Black wants to take on d3. } 19. Rd4 Nxd3+
{ The pawn on a2 is taboo as after Kb1 the knight cannot escape. } 20. Qxd3 Bb5
{ The bishop on d7 was attacked so it moves away with tempo. } 21. Qd2 Bxe3
{ Leaving the battery of Qd2 and Be3 would have invited possible Bxh6 ideas, so Black doesn't lose time and takes on e3. }
22. Qxe3 Rad8
{ Fighting for the open d-file. An important remark is that the pawn on h2 is hanging so White has to concede the file. Instead, playing Rhd1 would drop the pawn after the exchange on d4. }
23. Rxd8 Rxd8
{ Now Black threatens Rd3. It's curious that Black's initiative continues even after a lot of pieces have been exchanged. A sample line is... }
24. h3 { Removing the pawn from the attacked square. } 24... Rd3
{ Harassing White's queen and also attacking the f3-pawn. } 25. Qf2 Qf4+ 26.
Nd2 { The only move to keep the extra pawn. } 26... Re3 { Threatening Re2. }
27. Re1 { Preventing Re2. } 27... Rxe1+ 28. Qxe1 Bc6
{ Pinning White down to the defence of the f3-pawn. Now a very exciting plan for Black is to use his king actively by playing Kh7-g6-g5 with strong pressure on the kingside. Note that, because of Black's activity, White cannot possibly dream of activating his queenside pawns. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Keres Attack - Various 7th Moves"]
[Black "Keres Attack Various - 7.Be3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. g4
{ The Keres Attack is White's most ambitious try against the Scheveningen. Black's last move closed the h3-c8 diagonal for the bishop on c8, so White uses that fact to advance the g-pawn immediately. }
6... h6 7. Be3
{ Here we will take a look at what happens if White employs the setup that is characteristic for the English Attack. }
7... Nc6
{ The usual developing move for Black. However, in this position Black has an interesting alternative in the move  7...e5!?  It has been played twice by Svidler and it seems that it's a good try.  The critical line runs  8.Bb5  Bd7  9.Bxd7  Qxd7  10.Nf5  g6  11.Nxh6  Bxh6  12.g5  Ng4  13.gxh6  Nxe3  14.fxe3  and now a possible improvement on the game Radjabov-Svidler from the World Cup in 2015 is the natural recapture  14...Rxh6  when Black should be fine. }
8. f3
{ This is the move that characterises the English Attack. The move  8.h3  is analysed via themove order 7.h3 Nc6 8.Be3, while the move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3pp1/2nppn1p/8/3NP1P1/2N1B3/PPP2P1P/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Rg1  transposes to the line analysed after7.Rg1 Nc6 8.Be3. The move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3pp1/2nppn1p/8/3NP1P1/2N1B3/PPP2P1P/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Bg2?  is bad as  8...Nxd4  followed by e5 wins the pawn on g4. }
8... d5
{ As is typical in the Scheveningen, Black is ready to strike early in the centre thanks to the development of both knights on c6 and f6 that control all four central squares e4, d4, e5 and d5. }
9. Bb5
{ The only critical try. Taking on d5 is harmless,  9.exd5  Nxd5  10.Nxd5  Qxd5  with easy play after  11.Nxc6  bxc6  with the idea of Bb7 @@StartBracket@@or  11...Qxc6  with the idea of b6 and Bb7@@EndBracket@@ as Black's bishops can easily come into play. }
9... Bd7 { Breaking the pin and threatening e5. } 10. exd5
{ White couldn't sustain the tension in the centre any longer and is forced to take. }
10... Nxd5
{ The usual recapture for Black, opening the h4-d8 diagonal and removing the knight from f6 where it could have been subject to attack after g5. }
11. Nxd5 exd5
{ This position resembles the one from the chapterKeres Attack with 7.h4 after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3pp1/3ppn1p/8/3NP1P1/2N5/PPP2P1P/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.h4  Nc6  8.Rg1  d5  9.Bb5  Bd7  10.exd5  Nxd5  11.Nxd5  exd5  ,  with the difference that here White has played f3 and Be3 instead of h4 and Rg1. On one hand, this facilitates his queenside development, but on the other, he has fewer chances on the kingside as g5 isn't a threat without the support from the rook and the h-pawn. }
12. Qe2
{ An alternative development of the queen. White threatens a discovered check. }
12... Be7 { Covering the e-file and preparing short castle. } 13. O-O-O O-O
{ Both sides are ready for the middlegame. The opposite-side castling promises sharp play, but the open centre means that pawn storms are less likely and that both sides will use pieces to create threats. Black now wants to play Re8 to take advantage of the somewhat clumsy position of White's queen and bishop on the e-file. }
14. Nb3
{ Targeting the d5-pawn. In case of  14.Nf5?!  Bxf5  15.gxf5  Re8  ,  with the idea of Bf6, Black is somewhat better as his bishop on f6 cements the kingside and exerts pressure on the long diagonal which Black can add to with ideas like Rc8, Nb4, Qa5 etc.   Now Black has two approaches. One is the more dynamic, where he sacrifices the central d5-pawn to obtain compensation in an open position and the other one is more positional when White's central blockade is compensated with the pair of bishops. }
14... Re8
{ This is the dynamic approach, sacrificing the central pawn on d5. If Black wants to keep it more positional he can play  14...a6  , forcing the exchange on c6. After  15.Bxc6  bxc6  16.Nc5  Rb8  White has control over the dark squares in the centre, d4 and c5 in particular, while Black has the pair of bishops and a solid position. His ideas are Rb5 @@StartBracket@@to keep an eye on the knight on c5@@EndBracket@@,a5 @@StartBracket@@to get some space on the queenside and remove the pawn from the vulnerable square@@EndBracket@@, Re8, Bf6 and so on.   Note that taking the pawn on a6 is not recommendable for White as  17.Qxa6?!  Rb5  gives Black good compensation because White cannot keep the blockade on the c5-square and after  18.Nxd7  Qxd7  Black can use the b-file after Rfb8 to create threats on the queenside. }
15. Rxd5 Qc7
{ Removing the queen from the pin. Now Black's compensation is based on the loose position of White's pieces: the queen and the bishop on the e-file are vulnerable, and so are the rook on d5 @@StartBracket@@Nb4 can be tricky to meet@@EndBracket@@ and the bishop on b5 @@StartBracket@@which can be harassed by a6@@EndBracket@@. }
16. Qd2 { The natural move, removing the queen from the e-file. } 16... Be6
{ Moving away from the attacked square. } 17. Rd3 Red8
{ It's important to move away from the pin and allow for Nb4 ideas. } 18. Kb1
Bxb3
{ Black eliminates the knight that controls the a5-square, as his idea is to play Nb4 and Qa5. }
19. cxb3
{ In case of  19.axb3?!  Nb4  followed by Qa5 White has problems defending his king against the intrusion on a2. However, with the doubled b-pawns White's pawn advantage is now largely irrelevant. }
19... Nb4 { With the idea of Qa5. } 20. Rd7
{ The alternative is  20.Qc3  but after  20...Qa5  21.a4  a6  22.Bc4  b5  Black has serious threats on the queenside. }
20... Qe5 { Defending the bishop on e7 and targeting both White's bishops. }
21. Bd4 Qxb5 22. Rxe7
{ Now White threatens a4 when Black's queen cannot defend both the knight on b4 and the pawn on b7. }
22... Nc6
{ The natural retreat that leads to a sharp endgame. If Black wants to keep the tension in the position he can play  22...a5!?  with the idea of Rac8-c2. }
23. Re4 f5 { Harassing White's rook. } 24. Rf4
{ The point of Black's move is that  24.gxf5?  is not possible in view of  24...Qxf5  and after  25.Ka1  Rd5  Black wins thanks to the pin on the d-file.  He threatens Rad8 and Qd7 when White cannot escape with the bishop on d4 first in view of the queen on d2 and second because of the mate on d1. }
24... g5
{ Black wins the bishop now, but White manages to pick up some pawns. } 25.
Rxf5 Rxd4 26. Qxg5+ { The best chance, getting as many pawns as possible. }
26... hxg5 27. Rxb5 Rf8
{ The endgame is objectively about equal as White manages to reduce the number of remaining Black pawns on the board. Still, it is Black who tries to squeeze something more out of it, while the maximum White can hope for is a draw. }
