16. Qd2 { The natural move, removing the queen from the e-file. } 16... Be6
{ Moving away from the attacked square. } 17. Bf4 Qc8
{ Black removes the queen and plans a6 next. } 18. Rd3 a6
{ The bishop has no squares to go to so White must take on c6. } 19. Bxc6 Qxc6
{ Now Black has the bishop pair in addition to his queenside activity as good compensation for the pawn. }
20. Nd4 Qa4
{ Thanks to the threat against the a2-pawn White doesn't have time to eliminate Black's bishop pair. }
21. a3 Bc4 { Moving away with tempo. } 22. Re3 Bd5
{ A nice move. Black's idea is to play Bc5 to attack the knight on d4 and force the exchange of all rooks, when the pawn on f3 will be vulnerable. }
23. Rhe1 Bc5 { Following the plan. } 24. Rxe8+ Rxe8 25. Rxe8+ Qxe8
{ Thanks to the pair of bishops and the weakness on f3 Black has excellent compensation in the endgame. }
