{ This position resembles the one from the chapterKeres Attack with 7.h4 after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3pp1/3ppn1p/8/3NP1P1/2N5/PPP2P1P/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.h4  Nc6  8.Rg1  d5  9.Bb5  Bd7  10.exd5  Nxd5  11.Nxd5  exd5  ,  with the difference that here White has played f3 and Be3 instead of h4 and Rg1. On one hand, this facilitates his queenside development, but on the other, he has fewer chances on the kingside as g5 isn't a threat without the support from the rook and the h-pawn. }
12. Qd2 Be7
{ If Black agrees to a repetition he can play  12...Qh4  13.Bf2  Qg5  14.Be3  Qh4  as any deviation from it by White is fine for him. }
13. O-O-O O-O
{ So far the play is identical to theline starting with 12.Qe2, but here the white queen doesn't experience problems on the e-file. }
14. Nb3 { A more positional approach, aiming to capture the d5-pawn. } 14... a6
{ Chasing away the bishop from b5. If White now wants to keep the pressure on the d-file he must put the bishop on e2, which will make both bishops vulnerable on the e-file. }
15. Be2 Rc8 { Threatening Nb4, which would attack both pawns on a2 and c2. }
16. Kb1 Re8
{ Black's compensation will largely be based on the vulnerable position of White's bishops on the e-file. }
17. Qxd5 Be6
{ As strange as it may seem, the queen doesn't have that many good squares to go to. }
18. Qe4
{ Unfortunately for him White cannot exchange queens as after  18.Qxd8?!  Bxd8!  @@StartBracket@@opening the e-file and threatening Bxb3@@EndBracket@@ we can see the point of Black's play when White cannot keep everything together. }
18... Bd6
{ Again emphasising White's problems on the e-file. The threat is Bxb3. } 19.
Qd3 { White attacks the bishop on d6 in return. } 19... Bxb3
{ Black opens the e-file in order to be able to directly attack the bishops on e3 and e2. }
20. cxb3
{ Taking with the a-pawn is bad in view of  20.axb3  Nb4!  21.Qxd6  Qa5  , winning for Black as there are simply too many threats.   If White abandons the pressure on the d-file and takes with the queen then  20.Qxb3  Qe7  21.Bc1  Na5  again exposes White's vulnerability on the e-file. }
20... Re6
{ An interesting move with the idea of Qe8. The simple  20...Qe7  leads to easy equality after  21.Qxd6  Qxe3  when Black's activity is more than sufficient. }
21. Bc1 Qe8 { Forcing the other bishop back to its initial square. } 22. Bf1
Bf4
{ A cute tactic based on the weakness of the first rank. The threat is to play Rd8xd1 and follow up with Re1. To illustrate: }
23. Bxf4
{ After  23.Qc4  Bxc1  24.Qxc1  Ne5  attacking the queen and the pawn on f3 Black has more than enough play for the pawn. }
23... Rd8 { Now Black wins the queen. } 24. Qxd8
{ Or  24.Qc2  Rxd1  25.Qxd1  Re1  . } 24... Nxd8
{ White should have enough for the queen but it's clear that only Black can play for a win here. }
