[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Keres Attack - Various 7th Moves"]
[Black "Keres Attack Various - 7.Be3 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. g4
{ The Keres Attack is White's most ambitious try against the Scheveningen. Black's last move closed the h3-c8 diagonal for the bishop on c8, so White uses that fact to advance the g-pawn immediately. }
6... h6 7. Be3
{ Here we will take a look at what happens if White employs the setup that is characteristic for the English Attack. }
7... Nc6
{ The usual developing move for Black. However, in this position Black has an interesting alternative in the move  7...e5!?  It has been played twice by Svidler and it seems that it's a good try.  The critical line runs  8.Bb5  Bd7  9.Bxd7  Qxd7  10.Nf5  g6  11.Nxh6  Bxh6  12.g5  Ng4  13.gxh6  Nxe3  14.fxe3  and now a possible improvement on the game Radjabov-Svidler from the World Cup in 2015 is the natural recapture  14...Rxh6  when Black should be fine. }
8. f3
{ This is the move that characterises the English Attack. The move  8.h3  is analysed via themove order 7.h3 Nc6 8.Be3, while the move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3pp1/2nppn1p/8/3NP1P1/2N1B3/PPP2P1P/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Rg1  transposes to the line analysed after7.Rg1 Nc6 8.Be3. The move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3pp1/2nppn1p/8/3NP1P1/2N1B3/PPP2P1P/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Bg2?  is bad as  8...Nxd4  followed by e5 wins the pawn on g4. }
8... d5
{ As is typical in the Scheveningen, Black is ready to strike early in the centre thanks to the development of both knights on c6 and f6 that control all four central squares e4, d4, e5 and d5. }
9. Bb5
{ The only critical try. Taking on d5 is harmless,  9.exd5  Nxd5  10.Nxd5  Qxd5  with easy play after  11.Nxc6  bxc6  with the idea of Bb7 @@StartBracket@@or  11...Qxc6  with the idea of b6 and Bb7@@EndBracket@@ as Black's bishops can easily come into play. }
9... Bd7 { Breaking the pin and threatening e5. } 10. exd5
{ White couldn't sustain the tension in the centre any longer and is forced to take. }
10... Nxd5
{ The usual recapture for Black, opening the h4-d8 diagonal and removing the knight from f6 where it could have been subject to attack after g5. }
11. Nxd5 exd5
{ This position resembles the one from the chapterKeres Attack with 7.h4 after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3pp1/3ppn1p/8/3NP1P1/2N5/PPP2P1P/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.h4  Nc6  8.Rg1  d5  9.Bb5  Bd7  10.exd5  Nxd5  11.Nxd5  exd5  ,  with the difference that here White has played f3 and Be3 instead of h4 and Rg1. On one hand, this facilitates his queenside development, but on the other, he has fewer chances on the kingside as g5 isn't a threat without the support from the rook and the h-pawn. }
12. Qd2 Be7
{ If Black agrees to a repetition he can play  12...Qh4  13.Bf2  Qg5  14.Be3  Qh4  as any deviation from it by White is fine for him. }
13. O-O-O O-O
{ So far the play is identical to theline starting with 12.Qe2, but here the white queen doesn't experience problems on the e-file. }
14. Nf5
{ This is a more aggressive move. Unlike thevariation starting with 12.Qe2 here this move makes more sense as the bishop on e3 and the queen on d2 allow for Bxh6 ideas. }
14... Bxf5 { The knight has to be eliminated as it is too strong on f5. } 15.
gxf5 a6
{ Black wants to determine the position of White's light-squared bishop and will tailor his counterplay based on its retreat. }
16. Ba4 { This invites Black's queenside expansion. } 16... b5 17. Bb3 d4
{ With this pawn sacrifice Black eliminates any possible sacrifices on h6 and activates his bishop on the long diagonal. }
18. Bxd4 Nxd4 19. Qxd4 Qc7
{ Black has good compensation here: he has an easy play on the queenside based on Bf6 and the advance of his pawns @@StartBracket@@a5-a4-a3 creating dark-square weaknesses around White's king@@EndBracket@@. Note the importance of the dark-squared bishop on f6 that both safely defends the king and exerts pressure on the long diagonal. }
