{ This is a more aggressive move. Unlike thevariation starting with 12.Qe2 here this move makes more sense as the bishop on e3 and the queen on d2 allow for Bxh6 ideas. }
14... Bxf5 { The knight has to be eliminated as it is too strong on f5. } 15.
gxf5 a6
{ Black wants to determine the position of White's light-squared bishop and will tailor his counterplay based on its retreat. }
16. Bd3 { Looking towards Black's kingside, but closing the d-file. } 16... Bf6
{ The ideal square for the bishop, defending the kingside and looking toward White's queenside. }
17. Rhg1 { Threatening Bxh6. } 17... Kh7
{ Escaping the pin and defending the h6-pawn. } 18. Rg3
{ White intends either to double on the g-file or to play Rh3 and threaten the pawn on h6. Note that the sacrifice on g7 is unsound:  18.Rxg7?  Kxg7  19.Qg2  Kh8!  20.Qh3  Bh4  and White has nothing. }
18... Ne5
{ The threat of Nxd3 aims to remove White's queen from the c1-h6 diagonal. }
19. Rdg1 Nxd3+ { Forcing White to take with a queen. } 20. Qxd3
{ In case of  20.cxd3?  Qc8  followed by Qxf5 Black wins a pawn and White has nothing to show for it. }
20... Rg8
{ Defending the kingside even though White can still sacrifice. Nevertheless, Black's defence is typical for the counter-attacking spirit of the Sicilian Defence. }
21. Bxh6 gxh6
{ Obviously forced, as taking with the king soon leads to mate after Rh3. } 22.
Rxg8 Qb6
{ The key move in Black's defence. All of a sudden he creates a lot of threats and White needs to think of a rescue plan. }
23. Rxa8 { Or  23.R1g7  Bxg7  24.Rxa8  Qg1  which amounts to the same. } 23...
Qxg1+
{ Taking on b2 is also possible:  23...Bxb2  24.Kd2  Qf2  with the same drawing mechanism. }
24. Kd2 Qf2+ 25. Qe2 Qd4+
{ With a perpetual check, as White cannot escape, for example: } 26. Ke1 Qg1+
27. Qf1 Qe3+ 28. Kd1 Bxb2
{ Threatening Bc3 with mating threats, so White must concede the perpetual with  29.Qd3  Qg1+  30.Kd2  Qf2+  . }
