[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Keres Attack - Various 7th Moves"]
[Black "Keres Attack Various - 7.Rg1 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. g4
{ The Keres Attack is White's most ambitious try against the Scheveningen. Black's last move closed the h3-c8 diagonal for the bishop on c8, so White uses that fact to advance the g-pawn immediately. }
6... h6 7. Rg1
{ This move can be a prelude to h4, but White can also postpone his kingside expansion. It is a useful move as sometimes White can push g5 without the help of h4 and the rook on the g-file can become active. }
7... Nc6 { Black develops in the usual way. } 8. Be3
{ Of course,  8.h4  d5  is a transposition to the chapterKeres Attack with 7.h4. The bishop move speeds up the queenside development, White stays flexible and prepares long castle after the queen moves from d1. This set-up is one of the more challenging ones for Black. }
8... Be7
{ Black develops the bishop and waits for White to move the queen, so he can take on d4 and win a tempo by pushing e5 @@StartBracket@@he didn't do this immediately as White would take Qxd4 in one go@@EndBracket@@. At the same time he keeps the option to push d5. So against any move Black will now react in one of these two ways: he will either take on d4 and push e5 or he will push d5. Now White has a wide choice. }
9. Qd2
{ White prepares long castling, but the queen left the d1-h5 diagonal and doesn't defend the g4-pawn. This is an additional reason for Black to go for the e5 push after exchanging on d4. }
9... Nxd4 10. Qxd4
{ White is forced to lose time with the queen as  10.Bxd4  e5  drops the pawn on g4. }
10... e5 { A double attack on the queen and the pawn on g4. } 11. Qa4+
{ In case of  11.Qd1  Be6  Black is perfectly fine as White only wasted time with the queen and did nothing as she ended up again on d1. }
11... Bd7 12. Bb5
{ White must play with tempo in order to avoid losing the pawn on g4. } 12...
a6 { Forcing exchanges on d7 that lead to an equal endgame. } 13. Bxd7+ Qxd7
14. Qxd7+ Kxd7
{ Black takes with the king as in the endgame he wants to keep him in the centre. }
15. O-O-O
{ After  15.a4  Rac8  with the idea to place the rook on c4 and possibly double on the c-file Black has good play. }
15... b5
{ Expanding on the queenside and introducing the threat of b4, which exposes the e4-pawn. }
16. f3 Ke6
{ Centralising the king and avoiding a possible fork on b6 after b4, Na4. } 17.
a3
{ Preventing b4. Note that the automatic move  17.Nd5  is harmless because after  17...Nxd5  18.Rxd5  h5  Black undermines White's kingside and obtains counterplay on the f-file after  19.g5  f5  .  White's control of the d5-square means nothing as White cannot get anything out of it because the pawn on d6 is well-protected and play takes place on the kingside. }
17... Rad8
{ Intending d5. Now everything will evolve around this central push - Black will try to achieve it and White will try to prevent it. }
18. h4
{ White indirectly prevents d5 because that will be met by g5, attacking the knight that protects the d5-pawn. }
18... Rd7
{ Another preparation for d5. To understand how this move helps the central push take a look at the following line:  18...d5?  19.Bb6!  @@StartBracket@@attacking the rook with tempo and avoiding the d4-fork, that is why it is important to move it from d8@@EndBracket@@  19...Rd7  20.g5  , hitting the knight on f6 and then winning the pawn on d5. }
19. Bf2
{ Another prophylactic move by White, getting away from a possible fork after d5-d4. The immediate  19.g5  is premature as first opens the h-file for Black and second it gives Black a target on the kingside after  19...hxg5  20.hxg5  Ne8  followed by the undermining move f6. }
19... Bd8
{ A fine prophylactic move by Black in return. The bishop gets away from being attacked in case of gxf6 @@StartBracket@@after a sequence of moves with d5, g5, d4@@EndBracket@@ and it also introduces the idea of Ba5, hitting the knight on c3. }
20. Rge1
{ White again prevents d5 in an indirect manner by placing the rook on the e-file that will be opened in that case. }
20... g6
{ The liberating move  20...d5?!  is again premature. After  21.exd5  Nxd5  22.Ne2!  with  the idea of Nd4 Black is under severe pressure in the centre. The idea of g6 is to start attacking White's kingside pawns with h5, so after White pushes g5 that pawn will already be fixed by Black's pawn on g6 so Black can continue to undermine White's structure with f6. Now a sample line illustrating Black's plan goes: }
21. Rd3 h5 22. g5
{ If  22.gxh5  then  22...Nxh5  and the knight will come to f4. } 22... Ne8
{ Intending f6. Note that after the exchange of the pawns on f6 White's pawn on h4 is also fixed and ties down White's bishop to its defence. Additionally, Black can also play g5 and obtain a passed h-pawn. }
23. Nd5 f6
{ Continuing with the plan. Note that the good-looking knight on d5 is largely ineffective because it is controlled by the bishop on d8 and Black successfully plays around it. }
24. gxf6 Nxf6
{ If allowed Black will take on d5 and then organise play on the f-file, targeting White's backward f3-pawn. }
25. Nb4 Ba5
{ Pinning the knight and eliminating it on the next move. With no passive pieces and everything protected, Black has good play in the endgame. He will try to achieve either d5 or g5, further liberating his game. }
