[White "2. Keres Attack - Various 7th Moves"]
[Black "Keres Attack Various - 7.Rg1 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. g4
{ The Keres Attack is White's most ambitious try against the Scheveningen. Black's last move closed the h3-c8 diagonal for the bishop on c8, so White uses that fact to advance the g-pawn immediately. }
6... h6 7. Rg1
{ This move can be a prelude to h4, but White can also postpone his kingside expansion. It is a useful move as sometimes White can push g5 without the help of h4 and the rook on the g-file can become active. }
7... Nc6 { Black develops in the usual way. } 8. Be3
{ Of course,  8.h4  d5  is a transposition to the chapterKeres Attack with 7.h4. The bishop move speeds up the queenside development, White stays flexible and prepares long castle after the queen moves from d1. This set-up is one of the more challenging ones for Black. }
8... Be7
{ Black develops the bishop and waits for White to move the queen, so he can take on d4 and win a tempo by pushing e5 @@StartBracket@@he didn't do this immediately as White would take Qxd4 in one go@@EndBracket@@. At the same time he keeps the option to push d5. So against any move Black will now react in one of these two ways: he will either take on d4 and push e5 or he will push d5. Now White has a wide choice. }
9. Qf3
{ Another queen move that prepares long castle. From f3 the queen keeps an eye on the g4-pawn. }
9... Nxd4 { Black goes for the usual transformation of the pawn structure. }
10. Bxd4 e5
{ Black obtains more space in the centre and liberates the e6-square for the light-squared bishop. }
11. Be3 Be6
{ Black finished development of his light pieces. Now he would like to continue with activity on the queenside with Rc8 and Qa5, introducing the threat of an exchange sacrifice on c3. }
12. Bb5+
{ This is an alternative, White checks Black's intentions depending on how he defends next. }
12... Kf8
{ The ambitious reply. Black keeps control over the d5-square. It is possible to simply cover with the knight, it leads to simplifications with an acceptable position for Black, for example  12...Nd7  13.O-O-O  a6  14.Bxd7  Qxd7  15.Nd5  Bxd5  16.Rxd5  Rc8  with idea to double on  the c-file with Rc4 @@StartBracket@@keeping an eye on the e4-pawn@@EndBracket@@ and Qc7@@StartBracket@@c6@@EndBracket@@. Black can then castle and advance with b5. White's control over the d5-square brings very little as the d6-pawn is securely defended. }
13. h4
{ If White tries to play  13.Ba4  here  @@StartBracket@@with the idea of Bb3 to obtain stronger control over the d5-square@@EndBracket@@, Black can meet this by  13...Qa5  14.Bb3  Bxb3  and now in view of the pin on the a-file White has to take with the c-pawn, so after  15.cxb3  b5  with the idea of b4 Black will take control over the d5-square which will help him achieve the d5 push. }
13... Rc8
{ Developing the rook and introducing the threat of Rxc3. Black has a good alternative here, the move  13...Nh7!?  is a typical move to stop White's kingside expansion by putting pressure on the h4-pawn. Advancing it means a dead-end to White's attack, so he is forced to sacrifice it.  After  14.O-O-O  Bxh4  15.Kb1  Bg5  Black is a pawn up with a solid position and objectively the position is unclear where Black can fancy his chances. }
14. g5
{ White continues with his plan, but this advance solves the problem of Black's development. After the exchange of the h-pawns the black rook on h8 obtains an open file and eliminates the problems of the uncastled king and the passive rook. }
14... hxg5 { Opening the h-file. } 15. hxg5 Rh3 { Activating the rook. } 16.
Rg3
{ In case of  16.Qg2  Nh5  the knight can jump to f4 while the threats on the queenside Rxc3 and Qa5 are still present. }
16... Rxg3 17. Qxg3 Nxe4 { A small tactic that wins a pawn. } 18. Qh2
{ The point is that  18.Nxe4?  Qa5  wins for Black as the bishop on b5 hangs while  19.Nc3  Rxc3!  wins a lot of material. }
18... f5 { Allowing Bg8 in case of Qh8 and defending the knight on e4. } 19.
gxf6 Nxf6
{ The position is unclear and sharp, but with a pawn up and good centralisation Black has every reason to look forward to this complex middlegame. He still has the ideas of Qa5 and Rxc3 and another idea is the maneuver Qe8-h5, trying to neutralise the presence of White's queen on the h-file. }
