1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. g4
{ The Keres Attack is White's most ambitious try against the Scheveningen. Black's last move closed the h3-c8 diagonal for the bishop on c8, so White uses that fact to advance the g-pawn immediately. }
6... h6 7. Rg1
{ This move can be a prelude to h4, but White can also postpone his kingside expansion. It is a useful move as sometimes White can push g5 without the help of h4 and the rook on the g-file can become active. }
7... Nc6 { Black develops in the usual way. } 8. Be3
{ Of course,  8.h4  d5  is a transposition to the chapterKeres Attack with 7.h4. The bishop move speeds up the queenside development, White stays flexible and prepares long castle after the queen moves from d1. This set-up is one of the more challenging ones for Black. }
8... Be7
{ Black develops the bishop and waits for White to move the queen, so he can take on d4 and win a tempo by pushing e5 @@StartBracket@@he didn't do this immediately as White would take Qxd4 in one go@@EndBracket@@. At the same time he keeps the option to push d5. So against any move Black will now react in one of these two ways: he will either take on d4 and push e5 or he will push d5. Now White has a wide choice. }
9. Qf3
{ Another queen move that prepares long castle. From f3 the queen keeps an eye on the g4-pawn. }
9... Nxd4 { Black goes for the usual transformation of the pawn structure. }
10. Bxd4 e5
{ Black obtains more space in the centre and liberates the e6-square for the light-squared bishop. }
11. Be3 Be6
{ Black finished development of his light pieces. Now he would like to continue with activity on the queenside with Rc8 and Qa5, introducing the threat of an exchange sacrifice on c3. }
12. O-O-O
{ This is the natural shelter for the white king, but it's not without dangers. }
12... Rc8
{ Black threatens to play Qa5 and take on c3, in one order or the other, which would wreck White's queenside and give Black good attacking chances. }
13. Bb5+
{ Now Black responds in the same manner by moving the king as in theline with 12.Bb5+. In case of  13.h4  Qa5  14.g5  hxg5  15.hxg5  Nd7  with the looming threat of Rxc3 Black has great play on the queenside. }
13... Kf8
{ The same idea from the line with theimmediate 12.Bb5+ Black wants to continue with his queenside activity with Rxc3 and Qa5. }
14. Ba4
{ This the point of White's 13th move - he wants to place his bishop on b3 in order to bolster his queenside and increase control over the d5-square. }
14... Rxc3
{ Black must be quick with his counterplay before White achieves his plan. It's slow to play  14...Qa5?!  because after  15.Bb3  Bxb3  16.axb3  he has nothing on the queenside and White obtains control over the d5-square.   An interesting alternative is the pawn sacrifice  14...b5!?  when White should decline it by  15.Bb3  and then after  15...b4  16.Nd5  Bxd5  17.Bxd5  Qc7  Black will play a5, g6, Kg7 and at some point take on d5 with an unclear position. The point is that White cannot remove the bishop from d5 with  18.Bb3  because after  18...a5  Black wants  to play Qc6, threatening both the pawn on e4 and the bishop on b3 after playing a4. }
15. bxc3 Qc8
{ Usually Black  follows up with Qa5, but here the queen is more effective from c8 as it targets both pawns on c3 and g4.   Even more so  15...Qa5?!  is insufficient as after  16.Bb3  Qxc3  17.Kb1  White consolidates his queenside and Black's compensation isn't easily visible. }
16. Kb2 Bxg4 { Taking the available pawn. } 17. Qg2
{ Thanks to the pin on the g-file White saves the exchange, but Black nevertheless has good compensation. }
17... g6 { Defending on the g-file and threatening to take on d1. } 18. f3 Be6
19. Bb3 Bc4
{ Gaining space on the queenside. Black has great play here. His position is very solid and he has the plan to advance on the queenside with b5 and a5-a4. On the kingside he will play Kg7 and involve his rook in his queenside activities. Even losing the a7-pawn is of little concern, for example: }
20. Bxa7 b5 21. Be3 Kg7 { With ideas like Qc7, Ra8, d5 etc. } *

