1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. g4
{ The Keres Attack is White's most ambitious try against the Scheveningen. Black's last move closed the h3-c8 diagonal for the bishop on c8, so White uses that fact to advance the g-pawn immediately. }
6... h6 7. Rg1
{ This move can be a prelude to h4, but White can also postpone his kingside expansion. It is a useful move as sometimes White can push g5 without the help of h4 and the rook on the g-file can become active. }
7... Nc6 { Black develops in the usual way. } 8. Be3
{ Of course,  8.h4  d5  is a transposition to the chapterKeres Attack with 7.h4. The bishop move speeds up the queenside development, White stays flexible and prepares long castle after the queen moves from d1. This set-up is one of the more challenging ones for Black. }
8... Be7
{ Black develops the bishop and waits for White to move the queen, so he can take on d4 and win a tempo by pushing e5 @@StartBracket@@he didn't do this immediately as White would take Qxd4 in one go@@EndBracket@@. At the same time he keeps the option to push d5. So against any move Black will now react in one of these two ways: he will either take on d4 and push e5 or he will push d5. Now White has a wide choice. }
9. Qf3
{ Another queen move that prepares long castle. From f3 the queen keeps an eye on the g4-pawn. }
9... Nxd4 { Black goes for the usual transformation of the pawn structure. }
10. Bxd4 e5
{ Black obtains more space in the centre and liberates the e6-square for the light-squared bishop. }
11. Be3 Be6
{ Black finished development of his light pieces. Now he would like to continue with activity on the queenside with Rc8 and Qa5, introducing the threat of an exchange sacrifice on c3. }
12. h4 { White quickly advances on the kingside and threatens g5. } 12... Nh7
{ The typical retreat, attacking the pawn on h4 and exerting more control over the g5-square. Moving the knight to d7 is worse, as after  12...Nd7?!  13.g5  hxg5  14.hxg5  followed by O-O-O and Nd5 White obtains good control.   12...Rc8  is equally bad:  13.g5  Nd7  14.gxh6  gxh6  and Black's kingside is weakened. }
13. g5
{ White is forced to sacrifice a pawn. The move  13.h5?  would be a positional mistake as after  13...O-O  Black's king is safe as White can never cross the g5-square, thus freeing Black's hands for a queenside attack.   The check on b5 is met by the usual moving of the king,  13.Bb5  Kf8  with similar play. }
13... hxg5 14. hxg5 Bxg5
{ Black takes with the bishop as he wants to exchange the dark-squared bishops @@StartBracket@@his bishop is the more passive one@@EndBracket@@ and at the same time he liberates the path for the queen to f6, thus increasing the presence of the pieces on the kingside, which effectively eliminates any danger of an attack. }
15. O-O-O
{ In case of  15.Bb5  Kf8  16.O-O-O  Bxe3  17.fxe3  the pawn on g7 is defended by the king and Black can get his knight back into the game with  17...Nf6  with a satisfactory position. }
15... a6
{ While the immediate  15...Qf6  is possible, it's better to prevent the check from b5 first. }
16. Bh3
{ Having no other choice White, develops the bishop from the other side. An interesting idea for Black is seen after  16.Rh1  Ke7!?  defending the rook on h8 and thus unpinning the knight on h7. Taking the bishop on g5 just helps Black,  @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/1p3ppn/p2pb3/4p1b1/4P3/2N1BQ2/PPP2P2/2KR1BR1 w kq - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16.Bxg5  Nxg5  followed by f6 solidifies Black's grip over the dark squares. }
16... Qf6 { Black follows his plan. } 17. Qg3 Bxe3+ 18. Qxe3
{ In case of  18.fxe3  O-O-O  Black is comfortably equal as his king has found safe shelter. Now Black cannot castle long as the white queen can penetrate along the dark-squares on the queenside. }
18... Rd8
{ Defending the pawn on d6 and threatening to exchange queens by Qh6. } 19. Kb1
Nf8
{ Getting the knight back into the game with tempo as the bishop on h3 is attacked. }
20. Bxe6 fxe6
{ Black needs to have control over the d5-square. The position is unclear, but Black has an extra pawn and is relatively safe. He has various ideas how to place his pieces, for example Rh2, attacking the f2-pawn, Qf4 or Qh6 to activate the queen and seek an exchange, Rd7 in order to cover the pawns along the 7th rank. }
