{ Of course,  8.h4  d5  is a transposition to the chapterKeres Attack with 7.h4. The bishop move speeds up the queenside development, White stays flexible and prepares long castle after the queen moves from d1. This set-up is one of the more challenging ones for Black. }
8... Be7
{ Black develops the bishop and waits for White to move the queen, so he can take on d4 and win a tempo by pushing e5 @@StartBracket@@he didn't do this immediately as White would take Qxd4 in one go@@EndBracket@@. At the same time he keeps the option to push d5. So against any move Black will now react in one of these two ways: he will either take on d4 and push e5 or he will push d5. Now White has a wide choice. }
9. h4
{ This is suboptimal as the move Be3 is superfluous if White wanted to play h4 and g5. Black reacts in the centre now. }
9... d5
{ The usual central push. Since White is still far from castling queenside Black doesn't fear problems on the d-file. }
10. exd5
{ The move  10.Bb5  transposes to the chapter on theKeres Attack with 7.h4 after  10...Bd7  11.exd5  Nxd5  12.Nxd5  exd5  . }
10... Nxd5
{ Black takes with the knight and opens the h4-d8 diagonal, targeting the pawn on h4. }
11. Nxd5 Qxd5
{ An important capture. Taking with the pawn would lead us to a worse line from the chapter on theKeres Attack with 7.h4. To compare, in the line from that chapter starting with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3pp1/3ppn1p/8/3NP1P1/2N5/PPP2P1P/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.h4  Nc6  8.Rg1  d5  9.exd5  Nxd5  10.Nxd5  exd5  11.Be3  the recommended move is  11...Qxh4!  , while the move  11...Be7  , which would lead to the position here if Black takes with the pawn is inferior in view of  12.Qd2!  when White has a solid advantage. }
12. Bg2 Qa5+ { Moving away with tempo. } 13. c3
{ The alternatives aren't better,  13.Qd2  Qxd2  14.Kxd2  Ne5  with the threats of Nc4, Bxh4 and Nxg4 is comfortable for Black.   While  13.Bd2  loses a pawn after  13...Qe5  14.Be3  Bxh4  since thanks to the pin on the e1-h4 diagonal the bishop on e3 is hanging, so White has no time to take on c6. }
13... Bd7
{ Black finishes development and defends the knight on c6. Now the worsening of the structure after exchanges on c6 is compensated with the simplification of the position. }
14. Nxc6 Bxc6 { Black naturally exchanges his passive bishop. } 15. Bxc6+ bxc6
{ Black has no problems here. The pawn on h4 hangs while Black wants to take control over the d-file after Rd8. He also has the somewhat safer king as White won't be able to castle queenside @@StartBracket@@due to the rook on d8 controlling the d1-square@@EndBracket@@. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Keres Attack - Various 7th Moves"]
[Black "Keres Attack Various - 7.Rg1 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. g4
{ The Keres Attack is White's most ambitious try against the Scheveningen. Black's last move closed the h3-c8 diagonal for the bishop on c8, so White uses that fact to advance the g-pawn immediately. }
6... h6 7. Rg1
{ This move can be a prelude to h4, but White can also postpone his kingside expansion. It is a useful move as sometimes White can push g5 without the help of h4 and the rook on the g-file can become active. }
7... Nc6 { Black develops in the usual way. } 8. Be3
{ Of course,  8.h4  d5  is a transposition to the chapterKeres Attack with 7.h4. The bishop move speeds up the queenside development, White stays flexible and prepares long castle after the queen moves from d1. This set-up is one of the more challenging ones for Black. }
8... Be7
{ Black develops the bishop and waits for White to move the queen, so he can take on d4 and win a tempo by pushing e5 @@StartBracket@@he didn't do this immediately as White would take Qxd4 in one go@@EndBracket@@. At the same time he keeps the option to push d5. So against any move Black will now react in one of these two ways: he will either take on d4 and push e5 or he will push d5. Now White has a wide choice. }
9. Be2
{ A simple developing move, but one that shouldn't be underestimated. After Black's typical reaction in the centre with d5 the bishop will come to f3 to exert pressure on the long diagonal. }
9... d5
{ Since White cannot put a rook on the d-file Black is not afraid to open the d-file. }
10. exd5 Nxd5
{ As usual, the exchange of the knights is in Black's favour as the knight on f6 runs the risk of being attacked after g5 @@StartBracket@@with or without the inclusion of h4@@EndBracket@@. }
11. Nxd5 Qxd5
{ It's important to recapture with the queen. In case of  11...exd5?!  12.Qd2  Black doesn't have the counterplay from the chapter on theKeres Attack with 7.h4 because there is no pawn on h4 that hangs! }
12. Nxc6
{ This is more challenging than the simple  12.Bf3  , which can be met by  12...Qa5  13.c3  Bd7  with similar play to theline 9.h4 d5  . }
12... Qxc6 13. Qd3
{ A strong prophylactic move.  The idea is to prevent Black's plan of b6 and Bb7.   For example, the automatic  13.Qd2  is met by  13...b6  14.O-O-O  Bb7  and Black has solved all his opening problems. }
13... Bd7
{ White's idea is seen after  13...b6?  14.Bd4!  with the threats of Bf3 and Bxg7 - here we see why the queen was needed on d3, from where she controls the f3-square and allows the bishop to take over the long diagonal.   However, Black can also play  13...e5!?  and eventually he should be fine in the endgame after  14.O-O-O  a6  15.Qd5  Qxd5  16.Rxd5  f6  though some precision is still required. }
14. O-O-O Qc7
{ Liberating the c6-square for the bishop and also intending Rd8. } 15. Bd4
{ This leads to some sharp play. } 15... O-O
{ Defending the pawn on g7, but White can in fact take it. } 16. Bxg7 Bg5+
{ Removing the bishop from the vulnerable e7-square @@StartBracket@@once White takes Qxd7@@EndBracket@@. }
17. Kb1 Kxg7 18. Qxd7 Qxh2 { Black regained the pawn. } 19. Qxb7 Qxf2
{ The position is sharp and unclear. Black's king is safe as the bishop on g5 and the pawn on h6 can never be dislodged while he can use the open b- and c-files for threats against White's king. He can also drop back the bishop to f6 to further increase the pressure along the dark squares. }
*

