[White "2. Keres Attack - Various 7th Moves"]
[Black "Keres Attack Various - 7.Rg1 #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. g4
{ The Keres Attack is White's most ambitious try against the Scheveningen. Black's last move closed the h3-c8 diagonal for the bishop on c8, so White uses that fact to advance the g-pawn immediately. }
6... h6 7. Rg1
{ This move can be a prelude to h4, but White can also postpone his kingside expansion. It is a useful move as sometimes White can push g5 without the help of h4 and the rook on the g-file can become active. }
7... Nc6 { Black develops in the usual way. } 8. Be3
{ Of course,  8.h4  d5  is a transposition to the chapterKeres Attack with 7.h4. The bishop move speeds up the queenside development, White stays flexible and prepares long castle after the queen moves from d1. This set-up is one of the more challenging ones for Black. }
8... Be7
{ Black develops the bishop and waits for White to move the queen, so he can take on d4 and win a tempo by pushing e5 @@StartBracket@@he didn't do this immediately as White would take Qxd4 in one go@@EndBracket@@. At the same time he keeps the option to push d5. So against any move Black will now react in one of these two ways: he will either take on d4 and push e5 or he will push d5. Now White has a wide choice. }
9. Qe2
{ This is White's most commonly played move. He wants to castle long, at the same time keeping the queen on the d1-h5 diagonal to have the g4-pawn defended. The difference with theline 9.Qf3 is that the f-pawn can move to f3 or f4. Now, in accordance with the rule of thumb of this line, when White's queen moves Black takes on d4 and follows up with e5. }
9... Nxd4 { Luring the bishop to d4. } 10. Bxd4 e5
{ Gaining tempo and liberating the e6-square for the light-squared bishop. }
11. Be3 Be6
{ Black finished the development of his minor pieces and intends to continue with Rc8 and Qa5 to obtain play against White's castled king. }
12. O-O-O
{ Going pawn grabbing with  12.Qb5?!  Bd7  13.Qxb7  Rb8  14.Qxa7  Rxb2  isn't recommendable for White, as Black has good compensation because of a lack of safe shelter for White's king. }
12... Rc8
{ Black already threatens to take on c3 to wreck White's queenside structure and then on e4. This is more direct than the move  12...Nd7  that was played in the game Karpov-Andersson from the Turin tournament in 1982. }
13. f3
{ With this move White defends the pawn on e4, but the typical exchange sacrifice still gives Black great play. }
13... Rxc3
{ Even without getting a pawn for the exchange, this sacrifice is very promising for Black. }
14. bxc3 a6
{ Controlling the b5-square and preventing Qb5 @@StartBracket@@which would have happened had Black played the immediate Qa5@@EndBracket@@. Now Black wants to continue with Qa5, attacking both pawns on c3 and a2 followed by d5, attacking the pawn on e4 and opening the a3-f8 diagonal for the dark-squared bishop.   In case of exd5 Nxd5 the knight is also included in the attack. Black's has a long-term positional compensation, since White cannot solve the problems of his weak king and poor structure, which means that he can continue without forcing events and play to build up his threats. }
15. c4 { Controlling the d5-square and closing the a2-g8 diagonal. } 15... Qa5
{ Black continues with his plan and activates the queen. } 16. Kb1 O-O
{ An ambitious attempt. Black already has a perpetual after  16...Qb4  17.Ka1  Qc3  , but he can also play on. Now he intends to open the b-file with b5 and include the rook in the attack. }
17. Qd2 Qa4
{ From a4 the queen targets the rook on d1, in case White plays opens the 2nd rank with c3 to defend the a2-pawn with the queen. }
18. c3 b5
{ With very promising play on the queenside for Black as he will open the b-file by taking bxc4. Note the importance of the queen on a4. }
19. cxb5 Bxa2+ 20. Qxa2 Qxd1+ { When the rook on d1 is lost. } *

