[White "2. Keres Attack - Various 7th Moves"]
[Black "Keres Attack Various - 7.Bg2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. g4
{ The Keres Attack is White's most ambitious try against the Scheveningen. Black's last move closed the h3-c8 diagonal for the bishop on c8, so White uses that fact to advance the g-pawn immediately. }
6... h6 7. Bg2
{ This is a natural follow-up when moving the g-pawn, but in most cases this would transpose to thelines after 7.h3. }
7... Nc6
{ Black develops naturally, already threatening to take on d4 and push e5, attacking the g4-pawn twice. }
8. Nb3
{ White's best is  8.h3  , which transposes to theline starting with 7.h3. Note that White cannot develop the other bishop as  8.Be3?  Nxd4  9.Bxd4  e5  drops the pawn on g4.   Note that the capture on c6 only strengthens Black's centre after  8.Nxc6  bxc6  9.e5  Nd5  when the knight is on a safe and dominating position on d5. }
8... Be7 { Black continues the development. } 9. h3
{ This is possible, but it makes little sense. If White wanted to play h3, he would have played it earlier, without the need to remove the knight from the centralised d4-square. Now Black has more than one satisfactory way to develop. }
9... a6
{ Or  9...Bd7  @@StartBracket@@liberating the c8-square for the rook@@EndBracket@@  10.f4  Rc8  11.Be3  Na5  @@StartBracket@@intending Nc4@@EndBracket@@  12.Nxa5  Qxa5  with Bc6 and b5 to come. }
10. Be3 Nd7
{ Avoiding an attack on the knight after e5. A good alternative is  10...Bd7  , defending the knight on c6 and preparing b5. }
11. Qe2 Qc7
{ Developing the queen and defending the knight on c6. Black will follow up with b5 next. }
12. O-O-O b5
{ With a typical Sicilian position. Black will play b4 next @@StartBracket@@even if White plays a3@@EndBracket@@, to dislodge the knight from c3 @@StartBracket@@a general rule in the Sicilian is that Black should play b4 at the first opportunity@@EndBracket@@, or to open the b-file in case of  13.a3  b4  14.axb4  Nxb4  . }
*

