1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. g4
{ The Keres Attack is White's most ambitious try against the Scheveningen. Black's last move closed the h3-c8 diagonal for the bishop on c8, so White uses that fact to advance the g-pawn immediately. }
6... h6 7. Bg2
{ This is a natural follow-up when moving the g-pawn, but in most cases this would transpose to thelines after 7.h3. }
7... Nc6
{ Black develops naturally, already threatening to take on d4 and push e5, attacking the g4-pawn twice. }
8. Nb3
{ White's best is  8.h3  , which transposes to theline starting with 7.h3. Note that White cannot develop the other bishop as  8.Be3?  Nxd4  9.Bxd4  e5  drops the pawn on g4.   Note that the capture on c6 only strengthens Black's centre after  8.Nxc6  bxc6  9.e5  Nd5  when the knight is on a safe and dominating position on d5. }
8... Be7 { Black continues the development. } 9. h4
{ Not the happiest of continuations, but a characteristic one as it shows Black's potential. Going  9.Be3  allows  9...Ne5  with the threats of Nexg4 and Nc4, hitting both the bishop on e3 and the pawn on b2. }
9... d5
{ White is somewhat lagging back in development. His king in particular cannot be evacuated quickly, so Black sacrifices a pawn to open up the position. }
10. exd5
{ Taking the pawn @@StartBracket@@or opening the position without taking it@@EndBracket@@ can quickly backfire for White. }
10... Nxd5 { The usual recapture, opening the h4-d8 diagonal. } 11. Nxd5 exd5
12. Be3
{ After  12.Bxd5?!  O-O  White is in danger as Black threatens Bxg4 and also Re8.   Taking with the queen drops the pawn on g4, i.e.  12.Qxd5?!  Bxg4  . }
12... Be6
{ Preparing the development of the queen to d7, to attack the pawn on g4. The development of the bishop also liberates the c8-square for the rook from a8. }
13. Qe2 Qd7 { Attacking the pawn on g4. } 14. g5
{ If  14.Bf3?!  Ne5  Black wins the bishop pair as the bishop on f3 cannot move. }
14... Bg4
{ A disruptive move, forcing either f3 or Bf3, both of which diminish the harmony in White's position. }
15. Bf3
{ The alternative is worse  15.f3?!  Bf5  16.O-O-O  O-O  and with the ideas of Rac8, Bc2 and Nb4 Black's attack is crushing. }
15... Bxf3
{ Black naturally takes on f3 as going back would be a loss of tempo. } 16.
Qxf3 hxg5
{ Exchanging the rooks along the h-file forces the white queen to allow access to the f5 and g4-squares to the black counterpart. }
17. hxg5 Rxh1+ 18. Qxh1 Qg4 { Preventing long castling. } 19. Rd1 O-O-O
{ Black is perfectly fine here, in fact White should be a bit careful, although after... }
20. Rxd5 Bxg5
{ The position simplifies. Black exchanged the IQP on d5 for the pawn on g5. Note that White cannot take on g5. }
21. Bxg5 { Or  21.Rxg5?  Rd1#  . } 21... Qe6+ { The rook on d5 is lost. } *

