{ The Keres Attack is White's most ambitious try against the Scheveningen. Black's last move closed the h3-c8 diagonal for the bishop on c8, so White uses that fact to advance the g-pawn immediately. }
6... h6 7. g5
{ White opens the g-file immediately and this means that Black won't be able to castle short. }
7... hxg5 8. Bxg5 Nc6
{ Black develops naturally. His intention is to put pressure in the centre with Qb6. }
9. h4
{ Note that this position can also arise via the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3pp1/3ppn1p/8/3NP1P1/2N5/PPP2P1P/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.h4  Nc6  8.g5  hxg5  9.Bxg5  . }
9... Qb6 { Black drives away the centralised knight on d4. } 10. Nb3 Bd7
{ Black develops his queenside and liberates the c8-square for the rook. Since White's queen is still on d1, there is no point in playing Ne5 @@StartBracket@@like in theline starting with 9.Qd2@@EndBracket@@ because there is no threat of Nf3. }
11. Be2
{ After  11.Qd2  Black plays  11...Ne5  , threatening Nf3, when  12.Be2  Rc8  transposes  back to the line after11.Be2 Rc8 12.Qd2 Ne5.   The other queen move  11.Qe2  allows  11...Nd4!  forcing a favourable exchange of the knights. }
11... Rc8 { The rook is best-placed on the semi-open c-file. } 12. Qd2
{ Now that he has the f3-square covered, White moves the queen to d2 and prepares long castling. }
12... Ne5
{ Black plays the typical move @@StartBracket@@like in theline 9.Qd2@@EndBracket@@ with threats like Nc4 and Rxc3 followed by Nxe4. }
13. f3
{ Covering the e4-pawn and preventing ideas based on the sacrifice on c3 since Black now cannot follow up with Nxe4. }
13... a5
{ Black continues with his queenside play. Now he wants to harass the knight on b3 with the threat of a4. }
14. Be3
{ If White stops the a-pawn with  14.a4  then after  14...Nc4  15.Bxc4  Rxc4  Black has very good play on the c-file coupled with the exposed a4-pawn that needs constant attention by White. }
14... Qc7
{ Retreating to the usual square for the queen in the Sicilian, at the same time putting more pressure on the c-file. }
15. a4 { White stops a4, but weakens his queenside. } 15... Nc4
{ With this move Black wins the bishop pair but sacrifices the pawn on a5. }
16. Bxc4 Qxc4 17. Nxa5 Qb4
{ Black's compensation is considerable, as he is very active. } 18. Nb3 d5
{ White is on the defensive. A sample line is: } 19. exd5 Rxh4 20. Rxh4 Qxh4+
21. Qf2 Qxf2+ { The endgame is comfortable for Black. } 22. Bxf2 Nxd5
{ In the endgame the bishop pair guarantees Black good chances. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Keres Attack - Various 7th Moves"]
[Black "Keres Attack Various - 7.g5 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. g4
{ The Keres Attack is White's most ambitious try against the Scheveningen. Black's last move closed the h3-c8 diagonal for the bishop on c8, so White uses that fact to advance the g-pawn immediately. }
6... h6 7. g5
{ White opens the g-file immediately and this means that Black won't be able to castle short. }
7... hxg5 8. Bxg5 Nc6
{ Black develops naturally. His intention is to put pressure in the centre with Qb6. }
9. h4
{ Note that this position can also arise via the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3pp1/3ppn1p/8/3NP1P1/2N5/PPP2P1P/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.h4  Nc6  8.g5  hxg5  9.Bxg5  . }
9... Qb6 { Black drives away the centralised knight on d4. } 10. Nb3 Bd7
{ Black develops his queenside and liberates the c8-square for the rook. Since White's queen is still on d1, there is no point in playing Ne5 @@StartBracket@@like in theline starting with 9.Qd2@@EndBracket@@ because there is no threat of Nf3. }
11. Be2
{ After  11.Qd2  Black plays  11...Ne5  , threatening Nf3, when  12.Be2  Rc8  transposes  back to the line after11.Be2 Rc8 12.Qd2 Ne5.   The other queen move  11.Qe2  allows  11...Nd4!  forcing a favourable exchange of the knights. }
11... Rc8 { The rook is best-placed on the semi-open c-file. } 12. Qd2
{ Now that he has the f3-square covered, White moves the queen to d2 and prepares long castling. }
12... Ne5
{ Black plays the typical move @@StartBracket@@like in theline 9.Qd2@@EndBracket@@ with threats like Nc4 and Rxc3 followed by Nxe4. }
13. f3
{ Covering the e4-pawn and preventing ideas based on the sacrifice on c3 since Black now cannot follow up with Nxe4. }
13... a5
{ Black continues with his queenside play. Now he wants to harass the knight on b3 with the threat of a4. }
14. Be3
{ If White stops the a-pawn with  14.a4  then after  14...Nc4  15.Bxc4  Rxc4  Black has very good play on the c-file coupled with the exposed a4-pawn that needs constant attention by White. }
14... Qc7
{ Retreating to the usual square for the queen in the Sicilian, at the same time putting more pressure on the c-file. }
15. O-O-O a4
{ Black continues to advance the a-pawn to disrupt the coordination of White's pieces. }
16. Nb5 { This is an alternative, but Black gets great play. } 16... Bxb5
{ Taking the knight is forced. } 17. Bxb5+ Nfd7
{ Thanks to the threats against the knight on b3 and Nc4 Black has excellent play on the queenside. }
18. Nd4
{ Taking on c4 loses due to  18.Bxa4?  Nc4  followed  by Nxe3 when White cannot take on e3 because of the mate on c2. }
18... Nc4 { Black eliminates White's bishop pair. } 19. Bxc4 Qxc4 20. Kb1 g6
{ Helped by the fianchettoed bishop Black only increases his pressure on White's queenside. }
*

