[White "2. Keres Attack - Various 7th Moves"]
[Black "Keres Attack Various - 7.g5 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. g4
{ The Keres Attack is White's most ambitious try against the Scheveningen. Black's last move closed the h3-c8 diagonal for the bishop on c8, so White uses that fact to advance the g-pawn immediately. }
6... h6 7. g5
{ White opens the g-file immediately and this means that Black won't be able to castle short. }
7... hxg5 8. Bxg5 Nc6
{ Black develops naturally. His intention is to put pressure in the centre with Qb6. }
9. Qd2 { This is the most common move, preparing long castle. } 9... Qb6
{ Attacking both the knight on d4 and the pawn on b2. } 10. Nb3
{ The endgame after  10.O-O-O  Qxd4  11.Qxd4  Nxd4  12.Rxd4  a6  is somewhat better for Black thanks to his better structure. He will continue with Bd7-c6 and will play in the centre and the kingside where White has the isolated h-pawn. }
10... Ne5
{ An important move, immediately targeting the weakened square on f3. } 11. Qe2
{ This loses a tempo, but it is the most commonly played move move in the position. }
11... Be7
{ A precise move. Black wants to take advantage of the fact that the bishop on g5 is not defended. }
12. O-O-O Nd5
{ The key move, using the fact that the bishop on g5 is not defended. } 13. Bd2
{ White should preserve his dark-squared bishop. } 13... Nxc3
{ Black removes the attacked knight on d5 with tempo. } 14. Bxc3 Rh4
{ Preventing f4, which would dislodge the centralised knight. } 15. f3 Bd7
{ Black finishes the development and liberates the c8-square for the rook. The middlegame is complex, but Black has good chances in view of his harmonious development and a position without weaknesses. }
