[White "2. Keres Attack - Various 7th Moves"]
[Black "Keres Attack Various - 7.h3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. g4
{ The Keres Attack is White's most ambitious try against the Scheveningen. Black's last move closed the h3-c8 diagonal for the bishop on c8, so White uses that fact to advance the g-pawn immediately. }
6... h6 7. h3
{ The setup with an 'advanced' fianchetto became very popular against the Najdorf and this popularity switched to the Scheveningen as well, especially after the more direct lines with 7.h4 were largely neutralised. Apart from this one, White has several other setups he can try. }
7... Nc6 { The usual developing move for Black in the Scheveningen. } 8. Bg2
{ This is less precise because it abandons control over the c4-square. Black can use it to create counterplay, considering the problematic development of White's dark-squared bishop. Now with the bishop on g2 the threat is  8...--  9.Nxc6  bxc6  10.e5  , hitting the pawn on c6. Hence, Black defends the knight on c6. }
8... Bd7 { Not only defending the knight, but also preparing Rc8. } 9. f4
{ Preventing Ne5, but the knight can reach c4 via a5 as well. } 9... Rc8
{ Finishing the development of the queenside and targeting the c4-square in preparation for the maneuver Na5-c4. }
10. Nb3
{ Preventing Na5. In case of  10.Be3  Na5  with Nc4 next,  Black has a great game as White will have problems with the vulnerability of the bishop on e3 and the pawn on b2. }
10... Be7
{ Simply continuing development. A good alternative is the sharper  10...d5!?  with the idea  11.exd5  Nxd5  threatening to give a check on h4. Then the weak position of White's king will be good compensation for the sacrificed pawn. }
11. Be3 Na5
{ Apart from the threat of Nc4 Black liberates the c6-square for the bishop. Since White cannot allow Nc4 he must take on a5. }
12. Nxa5
{ Of course, taking on a7 is suicidal:  12.Bxa7?  Nc4  and Black threatens both Nxb2 and b6, trapping the bishop on a7. }
12... Qxa5 13. Qd2 Bc6
{ Black is comfortably placed and will continue with b5-b4 with typical queenside activity. Since this makes White's queenside come under pressure, White will castle short and Black will follow suit. }
