1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. g4
{ The Keres Attack is White's most ambitious try against the Scheveningen. Black's last move closed the h3-c8 diagonal for the bishop on c8, so White uses that fact to advance the g-pawn immediately. }
6... h6 7. h3
{ The setup with an 'advanced' fianchetto became very popular against the Najdorf and this popularity switched to the Scheveningen as well, especially after the more direct lines with 7.h4 were largely neutralised. Apart from this one, White has several other setups he can try. }
7... Nc6 { The usual developing move for Black in the Scheveningen. } 8. Be3
Be7
{ Black continues with his development. Similar tothe line 7.Rg1 Nc6 8.Be3 Be7 he waits for the development of White's queen in order to take on d4. }
9. Bg2 O-O
{ Black wants to start some play in the centre, so he tucks away the king. This is simpler than the alternative  9...Bd7  , which aims to play along the lines of8.Bg2 Bd7 but here Black has already played Be7 so he is one tempo short. Nevertheless, it is perfectly playable, for example  10.f4  Rc8  11.Qd2  Nxd4  12.Bxd4  b5  with counterplay. }
10. f4 { Black has more than one satisfactory reply to this expansion. } 10...
Nd7
{ Threatening Bh4. The alternatives are  10...e5  and  10...Nxd4  followed by e5. }
11. O-O Nxd4 { Luring a piece to d4 in order to attack it with e5. } 12. Qxd4
e5
{ The idea of this break is to take on f4 and obtain the e5-square for the knight. }
13. Qd2 exf4 14. Bxf4 Ne5
{ Black has great play here. He will finish development with Be6 and strategically aim to exchange the dark-squared bishops in order to obtain a good knight @@StartBracket@@on e5@@EndBracket@@ vs. a bad bishop @@StartBracket@@on g2@@EndBracket@@ position. With this in mind, he will be happy to exchange his light-squared bishop for the knight on c3 in case it jumps to d5. }
