{ The setup with an 'advanced' fianchetto became very popular against the Najdorf and this popularity switched to the Scheveningen as well, especially after the more direct lines with 7.h4 were largely neutralised. Apart from this one, White has several other setups he can try. }
7... Nc6 { The usual developing move for Black in the Scheveningen. } 8. Be3
Be7
{ Black continues with his development. Similar tothe line 7.Rg1 Nc6 8.Be3 Be7 he waits for the development of White's queen in order to take on d4. }
9. Bg2 O-O
{ Black wants to start some play in the centre, so he tucks away the king. This is simpler than the alternative  9...Bd7  , which aims to play along the lines of8.Bg2 Bd7 but here Black has already played Be7 so he is one tempo short. Nevertheless, it is perfectly playable, for example  10.f4  Rc8  11.Qd2  Nxd4  12.Bxd4  b5  with counterplay. }
10. Qd2 Nxd4
{ Forcing White to move again either with the bishop or with the queen. } 11.
Bxd4
{ Taking with the queen will likely transpose after  11.Qxd4  e5  12.Qd2  Bd7  . }
11... e5
{ Expanding in the centre and taking control of the dark-squares, especially d4 and f4. }
12. Be3 Bd7
{ Developing and supporting b5. There is nothing wrong with  12...a6  followed by b5 either. }
13. O-O-O
{ Otherwise White has nothing, for example  13.O-O  b5  followed by Qc7, Rc8, and b4 at some point if allowed. }
13... b5 { Threatening b4 with initiative on the queenside. } 14. Kb1
{ White cannot stop b4 as  14.a3?  is met by  14...a5  and b4 inevitably happens, this time with the bonus of opening the a-file. }
14... b4 { Black's play is simple. } 15. Nd5 Nxd5 16. Qxd5 Qc7
{ Black is obviously on the offensive here. His play flows smoothly with Be6, Rfc8, a5-a4-a3 or b3 with excellent prospects. }
