1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. g4
{ The Keres Attack is White's most ambitious try against the Scheveningen. Black's last move closed the h3-c8 diagonal for the bishop on c8, so White uses that fact to advance the g-pawn immediately. }
6... h6 7. h3
{ The setup with an 'advanced' fianchetto became very popular against the Najdorf and this popularity switched to the Scheveningen as well, especially after the more direct lines with 7.h4 were largely neutralised. Apart from this one, White has several other setups he can try. }
7... Nc6 { The usual developing move for Black in the Scheveningen. } 8. Be3
Be7
{ Black continues with his development. Similar tothe line 7.Rg1 Nc6 8.Be3 Be7 he waits for the development of White's queen in order to take on d4. }
9. Qd2 { The critical continuation. } 9... Nxd4
{ Now White must lose a tempo and move again with either the bishop or the queen. Both moves require serious attention. }
10. Qxd4 { This is equally good. } 10... a6
{ Covering the b5-square and preparing the queenside expansion with b5. The immediate  10...b5?!  is met by  11.Bb5  . }
11. O-O-O
{ In case of  11.Bg2  the move  11...e5!  is important  to blunt the bishop on g2. When the queen moves Black can continue with b5, for example  12.Qd2  b5  with easy play as the bishop on g2 is out of the game. }
11... b5
{ Black prepares the development of the bishop to b7. Gaining a tempo against the queen with  11...e5  is natural, but not optimal as after  12.Qd2  Be6  13.Kb1  Qa5  14.f3  Rc8  15.a3  White manages to consolidate the queenside as there no longer are any exchange sacrifices on c3. }
12. f4
{ Playing with  12.f3  is harmless as after  12...Bb7  Black plays d5 on the next move, solving all problems. }
12... Bb7
{ Finishing development and putting pressure on White's centre. Now White has a wide choice, but his best move isn't one that comes easily. }
13. Kb1
{ A typical move for White in the Sicilian, improving the position of the king and covering the a2-pawn. }
13... Nd7
{ An important move, taking the sting out of the g5-push. The knight also liberates the f6-square for the bishop. }
14. Rg1
{ Removing the rook from the long diagonal and intending g5 and/or f5. Note that the pawn on g7 is taboo in view of  14.Qxg7?  Bf6  , trapping the queen. }
14... Qc7
{ Black is now fully developed and will react depending on White's next move. }
15. f5
{ The alternative pawn push  15.g5?!  is not very good as after  15...hxg5  16.fxg5  Ne5  Black has an eternal knight on e5. }
15... Bf6 { A very good positional pawn sacrifice. The idea is visible after: }
16. Qxd6 Qxd6 17. Rxd6 Ke7 { Forcing the rook to move back. } 18. Rd1 Rac8
{ All Black's pieces are active and attacking White's centre, either directly @@StartBracket@@like the bishop on b7 hitting the pawn on e4@@EndBracket@@ or indirectly @@StartBracket@@like the bishop on f6 and the rook on c8 which attack the knight on c3, the defender of the e4-pawn@@EndBracket@@. }
19. Bg2 Bxc3 20. bxc3 e5
{ Black's compensation is obvious: the doubled pawns on the c-file make White's extra pawn irrelevant as they are only subject to attack; the bishop on g2 is extremely passive and Black has great play on the queenside and against the pawn on e4. }
