3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. g4
{ The Keres Attack is White's most ambitious try against the Scheveningen. Black's last move closed the h3-c8 diagonal for the bishop on c8, so White uses that fact to advance the g-pawn immediately. }
6... h6 7. h3
{ The setup with an 'advanced' fianchetto became very popular against the Najdorf and this popularity switched to the Scheveningen as well, especially after the more direct lines with 7.h4 were largely neutralised. Apart from this one, White has several other setups he can try. }
7... Nc6 { The usual developing move for Black in the Scheveningen. } 8. Be3
Be7
{ Black continues with his development. Similar tothe line 7.Rg1 Nc6 8.Be3 Be7 he waits for the development of White's queen in order to take on d4. }
9. Qd2 { The critical continuation. } 9... Nxd4
{ Now White must lose a tempo and move again with either the bishop or the queen. Both moves require serious attention. }
10. Bxd4 a6
{ Preparing the queenside expansion with b5, which will also allow for the development of the bishop on b7.   Again @@StartBracket@@as in theline after 10.Qxd4@@EndBracket@@ the natural move  10...e5  is insufficient because White manages to stabilise his queenside after  11.Be3  Be6  12.O-O-O  Qa5  13.f3  Rc8  14.a3  and the exchange sacrifice on c3 brings little. }
11. O-O-O
{ After  11.Bg2  b5  is possible as  12.Bxf6  Bxf6  13.e5  isn't dangerous in view of  13...Bg5  14.Qxd6  Qxd6  15.exd6  Rb8  when the pawn  on d6 will sooner or later fall and Black will remain with the pair of bishops. }
11... b5
{ The natural continuation. Now White has two principled plans: to play more actively with f4 or to strengthen the e4-pawn by f3 and prepare h4 and g5. }
12. f4
{ This gives Black more counterplay in view of the vulnerability of the e4-pawn. }
12... Bb7 { Continuing development and attacking the e4-pawn. } 13. Bg2 b4
{ Harassing the knight on c3 and indirectly fighting for the centre. } 14. Ne2
{ In case of  14.Na4  Qa5  15.b3  O-O  the knight on a5 can become problematic after Nd7 and Bc6. }
14... Qa5
{ The pawn on e4 can be taken, but not with  14...Nxe4?  15.Qe3  because this wins for White in view of the pin on the long diagonal.   Instead, Black should take with the bishop  14...Bxe4  which leads to a mess after  15.Bxf6  Bxg2  16.Bxg7  Rg8  17.Rh2  Bd5  .  The queen move is a multi-purpose move: the queen attacks the pawn on a2 but she also supports the e5-move. }
15. a3
{ Trying to take advantage of the pin. In case of  15.Kb1  e5  Black has good play as White has problems with the defence of the pawn on e4. }
15... e5
{ Playing for the attack. It is again possible to take on e4, e.g.  15...Nxe4  16.Qxb4  Qxb4  17.axb4  O-O  with a sharp endgame where Black's chances aren't inferior. }
16. Be3 Qb5
{ A good move that targets the knight on e2, thus preventing Qxb4 as the queen would leave the knight without defence. At the same time, Black threatens to take on a3, so White's next is forced. }
17. axb4 a5
{ Black wants to open the a-file for his attack. White is under pressure here as in addition to the hanging pawn on e4 he must also think of the defence of his king. }
