11. Nxc6
{ White prevents Black's idea by exchanging the knight that was supposed to land on e5, for example after  11.Nb3  exf4  12.Bxf4  Ne5  . Jumping to f5 is met by the usual reaction of @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp1bbppp/2np1n2/4p3/3NPP2/P1NQB3/1PP1B1PP/R3K2R w KQ - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Nf5  Bxf5  12.exf5  d5  with good play. }
11... bxc6 12. O-O-O Ng4 { Black can also play  12...Qc7  followed by Rfd8. }
13. Bxg4 Bxg4 14. Rd2 Qa5 15. f5 { White cannot play this move in view of: }
15... d5 16. exd5 Bxa3 { With a devastating attack. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Classical Variation - 6.Be2"]
[Black "Classical Variation 6.Be2 Nc6 7.Be3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. Be2
{ This classical development is always a solid option for White in the Open Sicilian. When choosing this line White usually seeks more positional play, but there are also more aggressive plans. }
6... Nc6
{ Black can also start with  6...Be7  . In all except one line, his next two moves will be Nc6 and O-O so we would have a transposition. }
7. Be3
{ With this move order we will explore some more aggressive plans for White in which he aims to castle long and/or push his kingside pawns. }
7... Be7 { Black continues along the usual lines. } 8. a3
{ An extremely unlikely move, but after... } 8... O-O 9. Qd3
{ We have a position that was played at the Candidates tournament in one of the crucial games of the event between Caruana and Giri. }
9... Bd7
{ Black finishes development of the minor pieces and waits for f4 when he can reply with the typical counter-thrust e5. }
10. f4
{ In case of  10.O-O-O  Ne5  11.Qd2  Nfg4  Black wins the bishop pair as the bishop on e3 cannot move since the pawn on f2 is hanging. }
10... e5
{ The typical central break whose idea is to obtain the e5-square for the knight. }
11. Nxc6
{ White prevents Black's idea by exchanging the knight that was supposed to land on e5, for example after  11.Nb3  exf4  12.Bxf4  Ne5  . Jumping to f5 is met by the usual reaction of @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp1bbppp/2np1n2/4p3/3NPP2/P1NQB3/1PP1B1PP/R3K2R w KQ - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Nf5  Bxf5  12.exf5  d5  with good play. }
11... bxc6 12. O-O { This was Caruana's choice. } 12... exf4
{ Black has good alternatives in  12...Qc7  and  12...a5  , keeping the tension in the centre. }
13. Bxf4 Bg4
{ An improvement over the game Caruana-Giri where Black played the typical  13...Be6  but after  14.Qg3  followed by Rad1 he was under some pressure. With the move Bg4 Black plays for a quick d5. }
14. Rad1 { In case of  14.Bxg4  Nxg4  the knight will land on e5 next. } 14...
Bxe2
{ Forcing White to take with knight, easing his control over the d5-square. }
15. Nxe2 { In case of  15.Qxe2  Qb6  Black will collect the pawn on b2. } 15...
d5
{ Solving all problems with this liberating push. Going after the pawn on b2 is dubious as after  15...Qb6  16.Be3  Qxb2  17.Nd4  with Nf5 to come White has a dangerous attack. }
16. exd5 Nxd5 { Taking with the queen is equally good. } 17. Bc1 Bg5
{ Exchanging the dark-squared bishop weakens the pawn on b2 and the e3-square, which gives Black some tactical opportunities. The position is equal, Black's activity compensates for the isolated pawn on c6. }
*

