[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Classical Variation - 6.Be2"]
[Black "Classical Variation 6.Be2 Nc6 7.Be3 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. Be2
{ This classical development is always a solid option for White in the Open Sicilian. When choosing this line White usually seeks more positional play, but there are also more aggressive plans. }
6... Nc6
{ Black can also start with  6...Be7  . In all except one line, his next two moves will be Nc6 and O-O so we would have a transposition. }
7. Be3
{ With this move order we will explore some more aggressive plans for White in which he aims to castle long and/or push his kingside pawns. }
7... Be7 { Black continues along the usual lines. } 8. Qd2
{ White wants to castle long before deciding which pawn to push forward. } 8...
e5
{ This is the only line where Black doesn't follow up with short castle. It is important to play this move immediately. The reason lies in the fact that after  8...O-O  9.O-O-O  e5?!  White can play  10.Nf5  and after  10...Bxf5  11.exf5  Black cannot push d5, because with a rook on d1 White has sufficient control over the d5-square. }
9. Nb3 { The only reasonable move. } 9... a5
{ Black saves time on castling and intends to harass the knight on b3 immediately. }
10. Nd5 { This jump transforms the structure in the centre. } 10... Nxd5
{ Taking the pawn on e4 is risky, but possible. For example  10...Nxe4!?  11.Qd3  Nc5  12.Nxc5  dxc5  13.Nxe7  Qxe7  when White has the pair of bishops while Black has the extra pawn and strong control over the d4-square. The capture on d5 is simpler because it gives Black a solid position with a clear plan how to play. }
11. exd5 Nb8
{ The knight is flexible on b8. It can go to d7 and from there either to c5 @@StartBracket@@after some preparation@@EndBracket@@ or f6. An additional route for the knight can be via a6. }
12. Bb5+ Nd7
{ Black avoids the exchange of the light-squared bishops, seeing that his bishop is the better one. Strategically speaking, Black wants to avoid having only the dark-squared bishops on the board because his own is limited by the pawns on d6 and e5. }
13. a4
{ Fixing the structure on the queenside. Now White has a grip on the light squares, but this gives Black control over the dark squares, the c5-square in particular. }
13... O-O { Getting the king to safety and unpinning the knight on d7. } 14.
O-O-O { This is better than the tame  14.O-O  . } 14... Nf6
{ The knight threatens to come to g4 and capture the bishop on e3. } 15. f3
{ Controlling the g4-square. } 15... Bd7
{ A few moves earlier Black didn't want to exchange the light-squared bishops, but the situation changed with the white king on the queenside: the bishop on b5 securely defends against any Black activity on the queenside, so exchanging it will allow Black to be more active there. }
16. Qd3 Qc7
{ This is more complex. The simpler solution is to go for the exchanges with  16...Bxb5  17.Qxb5  Qd7  18.Qxd7  Nxd7  with the idea of Rfb8 and b5 on the queenside and f5 and Bf6 on the kingside and centre. }
17. Nd2 Rfc8
{ Threatening Nxd5. Black has a compact and promising position. After the exchange of the light-squared bishops he can reroute his knight via d7 to c5 to target the pawn on a4. At the same time he will also expand with f5 and play Bf6, threatening to open the long diagonal with a timely e4. This kingside expansion will also be useful for the endgame, when playing g5, h5 etc. will activate Black's majority on that side of the board. }
*

