{ With this move order we will explore some more aggressive plans for White in which he aims to castle long and/or push his kingside pawns. }
7... Be7 { Black continues along the usual lines. } 8. Qd2
{ White wants to castle long before deciding which pawn to push forward. } 8...
e5
{ This is the only line where Black doesn't follow up with short castle. It is important to play this move immediately. The reason lies in the fact that after  8...O-O  9.O-O-O  e5?!  White can play  10.Nf5  and after  10...Bxf5  11.exf5  Black cannot push d5, because with a rook on d1 White has sufficient control over the d5-square. }
9. Nb3 { The only reasonable move. } 9... a5
{ Black saves time on castling and intends to harass the knight on b3 immediately. }
10. Nd5 { This jump transforms the structure in the centre. } 10... Nxd5
{ Taking the pawn on e4 is risky, but possible. For example  10...Nxe4!?  11.Qd3  Nc5  12.Nxc5  dxc5  13.Nxe7  Qxe7  when White has the pair of bishops while Black has the extra pawn and strong control over the d4-square. The capture on d5 is simpler because it gives Black a solid position with a clear plan how to play. }
11. exd5 Nb8
{ The knight is flexible on b8. It can go to d7 and from there either to c5 @@StartBracket@@after some preparation@@EndBracket@@ or f6. An additional route for the knight can be via a6. }
12. Bb5+ Nd7
{ Black avoids the exchange of the light-squared bishops, seeing that his bishop is the better one. Strategically speaking, Black wants to avoid having only the dark-squared bishops on the board because his own is limited by the pawns on d6 and e5. }
13. a4
{ Fixing the structure on the queenside. Now White has a grip on the light squares, but this gives Black control over the dark squares, the c5-square in particular. }
13... O-O 14. O-O { White invites Black's kingside expansion. } 14... f5 15. f4
{ The only move, as  15.f3?!  f4  16.Bf2  gives Black a tremendous attack after  16...g5  followed by Rf7-g7, Nf6 and g4. }
15... Nf6
{ The knight aims for the e4-square that can no longer be controlled by a pawn. Note that  15...e4?  would be a strategical mistake as it kills off all Black's play and it gives away the d4-square to White. }
16. c4
{ White's majority is on the queenside, so he needs to move it forward. After  16.fxe5?!  dxe5  Black's pawn pair on e5 and f5 is much more mobile than White's pawns on the d- and c-files. }
16... Ne4 17. Qd3 exf4 { Opening the long diagonal for the bishop. } 18. Bxf4
Bf6 { Black has good play here. A sample line goes: } 19. Nd4 Nc5 20. Qd1 g5
{ This is a typical expansion on the kingside for Black. } 21. Be3 f4 22. Bf2
g4 { With a promising attack on the kingside. } *

