[White "3. Classical Variation - 6.Be2"]
[Black "Classical Variation 6.Be2 Nc6 7.Be3 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. Be2
{ This classical development is always a solid option for White in the Open Sicilian. When choosing this line White usually seeks more positional play, but there are also more aggressive plans. }
6... Nc6
{ Black can also start with  6...Be7  . In all except one line, his next two moves will be Nc6 and O-O so we would have a transposition. }
7. Be3
{ With this move order we will explore some more aggressive plans for White in which he aims to castle long and/or push his kingside pawns. }
7... Be7 { Black continues along the usual lines. } 8. Qd2
{ White wants to castle long before deciding which pawn to push forward. } 8...
e5
{ This is the only line where Black doesn't follow up with short castle. It is important to play this move immediately. The reason lies in the fact that after  8...O-O  9.O-O-O  e5?!  White can play  10.Nf5  and after  10...Bxf5  11.exf5  Black cannot push d5, because with a rook on d1 White has sufficient control over the d5-square. }
9. Nb3
{ The only reasonable move. Now  9.Nf5?  is bad as after  9...Bxf5  10.exf5  d5  Black  has an overwhelming position with d4 coming next. }
9... a5
{ Black saves time on castling and intends to harass the knight on b3 immediately. }
10. a4
{ The most natural reply, as allowing a4 forces the knight on b3 to go all the way back to c1, for example  10.Rd1  a4  11.Nc1  a3  12.b3  Be6  with Qa5 and O-O next with very comfortable position for Black. The knight on c1 is severely restricted. }
10... Be6
{ Black develops naturally. Now with the white a-pawn on a4 a capture on b3 is a possibility as it would force cxb3, worsening White's queenside structure. }
11. O-O-O
{ The more aggressive approach. Castling short is harmless as after  11.O-O  O-O  Black will use the b4-square for his knight and ideas like Nb4, Rc8 @@StartBracket@@putting pressure on the c-file and the c2-pawn in particular@@EndBracket@@ and d5 make his position easy to play.   Note that the move  11.f4  transposes after  11...O-O  12.O-O-O  Qc8  , as playing @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/1p2bppp/2npbn2/p3p3/P3P3/1NN1B3/1PPQBPPP/R3K2R w KQkq - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11.f4  O-O  12.f5  is premature in view of  12...Bxb3  13.cxb3  Rc8  with ideas like Nb4 and d5. }
11... O-O
{ Black finishes development. Now he has easy moves to make on the queenside: Nb4, Rc8 and possibly d5. }
12. f4 { White must advance sooner rather than later. } 12... Qc8
{ A subtle move that places a heavy piece on the c-file and liberates the d8-square for the rook at the same time. This latter factor will be important in case White exchanges on e5 and the d-file is opened. An additional idea of the move Rd8 is to support the d5-push. }
13. f5 { This is direct and natural, but Black is prepared. } 13... Bxb3
{ The only plausible move. } 14. cxb3 Nb4
{ The knight is untouchable on b4. Now Black threatens d5. } 15. Kb1
{ Sensibly removing the king from the open file. The naive  15.Bc4?  illustrates Black's attacking potential after  15...b5!  16.axb5  a4!  with strong attack. }
15... d5 { Opening the position in the centre. } 16. exd5 Qxf5+
{ Black's control over the light squares in the vicinity of White's king is annoying, so White should seek to neutralise it. }
17. Bd3 Nxd3 { Now after the exchanges... } 18. Qxd3 Qxd3+ 19. Rxd3 Bb4
{ The bishop slots in nicely on b4. Black has a great endgame with a better structure and a mobile central majority. }
