{ The usual central advance is even more justified here as it fixes the pawn on e4 and in doing so limits the scope of the bishop on f3. }
10. Nxc6
{ This is White's best, but obviously not threatening. Being aggressive is bad, as  10.Nf5?  Bxf5  11.exf5  exf4  12.Bxf4  d5  with the idea of d4 Black takes over the initiative. }
10... bxc6 11. fxe5 dxe5 12. Qxd8 Rxd8
{ The endgame is comfortable for Black. He has easy play with Rb8, a5 @@StartBracket@@to remove the pawn from the targeted square on a7@@EndBracket@@, Be6 and so on. }
