[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Classical Variation - 6.Be2"]
[Black "Classical Variation 6.Be2 Nc6 7.Be3 #12"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. Be2
{ This classical development is always a solid option for White in the Open Sicilian. When choosing this line White usually seeks more positional play, but there are also more aggressive plans. }
6... Nc6
{ Black can also start with  6...Be7  . In all except one line, his next two moves will be Nc6 and O-O so we would have a transposition. }
7. Be3
{ With this move order we will explore some more aggressive plans for White in which he aims to castle long and/or push his kingside pawns. }
7... Be7 { Black continues along the usual lines. } 8. f4 O-O
{ Black finishes development and on the next move will strike in the centre. }
9. Qd2
{ Preparing long castle. The alternatives @@StartBracket@@except  9.O-O  , which would lead to a transposition to thelines after 7.O-O@@EndBracket@@ are harmless and can even land White in trouble. }
9... e5 { The typical central thrust works well here. } 10. Nb3
{ Apart from  10.Nf3  this is the other critical move.   Note that going to f3 is the worst option, as the knight blocks the f-file, so after the typical reaction by Black after  10.Nf3  exf4  11.Bxf4  Be6  he has great play - the knight on f3 just stands in the way. }
10... a5 { Black immediately threatens to harass the knight on b3. } 11. a4
{ White cannot really allow a4 as the knight has no good squares to go to. }
11... Nb4
{ Landing on the weakened b4-square. After White's last move the knight cannot be chased away with a3 while c3 is impossible to organise. Black has a sharp alternative in  11...Be6  inviting  12.f5  Bxb3  13.cxb3  and now either the sharper  13...Nxe4!?  or the calmer  13...Rc8  , both of which lead to unclear play. }
12. O-O { This doesn't pose problems. } 12... Be6
{ Black develops naturally. He intends ...Rc8 next. } 13. f5
{ Trying to take advantage of Black's last move, but now Black can strike in the centre. }
13... Bxb3 { Of course, Black doesn't waste time retreating. } 14. cxb3 d5
{ The liberating push, easily equalising. } 15. exd5 Nbxd5 16. Nxd5 Nxd5
{ Black will exchange the knight for bishop on the next move since White cannot really avoid it. }
17. Bf2 Nf4
{ Now the bishop on e2 will be exchanged, eliminating White's only advantage in the position, that of the bishop pair. Then Black can boast the better pawn structure in this objectively equal position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Classical Variation - 6.Be2"]
[Black "Classical Variation 6.Be2 Nc6 7.Be3 #13"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. Be2
{ This classical development is always a solid option for White in the Open Sicilian. When choosing this line White usually seeks more positional play, but there are also more aggressive plans. }
6... Nc6
{ Black can also start with  6...Be7  . In all except one line, his next two moves will be Nc6 and O-O so we would have a transposition. }
7. Be3
{ With this move order we will explore some more aggressive plans for White in which he aims to castle long and/or push his kingside pawns. }
7... Be7 { Black continues along the usual lines. } 8. f4 O-O
{ Black finishes development and on the next move will strike in the centre. }
9. Qd2
{ Preparing long castle. The alternatives @@StartBracket@@except  9.O-O  , which would lead to a transposition to thelines after 7.O-O@@EndBracket@@ are harmless and can even land White in trouble. }
9... e5 { The typical central thrust works well here. } 10. Nb3
{ Apart from  10.Nf3  this is the other critical move.   Note that going to f3 is the worst option, as the knight blocks the f-file, so after the typical reaction by Black after  10.Nf3  exf4  11.Bxf4  Be6  he has great play - the knight on f3 just stands in the way. }
10... a5 { Black immediately threatens to harass the knight on b3. } 11. a4
{ White cannot really allow a4 as the knight has no good squares to go to. }
11... Nb4
{ Landing on the weakened b4-square. After White's last move the knight cannot be chased away with a3 while c3 is impossible to organise. Black has a sharp alternative in  11...Be6  inviting  12.f5  Bxb3  13.cxb3  and now either the sharper  13...Nxe4!?  or the calmer  13...Rc8  , both of which lead to unclear play. }
12. O-O-O { The sharper choice. } 12... Qc7
{ The queen is developed on the c-file where White's king is. From c7 she can also come to c6, attacking the pawns on e4 and a4. }
13. Kb1 { Removing the king from the sensitive c-file. } 13... Be6
{ Black is fully developed now, with the rooks connected, and doesn't fear White's possible advance with f5. }
14. f5 Nxe4
{ A great resource that gives Black very strong initiative. Here  14...Bxb3?  is bad as after  15.cxb3  Black cannot follow it up with the opening of the game with d5 and White can consolidate his light-square dominance with Rc1 and Bc4. }
15. Nxe4 Bxf5
{ But now it is Black who is attacking on the light squares. The immediate threat is d5, hitting the vulnerable pawn on c2. }
16. Bd3 { Threatening Nf6 to gain the bishop pair. } 16... Qd7
{ Defending against Nf6 by defending the bishop on f5 and reinforcing the threat of d5. Notice also that the pawn on a4 is hanging. }
17. g4
{ Trying to disrupt Black's coordination and liberating the g2-square for the queen from where she can defend the knight on e4. }
17... Bg6 { Keeping all threats. } 18. Qg2 Qc6
{ Introducing another pin. The immediate  18...d5?  is premature in view of  19.Nec5  . }
19. Rhg1 { Defending the queen. } 19... d5
{ Black finally pushes in the centre and now regains the invested material. }
20. Nc3
{ Defending the pawn on a4, which can be safely taken in case of  20.Ng3?  Qxa4  . }
20... Bxd3 { Exchanging on d3 before forking with d4. } 21. Rxd3 d4
{ Black regains the material and an equal position ensues. If Black prefers murky play he can try  21...Nxd3  22.Nxd5  Bh4  23.cxd3  Rad8  with a messy position. }
22. Qxc6
{ Or  22.Nxd4  exd4  23.Rxd4  Bc5  and the position equalises after the ensuing exchange of the bishops. }
22... Nxc6 23. Bxd4 exd4 24. Nb5 f5
{ With this move Black activates the rook by opening the f-file. The endgame is equal when White captures the pawn on d4, though Black can try to make better use of his bishop in an open position. }
