1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. Be2
{ This classical development is always a solid option for White in the Open Sicilian. When choosing this line White usually seeks more positional play, but there are also more aggressive plans. }
6... Nc6
{ Black can also start with  6...Be7  . In all except one line, his next two moves will be Nc6 and O-O so we would have a transposition. }
7. Be3
{ With this move order we will explore some more aggressive plans for White in which he aims to castle long and/or push his kingside pawns. }
7... Be7 { Black continues along the usual lines. } 8. f4 O-O
{ Black finishes development and on the next move will strike in the centre. }
9. Qd2
{ Preparing long castle. The alternatives @@StartBracket@@except  9.O-O  , which would lead to a transposition to thelines after 7.O-O@@EndBracket@@ are harmless and can even land White in trouble. }
9... e5 { The typical central thrust works well here. } 10. Nf3
{ This retreat is preferred by the engines. } 10... Ng4
{ Black goes after the important dark-squared bishop. } 11. Nd5
{ Even though natural, taking the central square brings nothing. } 11... Nxe3
{ Black eliminates the dark-squared bishop. } 12. Qxe3 Qa5+
{ An important check that helps prevent White's long castle in view of the fact that the pawn on a2 would hang. }
13. c3 exf4
{ This allows for the free development of the bishop on e6, not fearing f5. But even allowing f5 is possible, for example  13...Be6  14.Nxe7  Nxe7  15.f5  Bd7  with f6 next when Black has the better bishop and the plan of Bc6 and d5 or b5 with the usual queenside play. }
14. Qxf4 Be6 { Finishing development and threatening to take on d5. } 15. Nxe7+
{ White goes after the pawn on d6 but this allows Black great compensation. After  15.Bc4  Qc5  with b5-b4 next Black has excellent play on the queenside in addition to the unsettled position of the white king. }
15... Nxe7 16. Qxd6 Nc6 { Threatening to harass the queen with Rfd8. } 17. Qd3
{ Going to g3 isn't any better,  17.Qg3  Qa4!  with the idea of Qc2 is more than sufficient. }
17... Qb6
{ Black's compensation consists of his activity on the weakened dark squares in White's camp. This is also shown with the fact that White cannot hide his king safely. For example, here long castle loses: }
18. O-O-O Rfd8 { The white queen cannot protect everything. } 19. Qc2
{ Or  19.Qb5  Qe3  20.Rd2  Rxd2  21.Nxd2  Rd8  with Bxa2 next White's position is on the verge of collapse. }
19... Nb4 20. cxb4 Rdc8 { Winning the queen. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Classical Variation - 6.Be2"]
[Black "Classical Variation 6.Be2 Nc6 7.Be3 #18"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. Be2
{ This classical development is always a solid option for White in the Open Sicilian. When choosing this line White usually seeks more positional play, but there are also more aggressive plans. }
6... Nc6
{ Black can also start with  6...Be7  . In all except one line, his next two moves will be Nc6 and O-O so we would have a transposition. }
7. Be3
{ With this move order we will explore some more aggressive plans for White in which he aims to castle long and/or push his kingside pawns. }
7... Be7 { Black continues along the usual lines. } 8. f4 O-O
{ Black finishes development and on the next move will strike in the centre. }
9. Qd2
{ Preparing long castle. The alternatives @@StartBracket@@except  9.O-O  , which would lead to a transposition to thelines after 7.O-O@@EndBracket@@ are harmless and can even land White in trouble. }
9... e5 { The typical central thrust works well here. } 10. Nf3
{ This retreat is preferred by the engines. } 10... Ng4
{ Black goes after the important dark-squared bishop. } 11. Bg1
{ The principled retreat. In case of  11.fxe5?!  dxe5  White only worsened his own structure @@StartBracket@@leaving him with a sole pawn island on e4@@EndBracket@@ and improved Black's @@StartBracket@@eliminating the backward pawn on d6@@EndBracket@@.   Note that in case of  11.O-O-O  exf4  12.Bg1  @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2bppp/2np4/8/4Ppn1/2N1BN2/PPPQB1PP/2KR3R w - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Bxf4?  Nf2  loses the exchange@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2bppp/2np4/8/4Ppn1/2N2N2/PPPQB1PP/2KR2BR b - - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Bf6  we have a transposition to the text. }
11... exf4
{ The typical move, though Black has a more complex option in  11...f5!?  with complications that are quite acceptable for him, for example after  12.fxe5  fxe4  13.Nxe4  d5  with Be6 and Ngxe5 next. }
12. O-O-O
{ Taking the pawn immediately  12.Qxf4?!  Bf6!  only speeds up Black's counterplay with the threats of Bxc3 and Re8. }
12... Bf6 { Black activates his dark-squared bishop. } 13. Nd5
{ With a knight on c3 White cannot take  13.Qxf4  without allowing a wrecking of his queenside structure with  13...Bxc3  . }
13... Re8 { Developing the rook with tempo, attacking the pawn on e4. } 14.
Qxf4 Be6
{ Black finished development and the middlegame is quite complex. White has control over the light squares, the knight on d5, in particular, emphasises this fact, so Black would like to exchange it. Black on the other hand controls the dark squares, the e5-square in particular. Both sides have isolated pawns, on e4 and d6 and they are both subject to attack. }
15. Nxf6+
{ This is an attempt to take the pawn on d6, so it's important to see how Black reacts. }
15... Nxf6 { The knight comes back to f6 to exert pressure on the pawn on e4. }
16. Rxd6 Qa5
{ Black has excellent play even after the modest  16...Qc7  17.e5  Nd7  with Rac8 next and the pawn on e5 under attack. }
17. a3 Nxe4 { A very nice tactic based on the weakness of the g2-pawn! } 18.
Qxe4 Bh3
{ This is the idea of Black's combination. Now White manages not to lose the exchange but remains a pawn down after: }
19. Qf4 Bxg2 20. Bc4 Re7 21. Bb6 { Liberating the rook on h1 with tempo. }
21... Qxb6 22. Rhd1
{ And now the simplest is to take on f3 and offer further exchanges. } 22...
Bxf3 { The alternative is  22...Qf2  which is also quite good. } 23. Qxf3 Rd8
{ When White has no compensation for the pawn. } *

