{ Black finished development and the middlegame is quite complex. White has control over the light squares, the knight on d5, in particular, emphasises this fact, so Black would like to exchange it. Black on the other hand controls the dark squares, the e5-square in particular. Both sides have isolated pawns, on e4 and d6 and they are both subject to attack. }
15. h3
{ Chasing away the knight only allows Black to place it where he wants to. }
15... Bxd5 { Eliminating the knight first is important. } 16. Rxd5 Nge5
{ Landing on the ideal spot on e5. Black has a very solid position here. } 17.
Qd2 Qc7 { Planning Rad8. } 18. Rxd6 { Taking the pawn is not good. } 18... Rad8
{ Black's compensation is very strong. } 19. Rxd8
{ Going to d5, which is good in the analogousline starting with 15.Kb1, doesn't work here after  19.Rd5?  Rxd5  20.exd5  Nxf3  followed by Qe5 with the devastating threats of Qxb2 and Bg5. }
19... Rxd8 20. Qe1 Rc8
{ The threats on the c-file give Black a big advantage. } *

