[White "3. Classical Variation - 6.Be2"]
[Black "Classical Variation 6.Be2 Nc6 7.O-O #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. Be2
{ This classical development is always a solid option for White in the Open Sicilian. When choosing this line White usually seeks more positional play, but there are also more aggressive plans. }
6... Nc6
{ Black can also start with  6...Be7  . In all except one line, his next two moves will be Nc6 and O-O so we would have a transposition. }
7. O-O
{ The most common move, fully in line with the development with Be2, which seeks calmer play. }
7... Be7 { Black continues development and will castle next. } 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9.
Qd3 { This is a rare idea, the point being transferring the queen to g3. } 9...
O-O
{ Black castles and will remove the king to h8 on the next move to avoid any problems on the g-file. }
10. Qg3 Kh8 { Avoiding Bh6. } 11. b3
{ In case of  11.e5  dxe5  12.Qxe5  Bd6  with Qc7, Rb8 and Nd5 to come Black has rich piece play. The advance @@StartFEN@@r1bq1r1k/p3bppp/2pppn2/8/4P3/2N3Q1/PPP1BPPP/R1B2RK1 w - - 4 11@@EndFEN@@  11.f4  should be met by  11...d5  12.e5  Nd7  with easy play after c5, Rb8 etc. }
11... e5
{ Black takes advantage of the pawn on c6 that covers the d5-square, so he can advance with the e-pawn. }
12. f4 { The only way for White to create active play. } 12... Nd7
{ Black prepares for the exchange of the pawns on e5 and f4 and brings the knight to d7 so that it can occupy the e5-square once that exchange occurs. }
13. f5
{ This is rather harmless as, without the central tension, it is easy for Black to develop. }
13... Bb7
{ Developing the bishop on the long diagonal also supports the d5-push. } 14.
Bf3 Nf6 { The knight also supports the d5-push. } 15. Bb2 d5
{ This temporary pawn sacrifice is the most direct way. Black can keep the pawn structure intact and maneuver if he wishes so, for example  15...Qc7  followed by bringing the rooks to the central files. }
16. exd5 cxd5 17. Qxe5 Bd6 { Activating the bishop. } 18. Qd4 Re8
{ Now with the ideas of Be5 and Qc7 Black will regain the pawn as White cannot defend both pawns on h2 and c2. }
*

