[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Classical Variation - 6.Be2"]
[Black "Classical Variation 6.Be2 Nc6 7.O-O #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. Be2
{ This classical development is always a solid option for White in the Open Sicilian. When choosing this line White usually seeks more positional play, but there are also more aggressive plans. }
6... Nc6
{ Black can also start with  6...Be7  . In all except one line, his next two moves will be Nc6 and O-O so we would have a transposition. }
7. O-O
{ The most common move, fully in line with the development with Be2, which seeks calmer play. }
7... Be7 { Black continues development and will castle next. } 8. f4 O-O 9. Kh1
{ White postpones the development of the dark-squared bishop, but Black can take advantage of that fact. }
9... Nxd4
{ Here the usual central push is not optimal as after  9...e5  White can play  10.Nf3!  followed by Bd3, Qe1-g3 and so on.   The point is that with the bishop still on c1 Black would rather not take on f4 to allow Bc1xf4 in one go, but without that capture White has chances to develop an activity on the kingside with the queen transfer to g3 and possibly f5. With the exchange of the knights on the other hand, Black prepares a quick development of the light-squared bishop. }
10. Qxd4 b6 { On the next move Black will be practically fully mobilised. } 11.
Bf3 { In case of  11.f5  exf5  12.exf5  d5  Black has free play. } 11... Bb7
{ Black is now ready to play in the centre, with his plan to push d5. } 12. Be3
{ The most natural move. White can easily become worse if he rushes with central play, for example,  12.e5?  Bxf3  13.Rxf3  dxe5  14.Qxe5  Rc8  as in the game Gurevich-Kasparov played online in 1998 when Black was already better thanks to his development advantage and pressure down the c-file. }
12... d5
{ The most direct approach. Black can postpone this push with  12...Qc8  followed by Rd8 and then d5. }
13. e5
{ In case of  13.exd5  Nxd5  14.Nxd5  Bxd5  15.Bxd5  exd5  there is full equality on the board, as in the game Dimitrov-Leko from Ulcinj in 1997. }
13... Ne4
{ The knight is strong on this central square and it is not favourable for White to exchange it because after  14.Nxe4  dxe4  the pawn on e4 will be at least as annoying. }
14. Qd3 Qc8
{ Threatening Ba6 to activate the bishop and liberating the d8-square for the rook. Black has a very solid and comfortable position. }
*

