1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. Be2
{ This classical development is always a solid option for White in the Open Sicilian. When choosing this line White usually seeks more positional play, but there are also more aggressive plans. }
6... Nc6
{ Black can also start with  6...Be7  . In all except one line, his next two moves will be Nc6 and O-O so we would have a transposition. }
7. O-O
{ The most common move, fully in line with the development with Be2, which seeks calmer play. }
7... Be7 { Black continues development and will castle next. } 8. Be3
{ The usual development of the dark-squared bishop. White can also try a couple of other ideas. }
8... O-O { Black finishes the development of the kingside. } 9. Qd2
{ White connects the rooks and waits with f4. } 9... e5
{ The typical central push works well here. Black forces the knight from d4 away from the centre and liberates the e6-square for the development of the light-squared bishop. }
10. Nf3 h6
{ Black intends Be6, but first he takes control over the g5-square in order to avoid an attack on the bishop with Ng5. }
11. Bc4
{ In case of  11.Rfd1  Be6  Black has comfortable development and will continue with a6 and b5 because White cannot conveniently prevent it with a4 since then the b4-square will be weakened and the knight from c6 will nicely slot in there. }
11... Be6 { Black fights for the d5-square. } 12. Bd5
{ In case of  12.Bb3  Na5  Black wants to eliminate the light-squared bishop or to jump to c4, while after @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp2bpp1/2npbn1p/4p3/2B1P3/2N1BN2/PPPQ1PPP/R4RK1 w - - 2 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Bxe6  fxe6  the pawn on e6 controls the important light squared d5 and f5, giving Black free hands to play on the queenside in the usual manner with a6, b5 etc or even on the kingside, for example by Nh5-f4. }
12... Bxd5
{ This is the simplest. Black can also keep the tension in the centre with moves like  12...Qd7  and  12...Rc8  . }
13. exd5 Nb8
{ The knight will come to d7 and now Black's plan is clear: start an expansion on the kingside by pushing the f-pawn after Ne8 @@StartBracket@@or Nh7, or Ng4@@EndBracket@@ and f5. }
14. Nh4 { Trying to prevent Black's plan. } 14... Qd7 { Preventing Nf5. } 15.
f4 Ng4
{ Hitting both the bishop on e3 and the knight on h4. At the same time, the f6-square is liberated for the bishop. }
16. Nf3 Qc7
{ Now Black liberates the d7-square for the knight on b8. He will exchange the knight on g4 for the bishop on e3 and play Nd7 and Bf6 with good play as the dark-squared bishop will be very strong on the long diagonal. }
