[White "3. Classical Variation - 6.Be2"]
[Black "Classical Variation 6.Be2 Nc6 7.O-O #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. Be2
{ This classical development is always a solid option for White in the Open Sicilian. When choosing this line White usually seeks more positional play, but there are also more aggressive plans. }
6... Nc6
{ Black can also start with  6...Be7  . In all except one line, his next two moves will be Nc6 and O-O so we would have a transposition. }
7. O-O
{ The most common move, fully in line with the development with Be2, which seeks calmer play. }
7... Be7 { Black continues development and will castle next. } 8. Be3
{ The usual development of the dark-squared bishop. White can also try a couple of other ideas. }
8... O-O { Black finishes the development of the kingside. } 9. Nb3
{ White avoids a possible exchange on d4 and also removes the knight from a possible attack after Black's e5. Still, removing the centralised knight voluntarily makes little sense. }
9... a6 { Black wants to expand with b5 and develop the bishop to b7. } 10. a4
{ Preventing Black's plan and intending to fix Black's queenside with a5. }
10... b6
{ Black naturally prevents a5 and will develop the bishop on b7 on the next move. }
11. f4 Bb7
{ Black finished development and now it is important to note the following method of creating play on the queenside. }
12. Bf3 Nd7
{ The knight is removed from f6 so that it doesn't come under attack after g4-g5. }
13. g4
{ White's only plan is to attack on the kingside. If he doesn't do that Black will play Na5 or Nc5 in combination with Nb4 and exert pressure on White's queenside. }
13... Na5
{ This is an important idea that Black should know. He welcomes the doubling of the pawns on the a-file in order to open the b-file and then he can use both c- and b-files to exert pressure on White's queenside. }
14. g5
{ Taking  14.Nxa5?!  bxa5  is very favourable for Black, he can continue with Rc8, Nb6-c4 or with Rb8, Qc7, Rfc8 and Ba8, maximising the pressure on the semi-open files on the queenside. }
14... Nc4
{ The knight is dominating on c4, hitting both the bishop on e3 and the pawn on b2. }
15. Bc1 e5
{ Another important move that effectively eliminates any risk of a kingside attack. In view of the pressure on the pawn on g5 White cannot push f5, which means that the pawns will be exchanged, giving Black access to the e5-square. Then he will have a better position because his pieces will be better placed than White's. He will also have a safer king, while White's kingside will be exposed.   We have been following the game Nakamura-Carlsen from the Magnus Carlsen Invitation played in 2020, which was won by Black in great style. }
