[Black "Classical Variation 6.Be2 Nc6 7.O-O #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. Be2
{ This classical development is always a solid option for White in the Open Sicilian. When choosing this line White usually seeks more positional play, but there are also more aggressive plans. }
6... Nc6
{ Black can also start with  6...Be7  . In all except one line, his next two moves will be Nc6 and O-O so we would have a transposition. }
7. O-O
{ The most common move, fully in line with the development with Be2, which seeks calmer play. }
7... Be7 { Black continues development and will castle next. } 8. Be3
{ The usual development of the dark-squared bishop. White can also try a couple of other ideas. }
8... O-O { Black finishes the development of the kingside. } 9. Kh1
{ White postpones f4 in order to avoid Black's e5. } 9... Nxd4
{ Black has many good options here, like  9...e5  ,  9...d5  ,  9...Bd7  and  9...a6  @@StartBracket@@the last one leading to the Classical Scheveningen@@EndBracket@@, but the exchange on d4 is a simple solution. }
10. Bxd4
{ After  10.Qxd4  b6  11.f4  Bb7  12.Bf3  d5  we have a transposition to theline with 8.f4 0-0 9.Kh1. }
10... e5 { Expanding in the centre with tempo and intending Be6 next. } 11. Be3
Be6 { Now Black wants to push d5. } 12. f4
{ White prevents d5 by putting pressure on the e5-pawn, but now Black can react in typical fashion. }
12... exf4
{ This exchange is commonplace in the Modern Scheveningen: Black liberates the e5-square for a knight or bishop and isolates the pawn on e4. His own isolated pawn on d6 can be easily covered. }
13. Rxf4
{ After  13.Bxf4  d5  14.e5  Ne4  is the easiest, as here  13...Ne8  can be met by  14.Nb5  followed by Nd4, even though it is still playable for Black. }
13... Ne8
{ A very important maneuver in the Modern Scheveningen. Black defends the pawn on d6 and intends Bg5. The exchange of the dark-squared bishops is in Black's favour as then he will obtain control over the dark-squares and the better bishop, because his own bishop won't be restricted while White's will be by the pawn on e4. An additional idea for Black is the maneuver Bf6-e5, followed by Nf6, activating his minor pieces.   Note that the knight move is a fighting option, as Black can easily equalise with the simplifying  13...d5  and after  14.e5  Nd7  15.Nxd5  Nxe5  16.Nxe7  Qxe7  his untouchable centralised knight on e5 is not inferior to any of White's bishops. }
14. Rf1
{ Avoiding the exchange of the dark-squared bishops after Bg5 as now the bishop from e3 can retreat to g1. }
14... Bf6
{ Since now Bg5 is useless, Black employs the alternative idea of Bf6-e5 and Nf6. }
15. Nd5 Be5
{ Centralising the bishop. It's possible to take on b2, but that would activate the white rook  15...Bxb2  16.Rb1  and Rxb7. }
16. c3 Bxd5
{ Another typical move for Black: he wants to force White to land a pawn on d5 instead of a piece. Then the weakness of the pawn on d6 will be covered @@StartBracket@@as the d-file will be closed@@EndBracket@@ and Black will obtain the e-file and a mobile kingside majority. }
17. exd5
{ White is forced to give Black what he wants as  17.Qxd5?  Qh4!  18.Bg1  Nf6  wins the pawn on e4. }
17... g6
{ Black prepares the kingside expansion by f5, Nf6, possibly Ne4 and so on. He can also activate the queen with Qh4. He still wants to exchange the dark-squared bishops when he can use the e5-square for a knight.   Notice how the bishop on e2 is heavily restricted and it will only get worse for it as Black establishes the pawn chain of f5-g6-h7. This type of position is a dream scenario for Black who can safely play for a win thanks to his simple plan of kingside advance that can easily transform into an attack. }
