[White "3. Classical Variation - 6.Be2"]
[Black "Classical Variation 6.Be2 Nc6 7.O-O #10"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. Be2
{ This classical development is always a solid option for White in the Open Sicilian. When choosing this line White usually seeks more positional play, but there are also more aggressive plans. }
6... Nc6
{ Black can also start with  6...Be7  . In all except one line, his next two moves will be Nc6 and O-O so we would have a transposition. }
7. O-O
{ The most common move, fully in line with the development with Be2, which seeks calmer play. }
7... Be7 { Black continues development and will castle next. } 8. Be3
{ The usual development of the dark-squared bishop. White can also try a couple of other ideas. }
8... O-O { Black finishes the development of the kingside. } 9. f4
{ White expands in the centre and the kingside. } 9... e5
{ The key move of the Modern Scheveningen. It was the discovery of this move that gave the Scheveningen a modern twist. Black moves the e-pawn again but forces favourable changes in the centre. }
10. Ndb5
{ This move looks a bit strange, but White wants to put pressure on the d6-pawn. }
10... a6 { The natural move, attacking the knight immediately. } 11. fxe5
{ White's last move would make little sense if it weren't for this zwischenzug. }
11... Nxe5
{ Establishing an eternal knight. The other recapture also makes sense, though it does give White some justification for his 10th move after  11...dxe5  12.Qxd8  Bxd8  13.Nd6  . Now White is forced to return to d4. }
12. Nd4 b5
{ A standard Sicilian move, expanding on the queenside. However, Black's position is so comfortable that he has more than one good way here. For example, the direct  12...d5  , which was suggested by Kasparov, equalises comfortably after  13.Nxd5  Nxd5  14.exd5  Qxd5  15.Nf5  Qe6  16.Nxe7  Qxe7  because the untouchable knight on e5 is not worse than any of White's bishops - in fact it dominates the bishop on e2, which has no good squares to go to.   Another option is the quiet preparatory move  12...Re8  , with similar ideas like  13.Kh1  b5  or  13.Qd2  d5  . }
13. Nf5
{ After  13.a4  b4  14.Nd5  Nxd5  15.exd5  Bg5!  is an important move, activating the dark-squared bishop and seeking its exchange for White's counterpart. }
13... Bxf5 { A knight on f5 is never tolerated. } 14. Rxf5 Qc8
{ A good move and an improvement over  14...Rc8  , which was also good enough in the game Novikov-Timofeev played in Moscow in 2008. With the queen move, Black threatens Nxe4. }
15. Rf1 b4 { Attacking the knight on c3 and forcing it to move to d5. } 16. Nd5
Nxd5 17. exd5
{ Here we see another benefit of the move 14...Qc8: the queen on the c-file targets the pawn on c2 so White cannot recapture with the queen as that would drop that pawn. }
17... Qb7
{ Black is comfortable here, all thanks to the glorious knight on e5. He can also choose the simple move  17...Bf6  activating the bishop on the long diagonal, but the queen move has a less obvious maneuver in mind - the activation of the dark-squared bishop via d8 and b6. As always in these positions, the exchange of the dark-squared bishops is hugely in Black's favour as then his knight on e5 would dominate the bishop on e2 and he can freely play on the dark squares in addition to the advance of his kingside majority. }
