1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. Be2
{ This classical development is always a solid option for White in the Open Sicilian. When choosing this line White usually seeks more positional play, but there are also more aggressive plans. }
6... Nc6
{ Black can also start with  6...Be7  . In all except one line, his next two moves will be Nc6 and O-O so we would have a transposition. }
7. O-O
{ The most common move, fully in line with the development with Be2, which seeks calmer play. }
7... Be7 { Black continues development and will castle next. } 8. Be3
{ The usual development of the dark-squared bishop. White can also try a couple of other ideas. }
8... O-O { Black finishes the development of the kingside. } 9. f4
{ White expands in the centre and the kingside. } 9... e5
{ The key move of the Modern Scheveningen. It was the discovery of this move that gave the Scheveningen a modern twist. Black moves the e-pawn again but forces favourable changes in the centre. }
10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Kh1
{ A generally useful move for White in the Sicilian. Note that the seemingly ambitious  11.f5?  is met by the central counterstrike  11...d5  when Black takes over the initiative. }
11... exf4 { With this exchange Black obtains the e5-square for his knight. }
12. Bxf4 Be6
{ Developing the bishop to the natural square and preparing the Nd7-e5 maneuver. }
13. Qe1
{ Intending Qg3 and Rd1. Against other moves Black's play is simple - he wants to achieve the Nd7-e5 maneuver and to use the semi-open b-file for counterplay. A sample line is  13.Bf3  Qb6  14.b3  Rad8  15.Qe1  Rfe8  16.Rd1  Ng4  with Ne5 next. }
13... Nd7 { The knight is en route to e5. } 14. Rd1 Qc7
{ Defending the pawn on d6. Of course, the immediate  14...Ne5??  blunders the knight to  15.Bxe5  in view of the pin on the d-file. }
15. Qg3 Ne5
{ Black achieved the ideal set-up. The knight is untouchable on e5 and Black will use it as a stronghold in the centre that ensures against any problems on the kingside. He wants to use the b-file to put pressure on White's queenside. Here are a few moves from my game against GM Mladen Palac played at the Tromso Olympiad in 2014: }
16. Na4 { Threatening Nc5. } 16... Rad8
{ Supporting the pawn on d6 and allowing for Bc8 when the rook won't be shut on a8. }
17. c4 Ng6
{ The pawn on c4 is poisonous:  17...Nxc4?  18.Bh6  g6  19.Bxc4  Bxc4  20.Qc3  , winning a piece. }
18. Bg5 Bxg5
{ Black gladly exchanges the dark-squared bishops: the pawn on d6 is easily defended and the pawn structure favours Black's light-squared bishop. }
19. Qxg5 c5
{ Fixing White's pawns on light squares, thus limiting the scope of the bishop on e2. Black is slightly better here thanks to his control over the dark squares with ideas like Ne5-c6-d4. }
