1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. Be2
{ This classical development is always a solid option for White in the Open Sicilian. When choosing this line White usually seeks more positional play, but there are also more aggressive plans. }
6... Nc6
{ Black can also start with  6...Be7  . In all except one line, his next two moves will be Nc6 and O-O so we would have a transposition. }
7. O-O
{ The most common move, fully in line with the development with Be2, which seeks calmer play. }
7... Be7 { Black continues development and will castle next. } 8. Be3
{ The usual development of the dark-squared bishop. White can also try a couple of other ideas. }
8... O-O { Black finishes the development of the kingside. } 9. f4
{ White expands in the centre and the kingside. } 9... e5
{ The key move of the Modern Scheveningen. It was the discovery of this move that gave the Scheveningen a modern twist. Black moves the e-pawn again but forces favourable changes in the centre. }
10. Nb3 { The most commonly played move. } 10... exf4
{ By exchanging the pawns Black obtains the e5-square for his knight. } 11.
Bxf4 { Or  11.Rxf4  Ne8!?  with a transposition to themain line. } 11... Be6
{ Black develops and intends to push d5. Here  11...Ne8  is less logical as White can play  12.Qd2  ,  preventing Bg5 and preparing Rad1, putting pressure on the pawn on d6. }
12. Kh1
{ White has other moves at his disposal but they don't promise even a whiff of an advantage. For example, moves like  12.Qe1  or  12.Qd2  are nicely met by  12...d5  .   The move  12.Bf3  prevents d5 but after  12...Ne5  the bishop is very passive on f3. The move  @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp2bppp/2npbn2/8/4PB2/1NN5/PPP1B1PP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Bd3  , which was played in the classical game Botvinnik-Boleslavsky, Sverdlovsk 1943, also allows  12...d5  , though even the move Boleslavsky played,  12...Ne5  , is good enough. }
12... d5
{ The simplest solution and quite a typical one for the Modern Scheveningen. The alternative is to play the already-familiar move  12...Ne8!?  , which leads to unclear play after  13.Qd2  Bf6  14.Rad1  Be5  . }
13. e5
{ The only try for White, since the exchanges on d5 give nothing,  13.exd5  Nxd5  14.Nxd5  Qxd5  is too easy. }
13... Ne4
{ Black has an equally valid alternative in  13...Nd7  , which after  14.Nxd5  Ndxe5  leads to an equal open position. The point of Black's play in this line is that after  15.Nxe7  Qxe7  his centralised pieces, the knight on e5 in particular, efficiently neutralise White's pair of bishops. In fact, the knight on e5 is superior to the bishop on e2, which doesn't have moves without allowing to be exchanged. }
14. Nxe4 dxe4 15. Qc1
{ This prevents Bg5, which would be possible in case of  15.Qe1  Bg5!  . }
15... Nd4
{ This suggestion by Kasparov is an improvement over the move  15...Qc7?!  which was played in the game Slobodjan-Leko played at the FIDE World Championship KO in Groningen in 1997. }
16. Nxd4 Qxd4 17. c3 Qb6
{ Black has little to complain about. His bishops are active, he can operate along the d-file and the pawn on e4, if necessary, can easily be defended. }
