{ The simplest solution and quite a typical one for the Modern Scheveningen. The alternative is to play the already-familiar move  12...Ne8!?  , which leads to unclear play after  13.Qd2  Bf6  14.Rad1  Be5  . }
13. e5
{ The only try for White, since the exchanges on d5 give nothing,  13.exd5  Nxd5  14.Nxd5  Qxd5  is too easy. }
13... Ne4
{ Black has an equally valid alternative in  13...Nd7  , which after  14.Nxd5  Ndxe5  leads to an equal open position. The point of Black's play in this line is that after  15.Nxe7  Qxe7  his centralised pieces, the knight on e5 in particular, efficiently neutralise White's pair of bishops. In fact, the knight on e5 is superior to the bishop on e2, which doesn't have moves without allowing to be exchanged. }
14. Bd3 { White points the bishop towards the kingside. } 14... f5
{ Black stabilises the knight on e4 and practically forces White to take en passant. }
15. exf6
{ White cannot tolerate a strong centralised knight on e4, so he undermines it by eliminating one of its defenders, the pawn on f5. }
15... Bxf6
{ The bishop on f6 is quite powerful and the attack on the pawn on b2 makes sure that Black doesn't lose a pawn on e4. }
16. Nxe4
{ The start of a small tactical skirmish. In case of  16.Qe1  Black can try for the strategically complex  16...Bxc3!?  17.bxc3  Bf5  when his better structure, strong knight on e4 and the control over the light squares are more than enough to counter White's pair of bishops. }
16... dxe4 17. Nc5
{ Taking on e4 after  17.Bxe4  Qxd1  18.Raxd1  Bxb2  is somewhat preferable for Black, who can boast the better pawn structure. }
17... exd3
{ Black doesn't fear ghosts and takes the piece. The point is that after... }
18. Nxe6
{ Even though it seems like Black is losing material he has the following move at this disposal. }
18... dxc2 19. Qxc2
{ White shouldn't get greedy as  19.Qxd8?  Rfxd8  20.Nxd8  Rxd8  is winning for Black thanks to the strength of the pawn on c2 supported by all the other pieces: Bxb2, Nb4 and Rd2 are all decisive threats. }
19... Nd4
{ The key move for Black that forces simplifications and makes sure Black doesn't lose material. }
20. Nxd4 Qxd4 { The position is equal as Black has no problems whatsoever. }
21. Qb3+ Rf7 { He protects the pawn on b7 and keeps attacking the pawn on b2. }
