[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. Be3 Be7
{ It is important for Black to start with this move because of a possible transposition to theline with 6.f4 where Black needs to be able to castle quickly. }
7. Qe2
{ This is a rare move, as even though it prepares long castle, it blocks the development of the bishop on f1. On the positive side, the queen won't be blocking the d-file after White castles long. }
7... e5 { In typical Modern Scheveningen fashion Black strikes in the centre. }
8. Nf5 { This moves forces Black to exchange on f5. } 8... Bxf5
{ The knight has to be eliminated. } 9. exf5 d5
{ Black obtained a wonderful centre for the bishop pair. } 10. O-O-O O-O
{ Getting the king out of the centre and now Black is ready to start pushing the central pawns. }
11. Bg5 { White puts pressure on Black's centre. } 11... d4
{ Removing the pawn from the attacked square on d5. } 12. Bxf6
{ With this exchange White obtains the e4-square for his knight. Taking the pawn on e5 is not very good for White,  12.Qxe5?!  Nc6  13.Qe2  Qa5  gives Black excellent play. }
12... Bxf6 13. Ne4 Na6
{ An important move. The knight is developed on a6 with two ideas in mind: first, it doesn't block the c-file @@StartBracket@@as it would from c6@@EndBracket@@, and second, from a6 it can come to b4, attacking both pawns on a2 and c2, something that will be very dangerous once Black's rook comes to c8. Black has very good play in this complex position. }
