1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. Be3 Be7
{ It is important for Black to start with this move because of a possible transposition to theline with 6.f4 where Black needs to be able to castle quickly. }
7. g4 { This is another aggressive option. } 7... d5
{ Black reacts in the classical manner - he strikes in the centre to deal with an attack on the flank. }
8. exd5
{ This capture is easily dealt with as unlike the Keres Attack here Black has a bishop on e7 instead of a pawn on h6 so he can castle quickly and avoid any possible threats against the pawn on h6 as in the Keres Attack. }
8... Nxd5
{ Taking with knight forces white to recapture, thus centralising Black's queen. }
9. Nxd5
{ Note that the check  9.Bb5  transposes to the line starting with8.Bb5 Nbd7 9.exd5 Nxd5. }
9... Qxd5 10. Rg1 O-O
{ Black's king is safe now and all that remains is to develop the queenside. }
11. Bg2 Qa5+ { Moving away with tempo. } 12. Qd2
{ After  12.c3  Nd7  with Nf6-d5 Black activates the knight and can then develop the light-squared bishop. }
12... Qxd2+ { The endgame is pleasant for Black. } 13. Bxd2 Rd8
{ Attacking the centralised knight. } 14. c3
{ After  14.Nb3  Nc6  with e5 next Black solves the problem of his queenside development. }
14... e5
{ Chasing away the centralised knight. This also opens the h3-c8 diagonal for the light-squared bishop. }
15. Nf5 Bf8
{ Dropping back before continuing with Nc6 and Be6. Black is fine in the endgame as he finishes development and can then start playing in the centre where his pawn majority lies. }
