1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. Be3 Be7
{ It is important for Black to start with this move because of a possible transposition to theline with 6.f4 where Black needs to be able to castle quickly. }
7. g4 { This is another aggressive option. } 7... d5
{ Black reacts in the classical manner - he strikes in the centre to deal with an attack on the flank. }
8. g5 Nxe4 { Black naturally takes the pawn. } 9. Nxe4 dxe4 10. Nb5
{ White threatens to exchange queens and castle long, thus obtaining initiative against Black's king stuck in the centre. }
10... Bd7
{ Black wants to develop with Bc6, at the same time defending the extra pawn on e4. The alternative  10...Qa5  is also good, after  11.Qd2  Qxd2  12.Bxd2  Na6  followed by O-O Black has a good endgame, as he wants to develop with b6, Bb7 and defend the pawn on e4 with Nc5. }
11. Nd6+ Bxd6 12. Qxd6 Bc6
{ Now it will be very difficult for White to take on e4. He can take on g7 instead, but that gives Black time to centralise the knight. To illustrate: }
13. Qe5 Nd7 { Developing with tempo. } 14. Qxg7 Qa5+
{ This important check is what holds everything together. Black is just in time to play Qe5 next. }
15. Bd2 Qe5 { Forcing the exchange of queens. } 16. Qxe5 Nxe5
{ Black has great play here. His centralised knight is not inferior to either of White's bishops and together with the pawn on e4 they give Black a space advantage. Black can put the rooks on the g and d-files and will play in the centre. Black can either castle queenside or leave the king on e8. }
