[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. Be3 Be7
{ It is important for Black to start with this move because of a possible transposition to theline with 6.f4 where Black needs to be able to castle quickly. }
7. g4 { This is another aggressive option. } 7... d5
{ Black reacts in the classical manner - he strikes in the centre to deal with an attack on the flank. }
8. e5 { This leads to very sharp play. } 8... Nfd7
{ Attacking the pawn on e5 and forcing f4, which would weaken the e1-h4 diagonal. }
9. f4 Bh4+ { This robs White of the right to castle. } 10. Kd2
{ Exchanging the bishops with  10.Bf2?!  Bxf2  11.Kxf2  Nc6  gives Black an advantage as the dark squares in White's camp have been weakened.  Black can continue the attack with Qb6 and g5 when White will find it very difficult to defend. }
10... g5 { A strong move, undermining White's centre. } 11. Qf3
{ In case of  11.Nf3  gxf4  12.Bxf4  Be7  followed by Nc6, Nc5 etc. Play is very complex and Black has good chances. His priority is to develop his queenside and possibly castle long. }
11... Nc6 { Black develops and puts more pressure on White's centre. } 12. Bd3
{ This is a sensible move, developing the bishop to the most natural square. }
12... gxf4 { Black wins a pawn now as the pawn on e5 is lost. } 13. Qxf4 Ndxe5
{ Taking with the other knight is a mistake as after  13...Ncxe5?  14.g5  Ng6  15.Bxg6!  hxg6  16.Ncb5  Black's position collapses.  By keeping one knight on c6 Black keeps an eye on the knight on d4, thus preventing the g5-push, as it is explained in the next comment. }
14. Nxc6
{ Pushing g5 is a mistake as after  14.g5?  Nxd4  any recapture of the knight loses:  15.Bxd4  Bxg5  and the queen is pinned, or @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp3p1p/4p3/3pn1P1/3n1Q1b/2NBB3/PPPK3P/R6R w kq - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15.Qxd4  Nf3+  . }
14... Nxd3 { Black forces more exchanges. } 15. cxd3
{ The endgame after  15.Nxd8  Nxf4  is better for Black thanks to his pair of bishops. }
15... bxc6 16. g5
{ It appears that Black is losing a piece, but he the only, yet sufficient retort: }
16... d4
{ Making use of the overburdened queen and bishop that have to defend the pawn on g5 Black manages to avoid the loss of a piece. }
17. Qxh4
{ Of course, taking on d4 would lead to Black taking on g5,  17.Qxd4  Qxd4  18.Bxd4  Bxg5  with a very good endgame for Black thanks to his bishop pair. }
17... dxe3+
{ The bishop is more important than the knight because Black is weak on the dark squares. }
18. Kc2
{ Taking the pawn on e3 allows either Qb6 or e5, followed by the development of the bishop. }
18... h6
{ Attacking the pawn on g5, using the fact that it is pinned. The position is very sharp as neither king is too safe, but in the long-term, Black has the better minor piece as the bishop is stronger in this open position, it only needs to be developed. Black wants to exchange queens as in the endgame the bishop will be even stronger. }
