{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. Be3 Be7
{ It is important for Black to start with this move because of a possible transposition to theline with 6.f4 where Black needs to be able to castle quickly. }
7. g4 { This is another aggressive option. } 7... d5
{ Black reacts in the classical manner - he strikes in the centre to deal with an attack on the flank. }
8. e5 { This leads to very sharp play. } 8... Nfd7
{ Attacking the pawn on e5 and forcing f4, which would weaken the e1-h4 diagonal. }
9. f4 Bh4+ { This robs White of the right to castle. } 10. Kd2
{ Exchanging the bishops with  10.Bf2?!  Bxf2  11.Kxf2  Nc6  gives Black an advantage as the dark squares in White's camp have been weakened.  Black can continue the attack with Qb6 and g5 when White will find it very difficult to defend. }
10... g5 { A strong move, undermining White's centre. } 11. Qf3
{ In case of  11.Nf3  gxf4  12.Bxf4  Be7  followed by Nc6, Nc5 etc. Play is very complex and Black has good chances. His priority is to develop his queenside and possibly castle long. }
11... Nc6 { Black develops and puts more pressure on White's centre. } 12. Rd1
{ White prepares to castle artificially with Kc1. } 12... gxf4
{ Black goes after the pawn on e5. A completely messy position can arise after  12...h6!?  13.f5  O-O  , which is unclear but Black has good chances there. }
13. Qxf4 Ncxe5
{ Unlike theline after 12.Bd3, without a bishop on d3, Black needs to have the move Ng6 at his disposal in order to defend the bishop on h4 after g5. The other recapture loses the bishop after  13...Ndxe5?  14.Nxc6  Nxc6  15.g5  and the bishop on h4 is lost. }
14. g5 Ng6 { The only, but sufficient way to defend the bishop on h4. } 15. Qg4
Nde5
{ Centralising the knight with tempo and liberating the d7-square for the development of the light-squared bishop. Notice how strong Black's cluster of the knights on e5 and g6 and the bishop on h4 is: they are all defended, cannot be attacked or dislodged and this makes White's play more difficult as these pieces control a lot of important squares. }
16. Qh5 Bd7
{ Developing and opening the c-file. An additional idea for Black is to play Qe7 and castle long. }
17. Kc1 O-O
{ Black has good alternatives:  17...f5  18.gxf6  Qxf6  followed by O-O-O and @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/pp1b1p1p/4p1n1/3pn1PQ/3N3b/2N1B3/PPP4P/2KR1B1R b kq - 6 17@@EndFEN@@  17...Rc8  , for example, but not @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/pp1b1p1p/4p1n1/3pn1PQ/3N3b/2N1B3/PPP4P/2KR1B1R b kq - 6 17@@EndFEN@@  17...Qe7?  which runs into  18.Nf5!  . }
18. Rg1 Rc8
{ Introducing the threat of an exchange sacrifice on c3 @@StartBracket@@for example after  19.Bd3  Rxc3!  20.bxc3  Qc7  with great play@@EndBracket@@.  The position is very complex but Black has excellent chances. Apart from being a pawn up, his king is safe thanks to the strong position of the knights and the bishop on h4 that prevent any kingside attack. Black also has his own play on the queenside, based on the exchange sacrifice on c3, which wrecks White's structure and weakens White's king. As in some other lines of this repertoire, he can then continue to play positionally with Qc7 and move the knight from e5 in order to push e5 and so on. }
