{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. Be3 Be7
{ It is important for Black to start with this move because of a possible transposition to theline with 6.f4 where Black needs to be able to castle quickly. }
7. g4 { This is another aggressive option. } 7... d5
{ Black reacts in the classical manner - he strikes in the centre to deal with an attack on the flank. }
8. Bb5+ Nbd7
{ Covering the check with a knight leaves the bishop on b5 somewhat loose as White doesn't really want to take on d7. }
9. exd5 Nxd5
{ Black captures with the knight as it frees his play. Now the h4-d8 diagonal is open and after castling the bishop or the knight can come to f6. }
10. Nxd5 exd5 11. Qf3
{ The critical move, preparing castling long and attacking the pawn on d5. Against other queen moves Black castles and then plays a6 or Ne5 with good game. }
11... O-O
{ Black sacrifices the central pawn for active piece play. In fact, thanks to that activity he will soon regain it. }
12. Qxd5 Qa5+
{ Black removes the queen from d8 with tempo and now threatens Nf6, attacking the queen on d5 and the pawn on g4. }
13. c3
{ In case of  13.Bd2  Qc7  followed by Nf6 Black regains the pawn and still has free play. }
13... Nf6
{ This leads to a messy middlegame. If Black prefers a messy endgame, the alternative  13...a6  is a good one. After  14.Bc4  Qxd5  15.Bxd5  Nf6  16.Bg2  Nxg4  17.Bf4  Bf6  the endgame is balanced but still rather sharp. }
14. Qe5 a6 { Attacking the pinned bishop on b5. } 15. Qxe7 axb5 16. h3
{ Defending the pawn on g4. Playing  16.g5  Nd5  17.Qe5  Qd8!  with Re8 next and with the threat of Nxe3 gives Black great compensation. }
16... Bd7
{ Connecting the rooks and keeping the options open. Black can also play  16...Re8  17.Qc5  Bd7  , which would transpose, or @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/1p2Qppp/5n2/qp6/3N2P1/2P1B2P/PP3P2/R3K2R b KQ - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16...Nd5  17.Qc5  b4  which also gives him good compensation. }
17. O-O { Removing the king from the centre. } 17... h5
{ Attacking White's exposed kingside. Black can start with  17...Rfe8  18.Qc5  h5  , which would again transpose. }
18. g5 Rfe8 19. Qc5
{ In case of  19.Qd6  Ra6  20.Qh2  Nd5  all Black's pieces are very active and he has threats like Nxe3, Rg6 etc. }
19... Ne4 { Moving away with tempo. } 20. Qd5 Re7
{ An important move, preparing Bxh3. The immediate  20...Bxh3?  is met by  21.g6!  when Black is lost due to the threats of Qxf7 and Qxh5. However, an interesting alternative is @@StartFEN@@r3r1k1/1p1b1pp1/8/qp1Q2Pp/3Nn3/2P1B2P/PP3P2/R4RK1 b - - 4 20@@EndFEN@@  20...Bc6  , sacrificing another pawn. After  21.Nxc6  bxc6  22.Qxc6  b4!  ,  attacking both c3 and g5 Black has dangerous initiative. }
21. Qxb7
{ This is critical, taking another pawn. In case of  21.Nf5  Bxf5  22.Qxf5  Rae8  with the idea of Re5 Black has great play. }
21... Rae8 { Defending the rook and threatening Bxh3. } 22. Qd5 Qa6
{ Again preparing Bh3, as the immediate  22...Bxh3?  runs into  23.Nc6  . } 23.
Kh2 Qc8
{ Insisting on the Bxh3 threat. All Black's pieces are centralised and looking toward White's kingside. This gives Black excellent compensation. }
