[White "4. The English Attack - 6.Be3"]
[Black "The English Attack 6.Be3 Be7 7.f3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. Be3 Be7
{ It is important for Black to start with this move because of a possible transposition to theline with 6.f4 where Black needs to be able to castle quickly. }
7. f3
{ This is the move that characterises the English Attack. The idea is very simple - White strengthens the pawn on e4 and plans to play Qd2, castle long and then start a kingside attack with g4-g5, h4-h5 etc. Note that the moves  7.f4  O-O  transpose the chapterWhite Plays 6.f4, while the move @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2bppp/3ppn2/8/3NP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bc4  transposes to the chapter onthe Sozin. The move @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2bppp/3ppn2/8/3NP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Be2  transposes to the chapter on theClassical Variation. }
7... Nc6
{ It is also possible to castle first, the only difference lies in the line with an immediate g4, but against both  7...Nc6  8.g4  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2bppp/3ppn2/8/3NP3/2N1BP2/PPP3PP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...O-O  8.g4  Black is fine. Here is a sample line against the latter:  8...d5!  9.e5  Ne8  10.Qd2  Nc6  with good counterplay in the centre. In case of @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2bppp/3ppn2/8/3NP3/2N1BP2/PPP3PP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...O-O  8.Qd2  Nc6  we have a transposition to7...Nc6 8.Qd2 O-O. }
8. Qd2 O-O
{ Black moves the king from the centre and is ready to play in the centre. Now White needs to decide whether to follow suit or to start immediate kingside action. }
9. g4 { White starts immediate kingside action, threatening g5. } 9... d5
{ Black counters in the centre, following the principle that an attack on the wing should be met by a counterstrike in the centre. }
10. g5
{ White indirectly fights for the centre by attacking the knight on f6 that puts pressure on it. }
10... Nh5
{ This is slightly more precise than  10...Nxd4  . While in most cases the lines transpose, White does have one unpleasant option after  11.Qxd4  Nh5  12.Rg1!?  . }
11. f4
{ This move prevents e5 and allows for Be2, which would target the knight on h5. But the position in the centre becomes volatile now in view of the unstable position of the e4-pawn. }
11... Nxd4
{ This forces White to take with a queen and this will be used by Black to attack it with Bc5 later on. }
12. Qxd4
{ Taking with the bishop is met by  12.Bxd4?  dxe4  13.Nxe4  Nxf4!  and the queen on d2 cannot keep control of both d4 and f4. }
12... b6
{ An important move - the idea is to play Bc5. This is better than the move chosen by Leko against Becerra in 1997,  12...dxe4  , which after  13.Qxe4  @@StartBracket@@instead of the exchange of queens that was played by Becerra@@EndBracket@@ followed by O-O-O gives White an advantage. }
13. exd5
{ Taking the pawn, at least for now. In case of  13.O-O-O  Bc5  14.Qd2  d4!  Black is fine as taking on d4 after the exchanges leads to a capture of the f4-pawn. }
13... Bc5 { Attacking the queen. } 14. Qd2 exd5
{ This is stronger than  14...Bxe3  15.Qxe3  followed by O-O-O when White has strong pressure on the d-file. }
15. O-O-O Bg4
{ By attacking the rook on d1 Black alleviates the pressure on the d-file. }
16. Bxc5 { With this move White embarks on an exchange sacrifice. } 16... bxc5
{ Black threatens d4 so White is forced to sacrifice the rook on d1. } 17. Nxd5
Bxd1 { Black has no choice but to take the rook. } 18. Qxd1 g6
{ Stabilising the knight. The position is rather unclear where White has compensation for the exchange, but Black has good chances as well - he wants to play Re8, Qd7 and Rad8, centralising his heavy pieces.   An additional idea for Black is the piece sacrifice Nxf4 followed by Qxg5, when he obtains two pawns and free central squares for his rooks, for example after  19.Be2  Nxf4  20.Nxf4  Qxg5  . }
