6. Be3 Be7
{ It is important for Black to start with this move because of a possible transposition to theline with 6.f4 where Black needs to be able to castle quickly. }
7. f3
{ This is the move that characterises the English Attack. The idea is very simple - White strengthens the pawn on e4 and plans to play Qd2, castle long and then start a kingside attack with g4-g5, h4-h5 etc. Note that the moves  7.f4  O-O  transpose the chapterWhite Plays 6.f4, while the move @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2bppp/3ppn2/8/3NP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bc4  transposes to the chapter onthe Sozin. The move @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2bppp/3ppn2/8/3NP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Be2  transposes to the chapter on theClassical Variation. }
7... Nc6
{ It is also possible to castle first, the only difference lies in the line with an immediate g4, but against both  7...Nc6  8.g4  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2bppp/3ppn2/8/3NP3/2N1BP2/PPP3PP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...O-O  8.g4  Black is fine. Here is a sample line against the latter:  8...d5!  9.e5  Ne8  10.Qd2  Nc6  with good counterplay in the centre. In case of @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2bppp/3ppn2/8/3NP3/2N1BP2/PPP3PP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...O-O  8.Qd2  Nc6  we have a transposition to7...Nc6 8.Qd2 O-O. }
8. Qd2 O-O
{ Black moves the king from the centre and is ready to play in the centre. Now White needs to decide whether to follow suit or to start immediate kingside action. }
9. g4 { White starts immediate kingside action, threatening g5. } 9... d5
{ Black counters in the centre, following the principle that an attack on the wing should be met by a counterstrike in the centre. }
10. g5
{ White indirectly fights for the centre by attacking the knight on f6 that puts pressure on it. }
10... Nh5
{ This is slightly more precise than  10...Nxd4  . While in most cases the lines transpose, White does have one unpleasant option after  11.Qxd4  Nh5  12.Rg1!?  . }
11. O-O-O
{ The most common move for White. The move  11.exd5  will transpose after  11...Nxd4  12.Qxd4  Bxg5  13.O-O-O  exd5  . }
11... Nxd4 { Now White drops the pawn on g5 but will take on d5. } 12. Qxd4
{ This is more critical than  12.Bxd4  Bxg5  , which is fine for Black. } 12...
Bxg5 13. Kb1 { This move is the critical test. } 13... g6
{ This extremely rare move seems to be the best when it comes to keeping a balance between complexity and safety. Black has two good alternatives here. The simplest one is  13...Bxe3  14.Qxe3  Bd7  15.exd5  exd5  16.Nxd5  Re8  when he can hope to successfully neutralise White's slight initiative.   The most complex one is  13...Kh8  , when White has many options but Black is holding his own. }
14. Bxg5 Qxg5 15. Rg1 { This is rather harmless. } 15... Qf4
{ Black makes sure he exchanges queens when White regains the pawn on d5. } 16.
exd5 Qxd4
{ The endgame is good for Black, as he has the better pawn structure. } 17.
Rxd4 exd5
{ Black can also try to keep more tension with  17...Nf6  , though after  18.Bc4  he should again take on d5, leading to equality after  18...exd5  19.Nxd5  Nxd5  20.Bxd5  Re8  with ...Rb8 next to liberate the bishop from c8 from defending the pawn on b7. }
18. Nxd5 Be6 { Developing the bishop and setting a small positional trap. } 19.
Nc7
{ This is tempting, but this is the trap Black had in mind. In case of  19.Bc4  Rad8  all Black's pieces are in the game. }
19... Rad8 { Intending to exchange White's active bishop. } 20. Nxe6 fxe6
{ It may seem at first sight that White worsened Black's structure, but in fact, Black has the initiative here - the pawn on f3 is exposed on the semi-open f-file and after the exchange of rooks on the d-file White will have to spend a tempo to defend against mate. The knight will land on the untouchable square on f4 from where it will dominate the centre and the kingside. All these factors make this endgame more favourable for Black. }
