{ This extremely rare move seems to be the best when it comes to keeping a balance between complexity and safety. Black has two good alternatives here. The simplest one is  13...Bxe3  14.Qxe3  Bd7  15.exd5  exd5  16.Nxd5  Re8  when he can hope to successfully neutralise White's slight initiative.   The most complex one is  13...Kh8  , when White has many options but Black is holding his own. }
14. Be2 { With this move White keeps the tension in the centre. } 14... Bd7
{ Black cannot take on e4 in view of  14...dxe4?  15.Qc5!  when he suffers from the lag in development, so he makes sure he finishes his development before clarifying the position in the centre. Now the idea is to play Bc6. }
15. exd5 { Sooner rather than later White must regain the pawn. } 15... exd5
{ Black naturally recaptures. } 16. Qxd5
