{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. Be3 Be7
{ It is important for Black to start with this move because of a possible transposition to theline with 6.f4 where Black needs to be able to castle quickly. }
7. f3
{ This is the move that characterises the English Attack. The idea is very simple - White strengthens the pawn on e4 and plans to play Qd2, castle long and then start a kingside attack with g4-g5, h4-h5 etc. Note that the moves  7.f4  O-O  transpose the chapterWhite Plays 6.f4, while the move @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2bppp/3ppn2/8/3NP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bc4  transposes to the chapter onthe Sozin. The move @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2bppp/3ppn2/8/3NP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Be2  transposes to the chapter on theClassical Variation. }
7... Nc6
{ It is also possible to castle first, the only difference lies in the line with an immediate g4, but against both  7...Nc6  8.g4  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2bppp/3ppn2/8/3NP3/2N1BP2/PPP3PP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...O-O  8.g4  Black is fine. Here is a sample line against the latter:  8...d5!  9.e5  Ne8  10.Qd2  Nc6  with good counterplay in the centre. In case of @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2bppp/3ppn2/8/3NP3/2N1BP2/PPP3PP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...O-O  8.Qd2  Nc6  we have a transposition to7...Nc6 8.Qd2 O-O. }
8. Qd2 O-O
{ Black moves the king from the centre and is ready to play in the centre. Now White needs to decide whether to follow suit or to start immediate kingside action. }
9. g4 { White starts immediate kingside action, threatening g5. } 9... d5
{ Black counters in the centre, following the principle that an attack on the wing should be met by a counterstrike in the centre. }
10. g5
{ White indirectly fights for the centre by attacking the knight on f6 that puts pressure on it. }
10... Nh5
{ This is slightly more precise than  10...Nxd4  . While in most cases the lines transpose, White does have one unpleasant option after  11.Qxd4  Nh5  12.Rg1!?  . }
11. O-O-O
{ The most common move for White. The move  11.exd5  will transpose after  11...Nxd4  12.Qxd4  Bxg5  13.O-O-O  exd5  . }
11... Nxd4 { Now White drops the pawn on g5 but will take on d5. } 12. Qxd4
{ This is more critical than  12.Bxd4  Bxg5  , which is fine for Black. } 12...
Bxg5 13. Kb1 { This move is the critical test. } 13... g6
{ This extremely rare move seems to be the best when it comes to keeping a balance between complexity and safety. Black has two good alternatives here. The simplest one is  13...Bxe3  14.Qxe3  Bd7  15.exd5  exd5  16.Nxd5  Re8  when he can hope to successfully neutralise White's slight initiative.   The most complex one is  13...Kh8  , when White has many options but Black is holding his own. }
14. Rg1 { Hitting the bishop on g5. } 14... Bf6
{ With this move Black seeks complexity as he intends to keep the extra pawn. There is a simpler solution here in  14...Bxe3  15.Qxe3  Bd7!  , finishing development. After  16.exd5  exd5  17.Nxd5  Re8  18.Qh6  Nf6  Black manages to control White's initiative and the position is equal after  19.Bc4  Rc8  20.Bb3  Nxd5  21.Bxd5  Qf6!  22.Bxb7  Rc7  with Bf5 next, when Black has good compensation in view of the pressure along the c-file and the attack on the pawn on c2. }
15. e5
{ White naturally gains space. In case of  15.Qd3  Qa5  Black threatens to take on c3 and wreck White's queenside structure. }
15... Bg7
{ The fianchettoed bishop will exert pressure on the e5-pawn after Black's next move. }
16. f4 f6
{ Undermining White's centre and intending to open the f-file, when the rook will be able to come to f5 and attack the pawn on e5. An additional idea for Black to attack the pawn on e5 is the move Qc7. }
17. Be2
{ Attacking the knight on h5. This determines Black's choice of how to go about the attack on the pawn on e5. In case of  17.h4  he should go for  17...Qc7  when after the capture on e5 first with the pawn and then the bishop he will threaten to take on c3 to wreck White's queenside. }
17... fxe5 18. fxe5 Rf5
{ The only way for Black to avoid the opening of the h-file after Bxh5. At the same time, Black attacks the pawn on e5. On the next move, Black will take the pawn on e5 and will be two pawns up. He will still have to finish his development, but his position is solid, and White doesn't have a clear path on how to continue. A sample line goes: }
19. Bd3 Bxe5 20. Qg4 Ng7
{ Black sacrifices an exchange but centralises his knight and eliminates White's light-squared bishop in the process, thus eliminating any possibility of sacrifices on g6. }
21. Bxf5 Nxf5
{ Threatening both the bishop on e3 and to take on c3. Apart from these threats, Black's plan is to safely finish development behind the central pawn pair with Bd7-c6. }
