{ Black moves the king from the centre and is ready to play in the centre. Now White needs to decide whether to follow suit or to start immediate kingside action. }
9. O-O-O d5 { Before White starts to push g4-g5 Black strikes in the centre. }
10. exd5 { This leads to clarification of the position in the centre. } 10...
Nxd5
{ Black takes with the knight and in view of the threat Nxe3 he practically forces White to capture on d5. }
11. Nxd5 Qxd5 { Centralising the queen. } 12. Nxc6 Qxc6
{ The natural recapture, avoiding the worsening of the structure after  12...bxc6  . }
13. Bd3
{ An important move for White, preventing the easy development by b6 and Bb7 that can happen in the case of  13.Kb1  b6!  14.Bd3  Bb7  when Black has no problems. }
13... Rd8
{ Pinning the bishop and preparing the development of the light-squared bishop with Bd7. }
14. Kb1 Qc7
{ An important move for Black. First, he removes the queen from the vulnerable spot on c6 @@StartBracket@@for example  14...b6??  15.Be4  wins for White@@EndBracket@@; second, he keeps the option to play e5 and develop the bishop on e6; third, he waits to see how White will continue @@StartBracket@@in case of the immediate @@StartFEN@@r1br2k1/pp2bppp/2q1p3/8/8/3BBP2/PPPQ2PP/1K1R3R b - - 3 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Bd7  White can use the blocked d-file and play  15.Bd4  @@EndBracket@@. }
15. Rhe1
{ If White removes the queen from the d-file, for example,  15.Qf2  then Black plays  15...e5  followed by Be6. }
15... Bd7
{ White's last move discouraged  15...e5?!  in view of  16.Qe2!  followed by Bd2-c3, when Black will have some issues with the e5-pawn, so Black develops the bishop in another way. }
16. Bd4 Bc6
{ Black's pieces are harmoniously placed and they can extinguish White's slight initiative. }
17. Be5 Qb6
{ Black has a comfortable position with no weaknesses. His immediate threat is Bb5 to make use of the pin on the d-file. Another idea for Black is to push the a-pawn with a5-a4-a3, with the idea of creating weaknesses around White's king. }
