{ Black moves the king from the centre and is ready to play in the centre. Now White needs to decide whether to follow suit or to start immediate kingside action. }
9. O-O-O d5 { Before White starts to push g4-g5 Black strikes in the centre. }
10. Bb5
{ Attacking the knight on c6, but as we shall see the bishop is exposed on b5, often giving Black tempo for a6 and b5. }
10... Nxd4 { Black naturally escapes with tempo. } 11. Qxd4
{ Keeping the pressure on the d-file, though with little effect. After  11.Bxd4  a6  12.Bd3  dxe4  the exchanges on e4 favour Black who can then continue with Qc7 and b5. }
11... dxe4
{ This is the simplest. If Black wants to keep a bit more tension he can flick in  11...a6  first and then take on the next move. }
12. Qxd8 Rxd8
{ After the exchange of the rooks Black can more easily approach the centre with his king as the f8-square is available. }
13. Rxd8+ Bxd8 14. Rd1 Bc7
{ This is better than going to e7 since it keeps an eye on the pawn on h2. }
15. Nxe4 Nxe4 { Creating an isolated pawn on e4. } 16. fxe4 a6
{ Taking advantage of the exposed position of the bishop on b5 Black prepares to expand with b5 and finish development with Bb7. }
17. Be2 b5
{ With Bb7 next, Black is more than okay as he has the better pawn structure. }
18. Bf3 Bb7 19. Rd7 { This isn't scary. } 19... Rc8
{ With Bc6 next to chase away the rook on d7. } *

