{ It is also possible to castle first, the only difference lies in the line with an immediate g4, but against both  7...Nc6  8.g4  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2bppp/3ppn2/8/3NP3/2N1BP2/PPP3PP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...O-O  8.g4  Black is fine. Here is a sample line against the latter:  8...d5!  9.e5  Ne8  10.Qd2  Nc6  with good counterplay in the centre. In case of @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2bppp/3ppn2/8/3NP3/2N1BP2/PPP3PP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...O-O  8.Qd2  Nc6  we have a transposition to7...Nc6 8.Qd2 O-O. }
8. Qd2 O-O
{ Black moves the king from the centre and is ready to play in the centre. Now White needs to decide whether to follow suit or to start immediate kingside action. }
9. O-O-O d5 { Before White starts to push g4-g5 Black strikes in the centre. }
10. Bb5
{ Attacking the knight on c6, but as we shall see the bishop is exposed on b5, often giving Black tempo for a6 and b5. }
10... Nxd4 { Black naturally escapes with tempo. } 11. Qxd4
{ Keeping the pressure on the d-file, though with little effect. After  11.Bxd4  a6  12.Bd3  dxe4  the exchanges on e4 favour Black who can then continue with Qc7 and b5. }
11... dxe4
{ This is the simplest. If Black wants to keep a bit more tension he can flick in  11...a6  first and then take on the next move. }
12. fxe4 a6
{ Black makes a useful move with tempo, preparing a queenside expansion with b5 and the development of the light-squared bishop to b7. }
13. Be2 Qc7
{ Preparing both b5 and e5. The immediate  13...b5?!  is premature as after the exchange of queens White can push e5 and take advantage of the open long diagonal:  14.Qxd8  Rxd8  15.Rxd8  Bxd8  16.e5!  with Bf3 next. }
14. e5 Nd7 { Moving away with tempo. } 15. Bf4 Nc5
{ The knight is very good on c5, controlling the important light squares on e4 and d3 @@StartBracket@@for example preventing a possible battery of Bd3 and Qe4@@EndBracket@@. Now Black wants to continue with b5 and Bb7. }
16. Bf3 { Preventing b5. Now Black can change his plan. } 16... Bd7
{ With Rfd8 to follow and comfortable play, as his queenside activity can quickly become menacing after a further Rac8 and b5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. The English Attack - 6.Be3"]
[Black "The English Attack 6.Be3 Be7 7.f3 #17"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. Be3 Be7
{ It is important for Black to start with this move because of a possible transposition to theline with 6.f4 where Black needs to be able to castle quickly. }
7. f3
{ This is the move that characterises the English Attack. The idea is very simple - White strengthens the pawn on e4 and plans to play Qd2, castle long and then start a kingside attack with g4-g5, h4-h5 etc. Note that the moves  7.f4  O-O  transpose the chapterWhite Plays 6.f4, while the move @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2bppp/3ppn2/8/3NP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bc4  transposes to the chapter onthe Sozin. The move @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2bppp/3ppn2/8/3NP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Be2  transposes to the chapter on theClassical Variation. }
7... Nc6
{ It is also possible to castle first, the only difference lies in the line with an immediate g4, but against both  7...Nc6  8.g4  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2bppp/3ppn2/8/3NP3/2N1BP2/PPP3PP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...O-O  8.g4  Black is fine. Here is a sample line against the latter:  8...d5!  9.e5  Ne8  10.Qd2  Nc6  with good counterplay in the centre. In case of @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2bppp/3ppn2/8/3NP3/2N1BP2/PPP3PP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...O-O  8.Qd2  Nc6  we have a transposition to7...Nc6 8.Qd2 O-O. }
8. Qd2 O-O
{ Black moves the king from the centre and is ready to play in the centre. Now White needs to decide whether to follow suit or to start immediate kingside action. }
9. O-O-O d5 { Before White starts to push g4-g5 Black strikes in the centre. }
10. Qe1
{ The queen moves away from the d-file as White hopes to take advantage of the opposition of his rook and the black queen. }
10... e5
{ After White's last move there is no pressure on d5 so Black can expand in the centre. A more complex move to explore is  10...Bd7!?  . }
11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. exd5 cxd5
{ Black is actually spoilt for choice here. By taking with the pawn he is willing to sacrifice material for initiative and attack. He can also opt for the calmer alternative  12...Nxd5  , leading to a positional battle, for example,  13.Bc4  Be6  with a pleasant position for Black who will likely play Qc7 and then his ideas include a5, f5 followed by Bf6, putting the rooks in the centre or on the b-file. }
13. Bg5 { Putting maximum pressure on Black's centre. } 13... Be6
{ Developing the bishop and defending the pawn on d5. Black sacrifices the pawn on e5 in order to develop an attack on the white king. }
14. Bc4 Bb4 { Pinning the knight and threatening to take it. } 15. Qxe5 Bxc3
{ This forces White to take with the pawn, thus wrecking his king's shelter. }
16. bxc3 { Taking with the queen loses a piece to  16.Qxc3?  Rc8  . } 16... Nd7
{ Black continues the attack with tempo. } 17. Qg3 Qa5
{ Creating the multiple threats of taking the bishop on c4, taking on c3, and a check on a3. }
18. Bb3 Rfc8
{ A move that keeps the tension. It's perfectly possible to take on c3 with  18...Qxc3  19.Kb1  Kh8  with excellent play for Black as White's king is definitely the weaker one. After the rook move, Black keeps his options open:  he can take on c3, he can give check from a3 and then advance the a-pawn. White is under pressure here. }
*

