7... Nc6
{ It is also possible to castle first, the only difference lies in the line with an immediate g4, but against both  7...Nc6  8.g4  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2bppp/3ppn2/8/3NP3/2N1BP2/PPP3PP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...O-O  8.g4  Black is fine. Here is a sample line against the latter:  8...d5!  9.e5  Ne8  10.Qd2  Nc6  with good counterplay in the centre. In case of @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2bppp/3ppn2/8/3NP3/2N1BP2/PPP3PP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...O-O  8.Qd2  Nc6  we have a transposition to7...Nc6 8.Qd2 O-O. }
8. Qd2 O-O
{ Black moves the king from the centre and is ready to play in the centre. Now White needs to decide whether to follow suit or to start immediate kingside action. }
9. O-O-O d5 { Before White starts to push g4-g5 Black strikes in the centre. }
10. Qe1
{ The queen moves away from the d-file as White hopes to take advantage of the opposition of his rook and the black queen. }
10... e5
{ After White's last move there is no pressure on d5 so Black can expand in the centre. A more complex move to explore is  10...Bd7!?  . }
11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. exd5 cxd5
{ Black is actually spoilt for choice here. By taking with the pawn he is willing to sacrifice material for initiative and attack. He can also opt for the calmer alternative  12...Nxd5  , leading to a positional battle, for example,  13.Bc4  Be6  with a pleasant position for Black who will likely play Qc7 and then his ideas include a5, f5 followed by Bf6, putting the rooks in the centre or on the b-file. }
13. Bg5 { Putting maximum pressure on Black's centre. } 13... Be6
{ Developing the bishop and defending the pawn on d5. Black sacrifices the pawn on e5 in order to develop an attack on the white king. }
14. Qxe5 Qa5
{ Activating the queen and intending Rab8 when the threat of a sacrifice on b2 can become a very dangerous one. }
15. Nxd5
{ This is critical, taking a second pawn. Against other moves, Black plays Rab8 when an immediate tactical opportunity to take on b2 might arise or he will continue with Rfc8, Qb6, putting more pressure on White's queenside. }
15... Nxd5 { The natural response. } 16. Bxe7
{ White makes use of the pin along the 5th rank to regain the piece. } 16...
Rfc8
{ The rook is active on the c-file, while the other one can come to the b-file. Black now threatens to take on a2 or on c2, with the tactical idea of  17.--  Rxc2  18.Kxc2  Nb4+  , winning the undefended queen on e5. }
17. Bd3 { Covering the pawn on c2 and preventing Rxc2. } 17... Qxa2
{ Black regained one pawn and his attack is ongoing. Now the bishop on e7 hangs as the queen moved away from the pin along the 5th rank. }
18. Ba3 Nb6
{ Not an obvious move, but a good one. It creates the threat of Rd8 and then either Qa1 followed by Nc4, or the immediate Nc4. Black has more than enough compensation for the pawn, as he is doing all the attacking while White is on the defensive. }
