{ This is the move that characterises the English Attack. The idea is very simple - White strengthens the pawn on e4 and plans to play Qd2, castle long and then start a kingside attack with g4-g5, h4-h5 etc. Note that the moves  7.f4  O-O  transpose the chapterWhite Plays 6.f4, while the move @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2bppp/3ppn2/8/3NP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bc4  transposes to the chapter onthe Sozin. The move @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2bppp/3ppn2/8/3NP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Be2  transposes to the chapter on theClassical Variation. }
7... Nc6
{ It is also possible to castle first, the only difference lies in the line with an immediate g4, but against both  7...Nc6  8.g4  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2bppp/3ppn2/8/3NP3/2N1BP2/PPP3PP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...O-O  8.g4  Black is fine. Here is a sample line against the latter:  8...d5!  9.e5  Ne8  10.Qd2  Nc6  with good counterplay in the centre. In case of @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2bppp/3ppn2/8/3NP3/2N1BP2/PPP3PP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...O-O  8.Qd2  Nc6  we have a transposition to7...Nc6 8.Qd2 O-O. }
8. Qd2 O-O
{ Black moves the king from the centre and is ready to play in the centre. Now White needs to decide whether to follow suit or to start immediate kingside action. }
9. O-O-O d5 { Before White starts to push g4-g5 Black strikes in the centre. }
10. Be2
{ This calm move, simply developing the bishop when there is so much going on, is the trickiest one for Black to meet. }
10... Re8
{ A very deep and surreptitious move that prepares for the opening of the e-file after an exchange on d5, eyeing the bishops on e2 and e3. To understand why Black needs to prepare instead of playing in the centre and to see the strength of White's 10th move we can take a look at the endgame after  10...dxe4?!  11.Nxc6  bxc6  12.Qxd8  Rxd8  13.Rxd8  Bxd8  14.Rd1!  @@StartBracket@@taking the d-file with tempo, thanks to the fact that the bishop is hanging@@EndBracket@@  14...Be7  15.Nxe4  Nxe4  16.fxe4  e5  17.Bc4  with a favourable endgame as in the game So-Duda played online in 2018.   Black's other direct attempt  10...Nxd4?!  also doesn't work in view of  11.Bxd4  dxe4  12.fxe4  when again the bishop on e2 is useful as the white rook can come to f1 while White already threatens e5. Having seen the problems with direct play we now understand that Black needs to be more patient - hence the rook move. }
11. h4
{ This is more subtle than 11.g4 as it avoids the weakening created by moving the g-pawn, as we saw in the analysis ofthat line. }
11... Bb4
{ Without a target on g4 the exchange after  11...dxe4?!  12.Nxc6  Qxd2  13.Rxd2  bxc6  14.Nxe4  Nxe4  15.fxe4  e5  16.Bc4!  is advantageous for White -  the bishop on e2 can move to c4 and prevent the development of Black's bishop to e6. By playing Bb4 Black pins the knight on c3 and puts more pressure on White's center with the main threat to push e5. }
12. g4
{ White expands as taking on e4 is unfavourable for Black. After  12.Nb3  Qe7  Black threatens to take the pawn  on e4 once he has removed the queen from the d-file. }
12... e5
{ Taking on e4 leads to a bad endgame as after  12...dxe4?!  13.Nxc6  Qxd2  14.Bxd2  bxc6  15.Nxe4  Nxe4  16.fxe4  the bishop on b4 is under attack and Black doesn't have time to consolidate with e5 and Be6. After the central expansion play becomes very sharp. }
13. Nxc6 bxc6 { Threatening d4 so White's play is forced. } 14. g5 Nh5
{ Black has a calmer alternative here in  14...Nxe4!?  15.fxe4  d4  16.Bxd4  exd4  17.Qxd4  Qxd4  18.Rxd4  Bc5  with good compensation for the pawn in view of the pair of bishops and White's exposed pawns. }
15. exd5 Ng3 { The knight jumps back from the rim to join the game. } 16. Rhe1
Nxe2+
{ Black obtains the pair of bishops now and this will form part of his compensation. }
17. Rxe2 Ba6 { Activating the bishop. } 18. dxc6
{ In case of  18.Ree1  Qa5  Black's play is similar. } 18... Qa5
{ Creating a lot of threats: Ra@@StartBracket@@e@@EndBracket@@d8, Bxc3 and Qxa2 apart from the simple one to take the rook on e2. }
19. Rg2
{ White must keep the e1-square free for the queen. In case of the careless  19.Ree1?  Red8  Black wins as the queen must leave the knight on c3 without defence. }
19... Rad8 { Continuing with the forcing play. } 20. Qe1 Rxd1+
{ Forcing White to take with the king. } 21. Kxd1
{ Taking with queen would allow Black to take the knight and regain one pawn in addition to wrecking White's queenside. }
21... Bb5
{ Black wants to collect the pawn on c6 when he will have great compensation in view of his strong bishops in an open position and the continuous threats on the queenside. If White plays  22.c7  Black should flick in  22...Bc6  first before taking on c7 because the immediate  22...Qxc7?  runs into  23.Nxb5!  and after  23...Qd7  24.Bd2  Bxd2  25.Rxd2  Qxb5  Black is lost being a pawn down for no compensation. }
