12. Nb3 { White opens the d-file. } 12... Qe7
{ Removing the queen from the d-file and threatening to take on e4. The immediate  12...dxe4?!  gives White initiative in the endgame after  13.Qxd8  Rxd8  14.Rxd8  Nxd8  15.Rd1  Nc6  16.Nxe4  Nxe4  17.fxe4  when Black finds it difficult to develop his queenside. }
13. a3
{ Forcing Black to take on c3 and hoping to take advantage of the weakened dark squares afterwards. }
13... Bxc3 14. Qxc3 dxe4 { Black accepts the pawn sacrifice. } 15. Bc5
{ White plays on the dark squares. In case of  15.fxe4  Nxe4  16.Qc4  Nf6  Black will play e5 next, solving the problem of the development of the light-squared bishop. }
15... Qc7 { No other available square for the queen. } 16. Bd6 Qb6 17. g4
{ White wants to destabilise the knight on f6. } 17... Qf2
{ An important counter-attacking move. The bishop on e2 is short of good squares. }
18. Rhe1 Nd5 { Now the queen on c3 is harassed. } 19. Qc5 Qxc5
{ The exchange is welcome for Black who is a pawn up in the endgame. } 20. Nxc5
Ne3
{ The knight is quite mobile. In connection with Black's next move, it manages to exchange the annoying bishop on d6. }
21. Rd2 exf3
{ Now the bishop on e2 will have to give up control over the c4-square. } 22.
Bxf3 Nc4
{ The ideal square for the knight: it attacks the bishop on d6 and supports the e5 push that opens the h3-c8 diagonal for the light-squared bishop. }
23. Rdd1 e5
{ Black is fine in this double-edged endgame. He is a pawn up and no longer has development problems. He can eliminate the bishop on d6 and bring the king to the centre with Kf8. }
