{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. Bc4
{ The Sozin Attack is a universal weapon against many Sicilians. However, against the Scheveningen it is less optimal as with the black pawn already on e6 Black can play for quick development, save on the move a6 @@StartBracket@@when we can have a transposition to the Najdorf@@EndBracket@@ and aim for fast counterplay. }
6... Be7
{ A few words about the move-order: against the Sozin Black intends to use the absence of the pawn on a6 in order to use that square for the knight's route to c5, namely Na6-c5. That is why he first develops the kingside and then embarks on the knight maneuver. This is different from the usual lines when Black develops the knight to c6. }
7. Be3 O-O 8. Qe2
{ This is the setup known as the Velimirovic Attack. Its idea is simple: White wants to castle long and then start pushing g4-g5. Note that the move 8.Bb3 transposes to thelines after 7.Bb3. }
8... Qa5
{ Without the bishop on b3 there is less sense to embark on the Na6-c5 maneuver. Here Black has the fully satisfactory transposition to the Najdorf after  8...a6  , against which the Velimirovic Attack is not considered dangerous. However, with the queen move, Black avoids that direct transposition and takes the game into unexplored territory. The immediate threat is to take the pawn on e4 in view of the pin on the e1-a5 diagonal. }
9. O-O-O a6
{ With the help of the queen on a5 sooner or later the b-pawn will get all the way to b4. }
10. Bb3 b5 { Threatening b4. } 11. a3
{ White cannot allow the knight on c3 to be chased away. After  11.f3?!  b4  12.Nb1  Qc7  with the idea of a5-a4 Black's attack is very strong. }
11... Bb7
{ Putting pressure on White's centre. The immediate  11...b4  is also possible, after  12.axb4  Qxb4  13.g4  Qb7  @@StartBracket@@hitting the pawn on e4@@EndBracket@@  14.f3  Nc6  @@StartBracket@@challenging the knight on d4 and easing off the pressure on e6@@EndBracket@@  15.Nxc6  Qxc6  play is unclear where Black's chances are not worse. }
12. g4
{ This is also possible, and in view of the threat of g5 Black must create counterplay immediately. }
12... b4
{ Note that Black still couldn't take the pawn on e4 because after  12...Nxe4?  13.Nxe4  Bxe4  14.Bd2  he loses the bishop on e4 in view of the double attack on the queen on a5 and the bishop on e4. }
13. axb4 Qa1+ { Harassing White's king and forcing it to go to d2. } 14. Kd2
{ Covering with the knight is bad, as after  14.Nb1?  Nc6  15.Nxc6  Bxc6  Black's rooks join the attack with Rfc8 and Rab8. }
14... Qxb2 15. Rb1 Qa3 16. Nxe6
{ White must be aggressive, after the lame  16.f3?  d5!  Black's initiative is decisive. }
16... Rc8
{ White's idea consisted of  16...fxe6?  17.Bxe6  Kh8  18.Rb3  @@StartBracket@@or even 18.f3 first@@EndBracket@@ when the queen on a3 is short of squares.  With the rook move, Black creates counterthreats of his own, for example Rxc3 and Nxe4. }
17. f3 { Defending the vulnerable pawn on e4. } 17... Rxc3
{ Black continues in ultra-aggressive manner. He will capture the knight on e6 but before that wins a tempo to develop the knight from b8. }
18. Kxc3 Nc6
{ Threatening Qxb4, thus forcing the white king to retreat again. } 19. Kd2
fxe6 20. Bxe6+ Kh8
{ The position is a mess, but Black's safer king and mobile knights make his position easier to play. }
