{ A few words about the move-order: against the Sozin Black intends to use the absence of the pawn on a6 in order to use that square for the knight's route to c5, namely Na6-c5. That is why he first develops the kingside and then embarks on the knight maneuver. This is different from the usual lines when Black develops the knight to c6. }
7. Bb3
{ White usually drops the bishop back to b3 automatically, as playing  7.a3  is too slow: after  7...O-O  8.Ba2  Nc6  followed by Bd7, Nxd4 and then either b5 or Bc6 Black gets easy play. There is some sense to leave the bishop on c4 if White opts for the set-up from the Velimirovic Attack, since in that case sometimes the bishop can drop back to d3. Note that the move  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2bppp/3ppn2/8/2BNP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.O-O  after  7...O-O  8.Bb3  Na6  9.f4  Nc5  transposes to theline after 7.Bb3 O-O 8.f4 Na6 9.O-O Nc5. }
7... O-O
{ Black finishes development of the kingside and will now start the knight transfer to c5. }
8. f4
{ White generally has two plans: to castle long or short. With both these plans White plays the moves f4, Be3 and Qf3. There are also a few deviations that we will look at. Note that the hasty  8.g4  is met by  8...d5  . }
8... Na6 { Going to c5 next. } 9. O-O Nc5 10. e5
{ This is an independent attempt. After  10.Qf3  we have a transposition to thelines after 9.Qf3. }
10... dxe5 { Black naturally takes. Now the pawn on e5 can become weak. } 11.
fxe5 Nxb3
{ Black eliminates the bishop on b3 to decrease White's control over the d5-square. }
12. axb3 Nd5
{ The knight escapes and from d5 it controls the squares e3 and f4, thus making the development of White's bishop more difficult. }
13. Kh1
{ A useful move, removing the king from the vulnerable diagonal. In case of  13.Ne4?!  Qc7  @@StartBracket@@attacking the pawn on e5@@EndBracket@@  14.Nf3  b5!  Black will develop the light-squared bishop on the long diagonal. }
13... Nxc3
{ Black wants to develop his light-squared bishop to d7, before doing so he avoids Nxd5 exd5. }
14. bxc3 Bd7
{ Black is fully developed now. He has the pair of bishops and the better structure, but White has a good knight on d4 and control over the dark squares. In order to liberate his play Black will resort to the push f5 or f6. Another idea for Black in order to obtain play on the queenside is the push a5-a4, with or without the help of the b-pawn. }
15. Bf4
{ After  15.Qg4  f5!  16.exf6  Rxf6  Black solved all his problems as the rook can come to g6 if needed. }
15... f5
{ Again this is the simplest, the sooner Black eliminates the pawn on e5 the better. It is possible to keep it complex with  15...a5  16.Qg4  Kh8  with the idea to push a4. }
16. exf6 Bxf6
{ Black freed his play. The immediate threat is e5, while the idea to push a5, b5 and a4 to obtain a passed pawn on the queenside still remains. }
