[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. The Sozin Attack - 6.Bc4"]
[Black "The Sozin Attack - 6.Bc4 Be7 7.Bb3 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. Bc4
{ The Sozin Attack is a universal weapon against many Sicilians. However, against the Scheveningen it is less optimal as with the black pawn already on e6 Black can play for quick development, save on the move a6 @@StartBracket@@when we can have a transposition to the Najdorf@@EndBracket@@ and aim for fast counterplay. }
6... Be7
{ A few words about the move-order: against the Sozin Black intends to use the absence of the pawn on a6 in order to use that square for the knight's route to c5, namely Na6-c5. That is why he first develops the kingside and then embarks on the knight maneuver. This is different from the usual lines when Black develops the knight to c6. }
7. Bb3
{ White usually drops the bishop back to b3 automatically, as playing  7.a3  is too slow: after  7...O-O  8.Ba2  Nc6  followed by Bd7, Nxd4 and then either b5 or Bc6 Black gets easy play. There is some sense to leave the bishop on c4 if White opts for the set-up from the Velimirovic Attack, since in that case sometimes the bishop can drop back to d3. Note that the move  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2bppp/3ppn2/8/2BNP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.O-O  after  7...O-O  8.Bb3  Na6  9.f4  Nc5  transposes to theline after 7.Bb3 O-O 8.f4 Na6 9.O-O Nc5. }
7... O-O
{ Black finishes development of the kingside and will now start the knight transfer to c5. }
8. f4
{ White generally has two plans: to castle long or short. With both these plans White plays the moves f4, Be3 and Qf3. There are also a few deviations that we will look at. Note that the hasty  8.g4  is met by  8...d5  . }
8... Na6 { Going to c5 next. } 9. Qf3 Nc5 10. Be3 a5
{ Again a transposition to the Najdorf with  10...a6  is possible, as the theoretical verdict on those positions is that Black has no problems, but the Scheveningen option to push the a-pawn for two squares is an extra bonus here that Black can gladly take! The threat is a4-a3 to harass the bishop on b3 and to weaken White's queenside. Note that Black has another option in @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2bppp/3ppn2/2n5/3NPP2/1BN1BQ2/PPP3PP/R3K2R b KQ - 4 10@@EndFEN@@  10...d5!?  which leads to unclear play after both  11.e5  Nfe4  and @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2bppp/4pn2/2np4/3NPP2/1BN1BQ2/PPP3PP/R3K2R w KQ - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.exd5  Nxb3  12.axb3  exd5  . }
11. a4 { This stops a4, but it weakens White's structure. } 11... e5
{ Chasing away the knight from d4 so that Black can capture on b3 and force cxb3, which would wreck White's queenside pawns. }
12. Nf5
{ The other moves are clearly inferior,  12.Ndb5?!  Nxb3  13.cxb3  Be6  attacks the pawn on b3.   The queenside weaknesses are also exposed after  12.fxe5  dxe5  13.Nf5  Bxf5  14.Qxf5  Nxb3  15.cxb3  Qd3!  . }
12... Bxf5 13. exf5 e4
{ Once the path of the e-pawn has been cleared the passer should advance. } 14.
Qh3
{ Black plays the same if White retreats to e2:  14.Qe2  Nxb3  15.cxb3  d5  with good play. }
14... Nxb3 { Eliminating the bishop and wrecking White's queenside. } 15. cxb3
d5
{ The central pawns are strong, so White must do his utmost to blockade them. }
16. O-O-O
{ This gets the king away from the centre and enhances White's control over the blockading square on d4. }
16... Bb4
{ The knight on c3 exerts pressure on the central pawns so Black wants to exchange it. }
17. Bd4 { Threatening to take on f6 and d5. } 17... Bxc3
{ Black defends his central pawns by eliminating the piece that attacked them. }
18. Bxc3 Re8
{ Rook behind pawn and introducing the threat of e3. The play is very sharp. Black wants to push his central pawns but also has the option to play on the queenside with b5.   In fact, he can also try  18...b5!?  here, again with a messy position where his chances are quite good. }
