6. Bc4
{ The Sozin Attack is a universal weapon against many Sicilians. However, against the Scheveningen it is less optimal as with the black pawn already on e6 Black can play for quick development, save on the move a6 @@StartBracket@@when we can have a transposition to the Najdorf@@EndBracket@@ and aim for fast counterplay. }
6... Be7
{ A few words about the move-order: against the Sozin Black intends to use the absence of the pawn on a6 in order to use that square for the knight's route to c5, namely Na6-c5. That is why he first develops the kingside and then embarks on the knight maneuver. This is different from the usual lines when Black develops the knight to c6. }
7. Bb3
{ White usually drops the bishop back to b3 automatically, as playing  7.a3  is too slow: after  7...O-O  8.Ba2  Nc6  followed by Bd7, Nxd4 and then either b5 or Bc6 Black gets easy play. There is some sense to leave the bishop on c4 if White opts for the set-up from the Velimirovic Attack, since in that case sometimes the bishop can drop back to d3. Note that the move  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2bppp/3ppn2/8/2BNP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.O-O  after  7...O-O  8.Bb3  Na6  9.f4  Nc5  transposes to theline after 7.Bb3 O-O 8.f4 Na6 9.O-O Nc5. }
7... O-O
{ Black finishes development of the kingside and will now start the knight transfer to c5. }
8. f4
{ White generally has two plans: to castle long or short. With both these plans White plays the moves f4, Be3 and Qf3. There are also a few deviations that we will look at. Note that the hasty  8.g4  is met by  8...d5  . }
8... Na6 { Going to c5 next. } 9. Qf3 Nc5 10. Be3 a5
{ Again a transposition to the Najdorf with  10...a6  is possible, as the theoretical verdict on those positions is that Black has no problems, but the Scheveningen option to push the a-pawn for two squares is an extra bonus here that Black can gladly take! The threat is a4-a3 to harass the bishop on b3 and to weaken White's queenside. Note that Black has another option in @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2bppp/3ppn2/2n5/3NPP2/1BN1BQ2/PPP3PP/R3K2R b KQ - 4 10@@EndFEN@@  10...d5!?  which leads to unclear play after both  11.e5  Nfe4  and @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2bppp/4pn2/2np4/3NPP2/1BN1BQ2/PPP3PP/R3K2R w KQ - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.exd5  Nxb3  12.axb3  exd5  . }
11. O-O-O
{ The sharpest try, as after a4-a3 White's queenside will be weakened. } 11...
a4 12. Bc4 a3
{ A natural advance of the a-pawn that weakens the dark squares around White's king. }
13. b3
{ White shouldn't allow axb2, which would completely destroy White's queenside shelter. }
13... Nfxe4
{ This trick works again, only this time it's much more complicated than in theline with 11.O-O: here White has a rook on the d-file and this makes a considerable difference, as we shall shortly see. Black has an alternative in  13...Qa5  , but that one allows White to force a repetition if he wishes to after  14.Bd2  Qb6  15.Be3  Qa5  . }
14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Qxe4 d5 { Black regains the piece thanks to this fork. } 16.
Qf3
{ White keeps the d-file open for the rook. After  16.Bxd5?!  exd5  17.Qd3  Bf6  with Re8 next Black is simply better. White's king is weak and so are the light squares in White's camp, the e4-square in particular. }
16... dxc4 17. Nxe6
{ This is White's best chance. The rook on d1 makes the difference. } 17...
Bxe6
{ A fine positional queen sacrifice! Black has a valid alternative in  17...Qa5  18.Bd2  Qa7  19.Nxf8  cxb3  20.Qxb3  Bxf8  when he sacrifices an exchange but the weak white king gives him more than enough compensation. }
18. Rxd8 Rfxd8
{ This curious position is much more dangerous for White than it may look like at first sight. For example, now he has only one move in order not to be worse. }
19. Rd1
{ This is a natural move and a great line to showcase the dangers White is facing here. }
19... cxb3 { Black opens the position of White's king. } 20. Rxd8+ Rxd8 21.
cxb3 h5
{ Creating luft before commencing the attack. Black now plans Rc8, Bb4, Bf5 and Rc2xa2 or the simple Bxb3. White is helpess against this coordinated attack. }
