{ The Sozin Attack is a universal weapon against many Sicilians. However, against the Scheveningen it is less optimal as with the black pawn already on e6 Black can play for quick development, save on the move a6 @@StartBracket@@when we can have a transposition to the Najdorf@@EndBracket@@ and aim for fast counterplay. }
6... Be7
{ A few words about the move-order: against the Sozin Black intends to use the absence of the pawn on a6 in order to use that square for the knight's route to c5, namely Na6-c5. That is why he first develops the kingside and then embarks on the knight maneuver. This is different from the usual lines when Black develops the knight to c6. }
7. Bb3
{ White usually drops the bishop back to b3 automatically, as playing  7.a3  is too slow: after  7...O-O  8.Ba2  Nc6  followed by Bd7, Nxd4 and then either b5 or Bc6 Black gets easy play. There is some sense to leave the bishop on c4 if White opts for the set-up from the Velimirovic Attack, since in that case sometimes the bishop can drop back to d3. Note that the move  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2bppp/3ppn2/8/2BNP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.O-O  after  7...O-O  8.Bb3  Na6  9.f4  Nc5  transposes to theline after 7.Bb3 O-O 8.f4 Na6 9.O-O Nc5. }
7... O-O
{ Black finishes development of the kingside and will now start the knight transfer to c5. }
8. Be3 Na6
{ Black develops the knight to a6, a typical development in the Sozin. } 9. Qe2
{ Going for the Velimirovic set-up, but the knight is quick to come to c5 and attack the pawn on e4 and the bishop on b3. }
9... Nc5 { Forcing White to defend the pawn on e4 by f3. } 10. f3 Nxb3
{ This is the simplest, eliminating the bishop on b3 and following up with central play. }
11. axb3 e5 { The knight has only one good square to go to. } 12. Ndb5
{ Going to f5 is bad,  12.Nf5?  Bxf5  13.exf5  d5  gives Black a big advantage thanks to the powerful pawn centre. }
12... a6
{ Removing the pawn from the attacked square and threatening Be6 when the knight on b5 would hang. }
13. Na3 d5
{ Achieving the central push and equalising comfortably. In fact, it is now White who needs to seek equality. }
14. exd5 Nxd5 15. Nxd5 Qxd5 16. Nc4
{ The only move for White that keeps the balance. Thanks to the threat of Nb6 White makes sure that he won't allow Black to remain with the pair of bishops. }
16... Qc6
{ A move that invites White to take a pawn for which Black will have excellent compensation in view of the preserved bishop pair and the open e-file. The simple  16...Qe6  17.Nb6  Rb8  is sufficient for equality. }
17. Nb6
{ White shouldn't fall for it. In case of  17.Nxe5?!  Qc7  followed by Re8 Black has great play. }
17... Rb8 18. Nxc8 Rbxc8
{ Black is comfortably equal here. His position is the easier one to play as White still needs to solve the issue with the pressure on the c-file and the position of his king. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. The Fianchetto Line - 6.g3 "]
[Black "The Fianchetto Line 6.g3 - 9.h3 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. g3
{ The fianchetto is always a decent option for White in the Open Sicilian. White wants to play Bg2, castle short and then decide whether to play on the kingside by expanding with g4, f4 etc. or to play on the queenside with either Nxc6 followed by Be3, Na4 and c4, or with Nb3, Be3, a4-a5. }
6... Nc6
{ Black should be precise with this and the next move as after Bg2 the long diagonal becomes sensitive. For example  6...Be7  already means that after  7.Bg2  the move  7...Nc6?!  is not very good in view of  8.Nxc6  bxc6  9.e5  when White manages to inflict structural damage. }
7. Bg2
{ White already threatens to use the strength of the fianchettoed bishop by taking on c6 and pushing e5, attacking the pawn on c6. }
7... Bd7
{ A very important move. Black must defend against White's threat of Nxc6 and e5. Now in case of  8.Nxc6  he can safely recapture with  8...Bxc6  . }
8. O-O
{ White finishes development of the kingside and is ready for the middlegame. }
8... Be7
{ Black also continues developing and is ready to castle short. Now White has a wide choice of continuations and plans. }
9. h3 { This move is played with the idea to continue with g4. } 9... O-O
{ Black is now fully developed. } 10. Nde2
{ Avoiding an exchange on d4, which would ease Black's play. To illustrate, in case of  10.g4  Nxd4  11.Qxd4  Bc6  Black is perfectly fine as he exchanged one pair of knights,  liberating the c6-square for the light-squared bishop in the process, and can continue with his queenside play of b5, possibly a5 and b4. This exchange on d4 followed by Bc6 is typical for many lines in the Scheveningen. }
10... Rc8
{ Removing the rook from the long diagonal and activating it on the c-file. }
11. g4 h6
{ A typical move in the Fianchetto Line: Black stops g5 and is not worried about the weakening of his kingside because his own queenside counterplay comes faster than White's preparation to push through g5 with the help of f4 or h4. }
12. Ng3
{ White continues regrouping.  The knight on g3 lends more support to the e4-pawn and can be included in the kingside activities.   In case of  12.f4  b5!  Black's counterplay is fast as White cannot take the pawn on b5 in view of the double attack  13.Nxb5?  Qb6  14.Nbd4  e5  . }
12... Ne5
{ The knight is heading to c4, from where it will control the e3-square @@StartBracket@@making the development of White's dark-squared bishop more difficult@@EndBracket@@ and pressurise White's queenside, particularly the pawn on b2. }
13. f4 Nc4 { Threatening Qb6 followed by Ne3. } 14. Kh1
{ Removing the king from the sensitive g1-a7 diagonal. } 14... b5
{ Black is moving forward with his queenside activity and has great play. All of these moves have been played in my game against GM Kevin Spraggett from the San Sebastian tournament in 2011. I got an advantage with Black and after some adventures, the game ended in a draw. }
