[White "6. The Fianchetto Line - 6.g3 "]
[Black "The Fianchetto Line 6.g3 - 9.a4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. g3
{ The fianchetto is always a decent option for White in the Open Sicilian. White wants to play Bg2, castle short and then decide whether to play on the kingside by expanding with g4, f4 etc. or to play on the queenside with either Nxc6 followed by Be3, Na4 and c4, or with Nb3, Be3, a4-a5. }
6... Nc6
{ Black should be precise with this and the next move as after Bg2 the long diagonal becomes sensitive. For example  6...Be7  already means that after  7.Bg2  the move  7...Nc6?!  is not very good in view of  8.Nxc6  bxc6  9.e5  when White manages to inflict structural damage. }
7. Bg2
{ White already threatens to use the strength of the fianchettoed bishop by taking on c6 and pushing e5, attacking the pawn on c6. }
7... Bd7
{ A very important move. Black must defend against White's threat of Nxc6 and e5. Now in case of  8.Nxc6  he can safely recapture with  8...Bxc6  . }
8. O-O
{ White finishes development of the kingside and is ready for the middlegame. }
8... Be7
{ Black also continues developing and is ready to castle short. Now White has a wide choice of continuations and plans. }
9. a4
{ A common move in the Sicilian, taking some queenside space and preventing b5. }
9... O-O { Black completes his development. } 10. Re1
{ Other moves transpose, for example  10.Be3  transposes to the 9.Be3 O-O 10.a4 line, while  10.Nb3  transposes tothe line 9.Nb3 O-O 10.a4. }
10... Nxd4
{ Black has more than one satisfactory way here. For example a good alternative is  10...a6  11.Nxc6  Bxc6  12.a5  Nd7  with b5 next. With the exchange of the knights he liberates the c6-square for the bishop. }
11. Qxd4 Bc6
{ Black has a very flexible position. His main plan is to push b5, but he will be careful not to allow the fixing of his queenside by a5, so he can play more slowly with b6 first and then followed by a6 and ultimately b5 @@StartBracket@@helped by Rb8 or Qc7-b7@@EndBracket@@. }
12. Qd3 { White removes the queen from d4 and sets a small trap. } 12... a6
{ Black takes control over the b5-square and avoids any Nb5 ideas. This does allow a5, but White's trap consisted in  12...b6?  @@StartBracket@@not allowing a5, but in fact losing@@EndBracket@@  13.e5!  and with both the bishop on c6 and the knight on f6 hanging White wins at least a pawn after Black puts the knight on d5. Now we see why it was important to remove the queen from d4 as in the line  13...Bxg2?  14.exf6  Black doesn't have the recapture  14...Bxf6  with a tempo, attacking the queen on d4, so White simply takes the piece with  15.Kxg2  . }
13. a5 Nd7
{ Covering the b6-square. Note that again moving the b-pawn loses to the same trick:  13...b5?  14.e5!  and after  14...Nd5  (only move)  15.Nxd5  Bxd5  16.Bxd5  exd5  17.e6!  Black's position is falling apart. }
14. Be3 Rc8 { Activating the rook and preparing a possible Qc7-b8. } 15. Bd4
{ Black's position is extremely solid so White doesn't really have any constructive plans. For example the direct  15.Na4  is effectively met by  15...Bxa4  16.Rxa4  Qc7  @@StartBracket@@attacking c2@@EndBracket@@  17.c3  Nc5  18.Bxc5  Qxc5  with easy equality. }
15... Ne5 { Activating the knight. } 16. Qe2 Qc7
{ In anticipation of Bb6, so that the queen can slip back to b8, not hindering the communication between the rooks. }
17. Bb6 Qb8
{ Black is very compact. He can continue with Bf6 or Bd8 to chase away the bishop on b6 and then even f5 to start activities in the centre and the kingside. }
