Nxc6 { Or  11.a4  a6  and again threatening Nxd4 and b5. } 11... Bxc6 12. a4 a6
13. Re1
{ In case of  13.a5  Black can decide whether to go for  13...b5  14.axb6  Qxb6  with comfortable play or @@StartFEN@@2rq1rk1/1p2bppp/p1bppn2/P7/4P3/1PN3P1/1BP2PBP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Qc7  followed by Rfd8 and d5. }
13... b5
{ Black has many other moves, like  13...Qc7  ,  13...h6  ,  13...Re8  ,  13...Qa5  etc. but the queenside expansion looks like the easiest to remember as it is the typical Sicilian move. }
14. axb5 axb5 { Now Black threatens b4. } 15. Ba3 Qb6
{ Developing the queen and threatening b4. } 16. Bb4
{ Of course, taking on d6 loses after  16.Bxd6?  Rfd8  17.e5  Bxg2  and the knight on c3 also hangs. }
16... Qb7
{ Exerting pressure on the long diagonal and allowing Rfd8, which wasn't possible in view of the skewer with Ba5. Black is obviously very comfortable in this position. After Rfd8 he can try to push d5, fight for the a-file with Ra8 or play Rd7 with the idea of Bd8-b6. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. The Fianchetto Line - 6.g3 "]
[Black "The Fianchetto Line 6.g3 - 9.Be3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. g3
{ The fianchetto is always a decent option for White in the Open Sicilian. White wants to play Bg2, castle short and then decide whether to play on the kingside by expanding with g4, f4 etc. or to play on the queenside with either Nxc6 followed by Be3, Na4 and c4, or with Nb3, Be3, a4-a5. }
6... Nc6
{ Black should be precise with this and the next move as after Bg2 the long diagonal becomes sensitive. For example  6...Be7  already means that after  7.Bg2  the move  7...Nc6?!  is not very good in view of  8.Nxc6  bxc6  9.e5  when White manages to inflict structural damage. }
7. Bg2
{ White already threatens to use the strength of the fianchettoed bishop by taking on c6 and pushing e5, attacking the pawn on c6. }
7... Bd7
{ A very important move. Black must defend against White's threat of Nxc6 and e5. Now in case of  8.Nxc6  he can safely recapture with  8...Bxc6  . }
8. O-O
{ White finishes development of the kingside and is ready for the middlegame. }
8... Be7
{ Black also continues developing and is ready to castle short. Now White has a wide choice of continuations and plans. }
9. Be3 { This is a natural development of White's bishop. } 9... O-O 10. a4
{ Note that this can also arise after @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/pp1bbppp/2nppn2/8/3NP3/2N3P1/PPP2PBP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 5 9@@EndFEN@@  9.a4  O-O  10.Be3  . }
10... Ne5
{ This is a typical move, landing the knight on c4 would cause White problems with the bishop on e3 and the pawn on b2, so White must prevent it. }
11. b3 Rc8
{ Black continues to bring his pieces into the game with tempo. The rook attacks the knight and is removed from the long diagonal. }
12. Nce2
{ Moving away and intending c4. In case of  12.Qd2?!  d5!  13.exd5  Bb4  we can see how Black can use the weakness of the dark-squares created by White's move b3. }
12... d5
{ The liberating push is possible because with his last move White ceased to control the d5-square. }
13. exd5 Nxd5
{ It is also possible to take with  13...exd5  , which leads to complex play. }
14. Bd2 Qc7
{ Developing the queen, defending  the b7-pawn on the long diagonal and liberating the d8-square for the rook from f8.   Black has other satisfactory moves, like  14...Nc6  ,  14...Bc6  and  14...Qb6  , all of them giving him good play. }
15. Nb5 Qb8 { Tucking away the queen, which was also the point of 14...Qc7. }
16. c4 Nb4
{ The knight is nicely slotted on b4. Black will continue with Bc6 to exchange White's fianchettoed bishop with very good play thanks to his harmonious development and the blockade on the dark squares on the queenside. }
*

