{ White finishes development of the kingside and is ready for the middlegame. }
8... Be7
{ Black also continues developing and is ready to castle short. Now White has a wide choice of continuations and plans. }
9. Be3 { This is a natural development of White's bishop. } 9... O-O 10. Qe2
{ White continues with development and keeps it flexible - he can put either rook on d1. }
10... a6
{ Since White will put a rook on d1 Black takes measures against a possible Nb5, which would attack the pawn on d6. At the same time he prepares the typical queenside expansion with b5. }
11. Rad1 { This is natural, but it allows a typical sequence by Black. } 11...
Nxd4 { First Black lures a piece on d4. } 12. Bxd4 e5
{ In order to gain tempo and shut the bishop on g2. } 13. Be3 b5
{ So that he can expand freely on the queenside, not fearing the opening of the long diagonal after e5. Black has easy play here, he will continue with Be6, Qc7, b4, Rc8 etc. in different move orders. }
