{ White finishes development of the kingside and is ready for the middlegame. }
8... Be7
{ Black also continues developing and is ready to castle short. Now White has a wide choice of continuations and plans. }
9. Be3 { This is a natural development of White's bishop. } 9... O-O 10. Qe2
{ White continues with development and keeps it flexible - he can put either rook on d1. }
10... a6
{ Since White will put a rook on d1 Black takes measures against a possible Nb5, which would attack the pawn on d6. At the same time he prepares the typical queenside expansion with b5. }
11. a4
{ This is an attempt to stop b5 and at the same time threatening Nxc6 and a5, fixing the b6-square. }
11... Ne5
{ Black avoids the exchange on c6 and targets the c4-square. He wants to play Rc8 and Nc4. }
12. Rad1 Rc8 13. Bc1
{ White regrouped to remove the bishop from e3 and defend the pawn on b2 without shutting out the rook on a1. }
13... Nc4
{ Following the plan and provoking b3, in order to weaken White's knight on c3.   Black has good alternatives here, like  13...Rc4!?  , provoking  14.f4  Qb6  with interesting complications, or the simple @@StartFEN@@2rq1rk1/1p1bbppp/p2ppn2/4n3/P2NP3/2N3P1/1PP1QPBP/2BR1RK1 b - - 4 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Qc7  14.f4  Nc6  15.Nb3  Nb4  with complex play. }
14. b3 Ne5 15. Bb2 Qa5 { Continuing the attack on the knight. } 16. Qe1
{ Defending the knight and threatening Nd5. } 16... Bd8
{ Defending the queen and removing the bishop from the undefended square. It also introduces the idea of Bb6. The middlegame is complex, but Black has good play as he is active on the queenside while White cannot even start anything on the kingside. }
