6. g3
{ The fianchetto is always a decent option for White in the Open Sicilian. White wants to play Bg2, castle short and then decide whether to play on the kingside by expanding with g4, f4 etc. or to play on the queenside with either Nxc6 followed by Be3, Na4 and c4, or with Nb3, Be3, a4-a5. }
6... Nc6
{ Black should be precise with this and the next move as after Bg2 the long diagonal becomes sensitive. For example the move  6...Be7  after  7.Bg2  already means that  7...Nc6?!  is not very good in view of  8.Nxc6  bxc6  9.e5  when White manages to inflict structural damage. }
7. Bg2
{ White already threatens to use the strength of the fianchettoed bishop by taking on c6 and pushing e5, attacking the pawn on c6. }
7... Bd7
{ A very important move. Black must defend against White's threat of Nxc6 and e5. Now in case of  8.Nxc6  he can safely recapture with  8...Bxc6  . }
8. O-O
{ White finishes development of the kingside and is ready for the middlegame. }
8... Be7
{ Black also continues developing and is ready to castle short. Now White has a wide choice of continuations and plans. }
9. Be3 { This is a natural development of White's bishop. } 9... O-O 10. Qe2
{ White continues with development and keeps it flexible - he can put either rook on d1. }
10... a6
{ Since White will put a rook on d1 Black takes measures against a possible Nb5, which would attack the pawn on d6. At the same time he prepares the typical queenside expansion with b5. }
11. Nxc6
{ Opening the g1-a7 diagonal and intending a4-a5, fixing the b6-square. } 11...
Bxc6 { Black recaptures naturally, placing the bishop on the long diagonal. }
12. a4 { Preventing b5 and intending a5, which would fix the b6-square. } 12...
Qa5
{ Activating the queen and preventing a5. Black wants to continue with Rfd8 and Rac8 and then either move the queen from a5 to push b5 or to play in the centre with e5 or d5. }
13. Rfb1 { With this move White wants to expand on the queenside with b4. }
13... Rfc8
{ Not  13...Rfd8  since after  14.b4  White will follow up with a5 and Bb6, attacking the rook on d8. The other rook stays on a8 in order to keep the a6-pawn protected in case White continues with b5 and bxa6. }
14. b4 Qc7 { Increasing Black's presence on the c-file. } 15. a5
{ In case of  15.b5  Bd7  Black obtains counterplay along the c-file. } 15...
Be8
{ Here is another reason why the rook from f8 had to go to c8 - now the bishop on e8 doesn't block it and moving to e8 leaves the d7-square available for the knight. }
16. Rb3 { Defending the knight on c3. } 16... Nd7
{ Covering the b6-square and intending Bf6. The middlegame is balanced, Black has a safe position and can continue to maneuver with ideas like Bf6, g6 or, if appropriate, start some activity with Ne5-c4 or even b5. }
