{ Introduction to a very interesting idea. The alternative is  13...h6  14.Be3  Nh7  , stopping White's kingside advance. }
14. g5 { This allows Black to counterattack White's advanced kingside pawns. }
14... e5
{ The move  14...f6!?  is an equally good alternative, after  15.h4  fxg5  16.hxg5  e5  White's kingside pawns are under pressure. }
15. Qh5 { This only looks aggressive. } 15... exf4
{ Liberating the e5-square for the knight. } 16. Bxf4 Nc7
{ Covering the d5-square and intending Ne5. Black has very rich piece play here, as he can continue with Ne6, targeting the bishop on f4 and the pawn on g5. }
