15. h4
{ The move  15.Nd5  is met by  15...exf4  16.h4  f6  with a transposition to this line. }
15... f6 { Black is doing all the attacking on the kingside! } 16. Nd5 exf4
{ Reducing the number of white pawns on the kingside. } 17. Rxf4
{ Or  17.Bxf4  fxg5  18.Nxe7  Qxe7  19.hxg5  Ne5  with an advantage to Black who has the safer king and the more compact position. }
17... Nc7
{ Now  17...fxg5  would be met by  18.Rxf8  Bxf8  19.Bxg5  and the black queen is short of squares. }
18. Nb6
{ White's best try. Massive exchanges on f6 leave Black better developed, for example,  18.gxf6  Bxf6  19.Nxf6  Rxf6  20.Rxf6  Qxf6  with excellent play. }
18... Rb8 19. Nxd7 Qxd7 20. Nd4 Ne5
{ Black is at least equal here. He has the safer king, while White has the kingside weaknesses to deal with. }
