{ The positional idea I wanted to demonstrate. Black is fighting for the dark squares, especially the e5-square. A perfectly valid alternative is  14...Bf6  threatening Bxc3 and Na5. }
15. e5
{ An ambitious attempt not to allow Black control the dark squares, which would happen in case of  15.f5  h6  @@StartBracket@@solidifying the pawn on g5 and intending further Ne5, Nf6@@EndBracket@@ or after @@StartFEN@@2rqnrk1/3bbp1p/p1npp3/1p4p1/4PPP1/PNN1B3/1PP3BP/R2Q1R1K w - - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15.Nd2  gxf4  16.Bxf4  Ne5  . }
15... gxf4
{ Forcing White to take on d6. However the exchanges will be in Black's favour. }
16. exd6 fxe3 17. dxe7 Nxe7
{ Black would like to continue with Bc6, exchanging the defender of White's king. Black strives for an endgame here as in that case he can use his mobile central majority, while in the middlegame he can try the sharp plan of Kh8 and f5, opening the g-file and exposing White's king. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. White Plays 6.f4"]
[Black "White Plays 6.f4 -  6...Be7 7.Nf3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. f4
{ Usually, after 6.f4 White aims to establish a so-called 3rd rank set-up with Be3, Bd3, Qf3 and then either O-O or O-O-O. }
6... Be7
{ An important move! Usually Black plays Nc6, but against the line with 6.f4 it is important to castle as soon as possible. In the line  6...Nc6  7.Be3  Be7  8.Qf3  e5  9.Nxc6  bxc6  10.f5  White seems to have the upper hand even though the lines are quite complicated. }
7. Nf3
{ Retreating the knight to f3 is a clear sign that White wants to play Bd3, O-O and then either Qe1-g3 or Qe2 and e5. }
7... Nc6
{ Black doesn't hurry with castling in order to have the option to play Nb4, to harass the bishop on d3. }
8. Bd3
{ If White starts with  8.a3  then after  8...O-O  9.Bd3  Qb6  makes it tricky for White to castle. Then  10.Qe2  is met by  10...e5  with easy play for Black. }
8... Nb4 { Going after the light-squared bishop. } 9. O-O Nxd3
{ Eliminating the important bishop. } 10. cxd3
{ White strengthens the centre and his plan is to play Be3, Nd4, Qf3 and to try to develop play on the kingside with the help of f5. }
10... b5 { But Black is faster with his queenside play. } 11. Kh1
{ Of course,  11.Nxb5?  Qb6  wins the knight on b5. } 11... Qb6
{ Defending the pawn on b5 and developing the queen. Black's plan is to push b4 and attack the knight on c3, which doesn't have good squares to go to. The immediate  11...b4?  doesn't work in view of  12.Qa4  and the pawn on b4 is lost. }
12. a3 a5 { Black expands on the queenside and plans a future b4. } 13. Qe1
{ Intending Be3. } 13... O-O
{ Finishing the development of the kingside. Note how Black didn't rush with the natural move Bb7 in order to be able to put the queen there in case of Be3. }
14. Be3 Qb7
{ Defending the rook and intending b4. Black has good play here, with the bishop pair and the plan of queenside advance. He can also take some time to finish development with moves like Rd8 and Bd7. }
