[White "7. White Plays 6.f4"]
[Black "White Plays 6.f4 -  6...Be7 7.Nf3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. f4
{ Usually, after 6.f4 White aims to establish a so-called 3rd rank set-up with Be3, Bd3, Qf3 and then either O-O or O-O-O. }
6... Be7
{ An important move! Usually Black plays Nc6, but against the line with 6.f4 it is important to castle as soon as possible. In the line  6...Nc6  7.Be3  Be7  8.Qf3  e5  9.Nxc6  bxc6  10.f5  White seems to have the upper hand even though the lines are quite complicated. }
7. Nb3
{ Another knight retreat, aiming for the third rank set-up but avoiding the attack on the centralised knight with e5. }
7... Nc6 { The usual developing move for Black. } 8. Be3
{ White can also start with Bd3, but eventually he wants to play all three moves: Bd3, Be3 and Qf3. The good aspect for Black is that against any combination of these moves his reaction is the same: push a5! }
8... O-O { Black finishes development. } 9. Bd3 a5
{ An important disruptive move, targeting the knight on b3. The hapless knight escaped the d4-square to avoid being attacked by e5, but now it's harassed by the a-pawn! }
10. O-O
{ White doesn't have time for  10.Qf3?!  a4!  11.Nd2  d5  12.e5  Nd7  with the idea of Nc5 with great play. In case of @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1p2bppp/2nppn2/p7/4PP2/1NNBB3/PPP3PP/R2QK2R w KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.a4  e5  @@StartBracket@@threatening Ng4@@EndBracket@@  11.f5  Nb4  Black wants to push d5 next. }
10... a4 { Following the plan. } 11. Nd4 a3
{ Forcing weaknesses on White's queenside. } 12. Nxc6
{ With this exchange White prevents the knight from comfortably slotting on b4. For example after  12.b3  Nb4  followed by Qa5, Bd7 and Rc8 gives Black excellent play on the queenside.   12.bxa3  obviously only weakens White's queenside with Black having strong counterplay on the a-file. }
12... bxc6 13. b3 e5
{ The typical central push, threatening Ng4. Black has several good alternatives, for example a safe one is  13...Ba6  exchanging the light-squared bishops and ensuring against any kingside problems after e5. }
14. h3 exf4 { Liberating the e5-square for the knight. } 15. Bxf4 Nd7
{ Black has a very comfortable position. The knight will come to e5 and the bishop can follow to f6 or g5, as it is in Black's favour to exchange the dark-squared bishops in view of the weak dark squares White will have in that case: with all his pawns on light squares there will be no pieces to control the dark squares. }
