[White "7. White Plays 6.f4"]
[Black "White Plays 6.f4 - 6...Be7 7.Be3 O-O 8.Bd3 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. f4
{ Usually, after 6.f4 White aims to establish a so-called 3rd rank set-up with Be3, Bd3, Qf3 and then either O-O or O-O-O. }
6... Be7
{ An important move! Usually Black plays Nc6, but against the line with 6.f4 it is important to castle as soon as possible. In the line  6...Nc6  7.Be3  Be7  8.Qf3  e5  9.Nxc6  bxc6  10.f5  White seems to have the upper hand even though the lines are quite complicated. }
7. Be3 { The most natural development, aiming for Qf3 and Bd3. } 7... O-O
{ Completing the development of the kingside. Now Black is ready for play in the centre. }
8. Bd3 { This is an alternative, but Black is quick with his central play. }
8... Nc6 { The knight controls a lot of central squares. } 9. Qf3
{ In case of  9.Nb3  a5  we have a transposition to theline that starts with 7.Nb3. After @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2bppp/2nppn2/8/3NPP2/2NBB3/PPP3PP/R2QK2R w KQ - 5 9@@EndFEN@@  9.O-O  e5  Black threatens Ng4 and exf4, for example  10.Nf3  Ng4  11.Bd2  exf4  12.Bxf4  Be6  with great play along the dark squares. }
9... e5
{ Just before White castles Black attacks the centre. Now White has a choice how to deal with the central attack. }
10. Nde2 exf4 { The e5-square is the ideal one for a knight. } 11. Nxf4 Ng4
{ Black goes after White's important dark-squared bishop. } 12. Bd2
{ Giving away the bishop with  12.O-O-O  is positionally in Black's favour, who will have the bishop pair and control over the dark squares in the absence of White's dark-squared bishop. To illustrate,  12...Nce5  13.Qe2  Nxe3  14.Qxe3  Ng4  with Bf6 next. }
12... Nge5
{ Since the dark-squared bishop cannot be captured, Black will now obtain the bishop pair by taking the light-squared bishop. }
13. Qf2 Bh4
{ Provoking g3 before placing the bishop on the long diagonal. Since Black will capture the light-squared bishop he first forces one more pawn to a dark square, thus weakening the light squares, in this case the f3-square. }
14. g3 Bf6 { The bishop is best on the long diagonal. } 15. O-O-O Nxd3+
{ The knight on e5 liberates the square for its comrade on c6. } 16. Nxd3 Bg4
{ Activating the light-squared bishop with tempo. } 17. Rde1 Bd4
{ Black keeps harassing White's pieces. } 18. Qg2 Ne5
{ Here we see the importance of the weakening of the f3-square that Black provoked with his 13th move. Black threatens Nf3 to take White's other bishop as well. He also wants to take on d3, to open the c-file and weaken White's king. Black has a pleasant advantage in this position. }
