{ Black takes over the initiative as White's king is stuck in the centre. } 11.
fxe5 Nxe4 { Moving away with tempo. } 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Be2 Bxe2
{ Not wasting time, Black exchanges the bishops and develops the knight next. }
14. Qxe2 Nc6 { Attacking the pawn on e5. } 15. Bf4 f5
{ This is simpler than  15...a5!?  when Black does have compensation after  16.Qxe4  a4  17.Nd2  a3  . }
16. exf6 Bxf6 { Threatening both Bxb2 and Bh4+. } 17. Rd1 Qe8 18. O-O
{ Getting away from the centre in view of the threat Bh4+. } 18... Bxb2 19. c3
Ba3 { Of course, taking the pawn loses the bishop to  19...Bxc3??  20.Qc4  . }
20. Qc4+ Kh8
{ Black is at least equal here. He is a pawn up and even if White manages to capture the pawn on e4 Black will still have the better pawn structure. }
