9. Nf5 { The only ambitious move. } 9... Bxf5
{ The knight is too strong on f5, so Black takes it immediately. } 10. exf5
Nbd7
{ Black finishes development and plans to play Rc8, threatening the typical exchange sacrifice on c3. }
11. Bc4
{ This is a natural development of the bishop, but it gives Black a tempo for the development of the rook. }
11... Rc8 { Immediately hitting the bishop. } 12. Bb3 d5
{ A typical pawn sacrifice for Black in this line. Black also has another interesting idea at his disposal,  12...b5!?  , with the plan of b4. Black has great play here as well, for example  13.O-O  @@StartBracket@@castling long only invites the exchange sacrifice on c3@@EndBracket@@  13...b4  @@StartBracket@@or even @@StartFEN@@2rq1rk1/p2nbppp/3p1n2/1p2pP2/5P2/1BN1BQ2/PPP3PP/R4RK1 b - - 1 13@@EndFEN@@  13...a5  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@2rq1rk1/p2nbppp/3p1n2/4pP2/1p3P2/1BN1BQ2/PPP3PP/R4RK1 w - - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14.Nd5  Nxd5  15.Qxd5  Nc5  when Black makes sure he eliminates one of White's bishops. }
13. Nxd5
{ Taking on e5 is bad for White, after  13.fxe5?  Nxe5  14.Qe2  Re8  White has big problems on the e-file. }
13... Nxd5 14. Qxd5 Bc5
{ An improvement over the game Ivanchuk-Nisipeanu played in Bazna 2009, where Black played the inferior  14...exf4  15.Bxf4  , though even here after the improvement  15...Bg5!  with the idea of Re8 Black is fine. }
15. Bxc5 Nxc5 { Threatening Qa5 and Nb3. } 16. Qxd8
{ Immediately exchanging queens. After  16.O-O-O  exf4  Black is at least equal, while @@StartFEN@@2rq1rk1/pp3ppp/8/2nQpP2/5P2/1B6/PPP3PP/R3K2R w KQ - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16.fxe5?  is bad in view of  16...Qa5  17.c3  Rcd8  with Nxb3 next, winning a piece. }
16... Rfxd8
{ Black still has threats: he can take on f4 or on b3 followed by Rc2. } 17.
Rd1
{ This is safe for White. Taking the pawn on e5 is risky:  17.fxe5  Nxb3  18.cxb3  Rc2  and Black will harvest White's pawns on the second rank. }
17... exf4 { Establishing material parity. } 18. O-O Nxb3
{ Now Black eliminates the important bishop that defended the c2-pawn. } 19.
axb3 g5
{ Not only defending the pawn on f4 but also opening a luft for the king. Now Black threatens to take the pawn on c2 after the exchange of the rooks on the d-file. The endgame is equal. }
