1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. f4
{ Usually, after 6.f4 White aims to establish a so-called 3rd rank set-up with Be3, Bd3, Qf3 and then either O-O or O-O-O. }
6... Be7
{ An important move! Usually Black plays Nc6, but against the line with 6.f4 it is important to castle as soon as possible. In the line  6...Nc6  7.Be3  Be7  8.Qf3  e5  9.Nxc6  bxc6  10.f5  White seems to have the upper hand even though the lines are quite complicated. }
7. Be3 { The most natural development, aiming for Qf3 and Bd3. } 7... O-O
{ Completing the development of the kingside. Now Black is ready for play in the centre. }
8. Qf3 { Preparing for long castling. } 8... e5
{ Just before White castles, Black strikes in the centre, otherwise the rook on d1 would have made the opening of the centre more difficult. }
9. Nf5 { The only ambitious move. } 9... Bxf5
{ The knight is too strong on f5, so Black takes it immediately. } 10. exf5
Nbd7
{ Black finishes development and plans to play Rc8, threatening the typical exchange sacrifice on c3. }
11. O-O-O
{ Taking on b7 is bad,  11.Qxb7?  Rb8  followed by Rxb2 is almost winning for Black as White's king is stuck in the centre and White is also lagging in development. }
11... Rc8
{ Black threatens to take on c3. White has many options at his disposal now. }
12. Bd2
{ Preventing the sacrifice on c3. Except for  12.Qxb7  all the moves that allow the sacrifice are dubious. }
12... Qc7
{ Black continues the development and pins the knight on c3 in view of the mate on c2. He intends to continue with d5 next. }
13. Bd3 { Defending c2, so now the knight can move. } 13... d5
{ Black doesn't mind the sacrifice as it opens the files that he can use to put pressure on White's position. }
14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Qxd5 Nc5
{ Black has a threatening position. Apart from the simple capture on f4 he intends Rfd8 and Nxd3, which is possible thanks to the pin on the c-file. }
16. Kb1 Nxd3
{ The simplest. Black has also sharper options like  16...e4!?  17.Bxe4  Bf6  with good compensation thanks to the excellent position of all his pieces. Other good moves are @@StartFEN@@2r2rk1/ppq1bppp/8/2nQpP2/5P2/3B4/PPPB2PP/1K1R3R b - - 2 16@@EndFEN@@  16...Bf6  and  16...exf4  . }
17. Qxd3 Rfd8 { Gaining a tempo before regaining the pawn. } 18. Qc3 Qxc3 19.
Bxc3 exf4
{ The endgame is equal, though Black can try to take advantage of the somewhat exposed position of the pawn on f5. }
