[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Various 6th Moves"]
[Black "Various 6th Moves - 6.Bb5+"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. Bb5+
{ In this chapter we will take a look at some rare moves White can try. This check comes with the idea of quick development, but Black has no problems. Note that a move like  6.f3  will likely transpose to the chapter on theEnglish Attack after  6...Be7  7.Be3  , while a move like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/3ppn2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.h3  will likely transpose to theKeres Attack after  6...Nc6  7.g4  h6  . }
6... Bd7
{ Immediately challenging the bishop. In case White captures on with  7.Bxd7+  Black will speed up his queenside development by taking with  7...Nbxd7  . }
7. Qe2
{ White continues with the development. Completely harmless is  7.Bxd7  Nbxd7  with Be7 and O-O next as is  @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pp1b1ppp/3ppn2/1B6/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.O-O  Bxb5  8.Ndxb5  a6  9.Nd4  Be7  with O-O next. }
7... a6
{ Forcing the bishop to either retreat, thus admitting the loss of tempo, or to take on d7 and help Black develop the knight from b8. }
8. Bxd7+
{ In case of  8.Bd3  Nc6  9.Be3  Be7  Black is ready to do several things, depending on White's plan: play Nxd4 followed by e5, b5, Be6 and so on; castle; play b5 immediately, or play Qc7 or Rc8 first followed by b5. }
8... Nbxd7
{ Black finished the development of his queenside and now the kingside will follow. }
9. Bg5 Be7 10. O-O-O Rc8
{ An important move and one that is typical for Black in the Sicilian. The threat of a positional exchange sacrifice on c3 is a serious one.   In the game Vitolinsh-Timoshchenko from the Soviet Team Championship in 1981 Black played  10...O-O  first and then after  11.f4  Rc8  12.Kb1  had another chance to take on c3,  12...Rxc3!  followed by d5, which would have given him a considerable advantage. For some reason, he didn't sacrifice and eventually lost the game.  After 10...Rc8, which doesn't spend time on castling, White is faced with the choice of either allowing the sacrifice, which would weaken his queenside and give Black long-term compensation, or to prevent it by spending a move on it, which allows Black to start his queenside play with b5. In both cases, Black has an advantage. }
