[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Various 6th Moves"]
[Black "Various 6th Moves - 6.Bd3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. Bd3
{ A simple developing move. White intends the third-rank set-up with f4, Qf3 etc. }
6... Nc6
{ Immediately challenging the knight on d4, now without the support from the queen on d1. }
7. Be3
{ In case of  7.Nb3  Be7  8.Be3  O-O  9.f4  a5!  we have a transposition to the chapterWhite Plays 6.f4. }
7... Be7 { Black continues with his kingside development. } 8. O-O O-O 9. Nb3
{ An independent try, as playing  9.f4  is a transposition to a line in the chapterWhite Plays 6.f4. }
9... Ne5
{ A move that aims to take advantage of the fact that White hasn't played f4 and taken control over the e5-square. Naturally, with White's timid set-up Black has more than one satisfactory way,  9...a6  ,  9...b6  ,  9...Nb4  all being good alternatives. }
10. Be2 { Trying to preserve both bishops. } 10... Qc7 { Intending Nc4. } 11.
f4
{ Unless he plays the English Attack, White can rarely do without this move in the Open Sicilian. Note that attacking the queen with  11.Nb5?!  achieves nothing, as after  11...Qc6  the pawn  on e4 hangs and the knight is useless on b5. }
11... Nc4 12. Bxc4 Qxc4
{ Black is comfortably equal here. He obtained the pair of bishops early in the game and has long-term prospects in his favour. Now he will likely drop the queen back to c7, develop with Bd7 and start the usual advance in the queenside with b5. }
