[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Various 6th Moves"]
[Black "Various 6th Moves - 6.Bg5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. Bg5
{ The move  6.Bg5  is the most common of White's rare 6th moves, popular with players who play the same move against the Najdorf. }
6... h6
{ Black wants to clarify what the bishop intends to do. The move  6...a6  is a transposition to the Najdorf and the move  6...Nc6  is a transposition to the Rauzer Attack in the Classical Sicilian. }
7. Bh4
{ The retreat  7.Be3  makes little sense, as White gives Black a clear tempo @@StartBracket@@h6@@EndBracket@@ in the English Attack. Even more so, this tempo is useful for Black as it stops g5 in many lines. Black can play along the same lines as in the chapter The English Attack with  7...Be7  followed by Nc6, O-O and d5 and will be fine.   The exchange on f6 is also not very threatening, after  7.Bxf6  Qxf6  Black has the bishop pair very early in the game. He will retreat the queen back to d8 in order to remove it from possible attacks with g4-g5 and will continue with Be7, a6, b5, Bb7 etc. }
7... Nc6
{ The more complex move. The alternative  7...Be7  is just as good, with the idea to continue with a6 and b5 in Najdorf-style. }
8. Qd3 { With the idea to castle long. } 8... Be7
{ Black continues in Scheveningen style, aiming to meet White's f4 with e5. }
9. O-O-O O-O 10. f4 e5 { The typical Modern Scheveningen reaction. } 11. Nxc6
{ The other moves are easier to deal with,  11.fxe5  Nxe5  is comfortable, while @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2bpp1/2np1n1p/4p3/3NPP1B/2NQ4/PPP3PP/2KR1B1R w - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Nf5?!  Bxf5  12.exf5  exf4  with Qa5 and d5 to come gives Black initiative on the queenside. }
11... bxc6 12. f5
{ The endgame after  12.fxe5  dxe5  13.Qxd8  Rxd8  14.Rxd8  Bxd8  15.Bc4  Kf8  is quite alright for Black, the weaknesses of the pawns on c6 and e4 compensate each other. }
12... d5 { A very promising pawn sacrifice. } 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. exd5 Qb6
{ The key move, introducing threats on the long diagonal and the b-file, both converging on the b2-square. }
15. b3 Rd8 { Activating the rook on the d-file. } 16. d6 Qa5
{ Black is targeting the weakened dark squares around White's king. } 17. Ne4
{ White must prevent e4. } 17... Qxa2
{ The position is unclear, but Black has good chances. His main positional idea is a5-a4, while the capture on f6 is good for Black in view of: }
18. Nxf6+ gxf6 { With the threat of Qa3 and Rxd6. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Various 6th Moves"]
[Black "Various 6th Moves - 6.Bg5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Scheveningen also allows a different move-order, i.e.  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  . In order to keep it practical, I chose the move order with 2...d6 so that it is compatible with my Anti-Sicilians course. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen set-up that Black achieves with this move is a very flexible one. Black establishes a so-called 'small centre' @@StartBracket@@with the pawns on e6 and d6@@EndBracket@@ and is ready to finish the development of the kingside with Be7 and O-O.In contrast to the Najdorf @@StartBracket@@5...a6@@EndBracket@@, in the Modern Scheveningen Black plays in the centre and hopes to make do without the move a6, thus saving a tempo for faster central activity. One of Black's main ideas is to play Nc6 and then play in the centre by pushing either e5 or d5. }
6. Bg5
{ The move  6.Bg5  is the most common of White's rare 6th moves, popular with players who play the same move against the Najdorf. }
6... h6
{ Black wants to clarify what the bishop intends to do. The move  6...a6  is a transposition to the Najdorf and the move  6...Nc6  is a transposition to the Rauzer Attack in the Classical Sicilian. }
7. Bh4
{ The retreat  7.Be3  makes little sense, as White gives Black a clear tempo @@StartBracket@@h6@@EndBracket@@ in the English Attack. Even more so, this tempo is useful for Black as it stops g5 in many lines. Black can play along the same lines as in the chapter The English Attack with  7...Be7  followed by Nc6, O-O and d5 and will be fine.   The exchange on f6 is also not very threatening, after  7.Bxf6  Qxf6  Black has the bishop pair very early in the game. He will retreat the queen back to d8 in order to remove it from possible attacks with g4-g5 and will continue with Be7, a6, b5, Bb7 etc. }
7... Nc6
{ The more complex move. The alternative  7...Be7  is just as good, with the idea to continue with a6 and b5 in Najdorf-style. }
8. Bb5
{ Note that the natural  8.Qd2?  is a mistake in view of  8...Nxe4!  winning a pawn. }
8... Qb6 { Putting pressure on White's somewhat exposed light pieces. } 9. Bxf6
gxf6 10. O-O Bd7 { Now the knight on d4 hangs. } 11. Nce2
{ With the idea of c4. After  11.Bxc6  bxc6  Black has good prospects with the powerful central pawn mass and the pair of bishops. }
11... Rd8
{ Making sure to be able to capture on d7 with a rook. An alternative is  11...a6  12.Ba4  O-O-O  which leads to unclear play. }
12. c4 Bg7
{ The bishop on the long diagonal can easily be activated with a timely f5. A good alternative is the simplifying  12...Nxd4  13.Bxd7  Rxd7  14.Nxd4  Bg7  followed by O-O when Black wants to double on the c-file. }
13. Bxc6 bxc6
{ Black has a strong central pawn mass and the power of bishops. He will use the pawns to push the knights back. }
14. Rc1 c5
{ The centralised knight is pushed back and the light-squared bishop will find a good spot on c6. }
15. Nb3 h5
{ An important move, introducing the idea of h4-h3 and allowing the activation of the dark-squared bishop with Bh6. There is a complex middlegame that lies ahead, but Black has the better prospects looking long-term. His plan is to push the pawn to h3 if allowed, play Bc6, Bh6 and look for ways to open the game. A curious idea can be the rook maneuver Rh5-g5 to exert pressure on the g-file. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
