[White "9. Strategy and Tactics"]
[Black "Simplifying Sequence #1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqk2r/pp2bpp1/2nppn1p/8/3NP1P1/2N1B3/PPP1QP1P/R3KBR1 b Qkq - 0 9"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ With his last move @@StartBracket@@9.Qe2@@EndBracket@@, White prepared to castle long. Now Black executes a simplifying sequence of moves that allow him to finish development and take control over the dark squares in the centre. Which one? }
9... Nxd4 10. Bxd4 e5
{ Black lured the bishop to d4 so that he can win a tempo with this move, which also controls the dark squares d4 and f4. }
11. Be3 Be6
{ Comfortably finishing development. The bishop controls the d5-square and eyes the pawn on a2. As a consequence of its development, the rook on a8 obtained access to the c8-square, from where it will threaten the typical Sicilian exchange sacrifice on c3. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Strategy and Tactics"]
[Black "Simplifying Sequence #2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/pp1bbppp/2nppn2/8/P2NP3/2N3P1/1PP2PBP/R1BQR1K1 b - - 0 10"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Black has a compact position but his pieces need space. With his next two moves, Black solves the problem. How? }
10... Nxd4
{ Black simplifies the position and, with the removal of his own knight from c6, he liberates that square for his light-squared bishop. }
11. Qxd4 Bc6
{ Now Black doesn't suffer anymore due to lack of space, because all his pieces are comfortably placed. }
